<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NancyReagan-Astrology     08-15 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy Reagan-Astrology,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady: Trauma of Shooting Led to Astrologer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Lady Nancy Reagan said Monday she
consulted an astrologer on President Reagan's travel schedule
because she was ``obsessed with his safety'' after he was shot in
March 1981.
   It was ``a terrible trauma'' when her husband was shot, ``and
you're in shock much longer than you know you're in shock,'' Mrs.
Reagan said in a CBS News interview. ``And you reach out anywhere
for, for comfort.''
   Mrs. Reagan was first reported to have consulted an astrologer
on her husband's schedule in a book by former White House Chief of
Staff Donald Regan. The White House later confirmed it.
   Interviewed during CBS' coverage of the Republican National
Convention, Mrs. Reagan told anchorman Dan Rather that some months
after the attack on her husband she heard about a woman who had
said she would have warned against his public appearance that day.
   ``And I said, `Oh, gee, did she really?' And I was so obsessed
with his safety, that anytime he went out of the house, I think my
heart stopped,'' Mrs. Reagan said. ``So all I would do would, would
be to ask her, `Is, is this a, would he be all right? Is it better
for him to go to Chicago on Wednesday or Tuesday?'''
</TEXT>
