<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MiracleService 2ndLd-Writethru a0823 08-15 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miracle Service, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0823,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Gather at Church Where Four Claim to Hear Messages from
Mary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 8-9 bgng `To some' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
quotes from priest, add explanation. Subs 15th graf pvs `The
reported' to CORRECT that only two in Yugoslavia claim to still see
apparitions. Subs final graf to restore first reference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worshipers screamed and lifted their hands
toward the sky as a ray of light burst through the clouds Monday
evening during an outdoor Mass where thousands came expecting a
miracle.
   Shortly after the 6 p.m. Mass began at St. John Neumann Catholic
Church, throngs of pilgrims stood and applauded as many spectators
pointed skyward, crying that they saw Jesus and the Virgin Mary and
calling it a miracle.
   ``I saw the sun pulsating a lot and saw Jesus about 10 times,''
said Mamie Fertitta. ``Then I saw Jesus above and the doves below.''
   A dozen priests standing on a rooftop altar and 600 Eucharist
ministers turned their backs to the crowd to look at the sky and
wave. After minutes of silence, St. John Neumann pastor Monsignor
Joseph James began to sing ``Amazing Grace.''
   People in the audience whipped out cameras to photograph the
clouds and light.
   ``I saw baby Jesus for an instant in the sky,'' said Koreth
Vargahese of Houston.
   The Texas National Guard estimated the crowd for the service at
about 12,000 people.
   To some in the crowd the shape they saw in the sky was the
miracle they had been hoping for. Their shouts alerted others. Some
then reported seeing the same apparation and others did not.
   ``I'm positive other people saw things and they took
photographs,'' said Father Albert Meyer, a Benedictine monk from
Pecos, New Mexico.
   ``I didn't see anything, but some of the other priests on the
altar did,'' Joe Richard, a deacon of the Lubbock parish.
   Monday was the Catholic feast of the ascension of the Virgin
Mary into heaven. The crowds were drawn to the charismatic parish
in West Texas by national attention given to three parishioners'
reports that they received messages from the Virgin Mary this
spring, including tidings of miracles on the feast day.
   Earlier Monday, parish members and priests laid hands on the
pilgrims and said prayers for the scores of handicapped people
present.
   Hundreds of people in wheelchairs and walkers settled on the
grassy hillside beneath a 60-foot-long altar built atop the church
office.
   ``I heard that Mary's crown was spinning on the statue inside
the church last night, so I believe anything can happen,'' said
Marilyn Oliver as she stepped off a bus with 43 other Catholics
from East Texas.
   Parish officials did not confirm the rumor about the crown.
   James said he did not know whether attendance would reach the
20,000 people he said Mary told him would come. ``It doesn't matter
how many are here. Some beautiful spirtual things are going on.''
   The reported messages at the church came after James and several
parishioners returned from Medugorje, Yugoslavia, where six youths
claimed they began seeing apparitions of Mary in 1981 and two say
they still see them daily.
   One group skeptical of the reports said the trip and the
beginning of the messages was too coincidental to be believable.
   ``While we are certainly open to any verifiable paranormal
events, so far the only amazing thing that has happened here is the
fact that thousands of people would flock here from all over,
against common sense, on the unverified claims of one man,'' said
Harvey Madison, spokesman for West Texans to Promote Rational
Thought, a group that investigates claims of paranormal behavior.
   The three parishioners say Mary and God speak to them during
Monday night recitations of the rosary. The trio write the
``messages'' in notebooks and read them aloud after the service.
   ``I feel her love, her joy, her sorrow and that's what I write
down,'' said one of the three, Mary Constancion, a former hospital
therapist who quit her job to devote more time to prayer and church
work.
</TEXT>
