<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LAMayoralRace     08-15 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LA Mayoral Race,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaked Memos Derail Councilman's Challenge To Mayor Bradley</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaked campaign strategy memos laced with
coarse remarks threaten to ignite racial tensions in the early
stages of a mayoral campaign that pits a Jewish city councilman
against black incumbent Tom Bradley.
   The memos were prepared by a consulting firm associated with
39-year-old City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, who is seeking to
become the city's first Jewish mayor and poses by many accounts the
first real challenge to Bradley in a decade. Both are Democrats;
the race is nonpartisan.
   The documents by veteran strategists Michael Berman and Carl
D'Agostino, whose firm is known as BAD Campaigns, berate
Yaroslavsky about his grim demeanor, mock Bradley's intelligence,
refer to environmentalists as ``tree huggers'' and slow-growth
advocates as ``crazed homeowners.''
   The strategists urge Yaroslavsky, who represents a chunk of the
city's largely affluent and liberal west side, to skip City Council
meetings and focus his energies on fund-raising efforts among
Jewish contributors.
   ``What we do know is that Jewish wealth in Los Angeles is
endless,'' said one of the memos, which were leaked anonymously.
   Elsewhere, the advisers wrote: ``The reason why BAD thinks you
can beat Bradley is: You've got 50 IQ points on him (and that's no
compliment).''
   Berman and D'Agostino, after the memos' release last week,
announced their ``regrets that our private, irreverent attempts at
humor might have caused embarrassment or offense.''
   Yaroslavsky quickly divorced himself from the consultants,
saying, ``I do not agree with many of their ideas and I find many
of their statements to be insulting, insensitive and not reflective
of my views.''
   Mark Ridley-Thomas, executive director of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference of Greater Los Angeles, said the memos'
contents ``come perilously close to being blatant racist remarks.''
   ``At the absolute minimum they're highly insensitive,'' he said.
   He said the memos threaten to inflame black resentment over a
perceived lack of Jewish support during Bradley's failed 1986
campaign for governor, and over tensions that emerged between Jews
and blacks during Jesse Jackson's Democratic presidential bid
earlier this year.
   The mayor, who at age 70 is seeking an unprecedented fifth term
as mayor of the nation's second-largest city, denounced the memos
as unprincipled and potentially racially divisive.
   ``Talking about the relative intelligence of candidates is of no
consequence,'' Bradley said. ``I think I've demonstrated over the
years my intelligence and my ability to handle the public's
problems.''
   Bradley has become politically vulnerable because of his
protracted tenure of 16 years and position on environmental issues.
He has switched from opposition to approval of a proposed onshore
drilling project near Pacific Palisades, an exclusive canyon
enclave overlooking the Pacific.
   Despite its name, BAD Campaigns is a highly regarded firm.
``D'Agostino and Berman are extremely well-respected as very
capable and talented and winning consultants,'' said former
Republican U.S. Rep. Bobbi Fiedler.
   Berman said Bradley found his advice amusing when Berman
submitted similar pointed comments during Bradley's unsuccessful
1969 mayoral campaign and in 1973, when he was elected the first
black mayor of a major U.S. city.
   ``When it's excerpted, it becomes a bit embarrassing,'' Berman
said of the memos. ``We don't mean to offend anybody. We had no
intention of offending the mayor on the IQ.''
   Fiedler, summing up the controversy, said, ``I think what's
happened is that the voters have been given a glimpse into what
politics is really like.''
   Political consultants in general ``tend to see themselves as the
movers and shakers and the candidate as the vehicle,'' she said.
``So they often will seem somewhat arrogant and paternal to this
woeful candidate.''
</TEXT>
