<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Parties 2ndLd-Writethru a0784 08-15 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Parties, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0784,630</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Elephant Romp, editing to trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Delegates Let Good Times Roll in Party City of New Orleans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans paid $100 a piece for Sunday
night snacks with a zoo elephant as their rollicking pre-convention
weekend wound down.
   The Very Important Pachyderm at the ``Elephant Romp Welcome'' at
Audubon Zoo was Ellie Mae, who drew adoring attention from the herd
of 3,600 partiers. ``It's a wonderful elephant, obviously
Republican,'' said Joan Milke Flores, a California delegate and Los
Angeles city councilwoman.
   Ellie Mae's handler, James Holston, said the 1,200-pound
elephant was named the convention's official mascot, and had a full
schedule of national television appearances for the entire week.
   New Orleans city councilman Mike Early, who took credit for the
zoo party idea, said the goal was to stuff a 3-week New Orleans
experience into three hours.
   ``A philosophy of this party, I think, would be that in New
Orleans, we believe that throwing a party, hosting a party, really
is an art. It really is a science,'' said Early, a Democrat.
   New Orleans chef Paul Prudhomme stirred chicken etoufee under
one of four air-conditioned zoo tents, and Pat O'Brien's, which
claims to dispense more alcohol than any bar in the world, prepared
2,000 potent Hurricanes in 15-ounce paper cups. ``This is the
official drink, and we want the GOP to try it,'' said O'Brien's
spokesman Lou Reynolds.
   Sunday was filled with dancing and Dixieland from the French
Quarter to private homes in the fashionable Garden District.
   Jazz musicians had plenty of work. At the Sheraton Hotel, a
three-piece group entertained incoming guests, while another combo
imparted Dixieland flavor to a congressional brunch.
   Across the street at the Marriott, Alaska sponsored a
$20,000-plus feast featuring 1,000 pounds of seafood flown in for
the occasion, and exotic treats like moose and reindeer sausage.
   Seafood flown into a city known for its seafood?
   ``That's your kind of seafood, not necessarily our kind,'' said
Jim Crawford, the Alaska GOP chairman. ``But I don't think there's
a better party town in the United States than New Orleans.''
   Some delegates got a head start on the festivities Saturday
night with a rollicking river boat race, Mardi Gras-style parade
and samplings of turtle soup au sherry.
   At the New Orleans' Convention Center, delegates tasted the
city's finest cooking and danced behind a fast-marching city high
school band and miniature Mardi Gras floats. The floats carried
costumed party-goers who pitched plastic beads and doubloons
touting the carnival's sponsor, The Times-Picayune newspaper.
   Al Bullock, an alternate delegate from Maryland who has attended
three conventions, scoffed at decorum and danced in the parade.
``This is the greatest party ever,'' said Bullock, swaying in a
navy blazer and purple beads.
   White-uniformed servers from Commander's Palace ladled 138
gallons of turtle soup au sherry into white styrofoam bowls. At the
105-year-old restaurant, an appetizer portion runs $4.50. On a
night of freebies, there were very few leftovers.
   ``The food's a big hit, and so's the parade,'' said Mark Moses,
a Copeland's supervisor. ``One nice thing about New Orleans. It
opens you up and brings you back to a childhood state. Folks start
out saying about the dancing that it's really stupid. But five
minutes later, they are out there chasing the band.''
   Jefferson Parish Sheriff Harry Lee, a Democrat, watched the
Republicans eat, drink and dance, then said with laughter, ``We'll
party with them now, and then we'll slug it out this November.''
</TEXT>
