<DOCNO> AP880815-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     08-15 0975</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,1014</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Athol Fugard, who's appearing in the
off-Broadway production of his play, ``The Road to Mecca,'' is
heading down a new road _ an appearance on the soap opera ``One
Life to Live.''
   The South African playwright is to appear in the ABC-TV soap
Aug. 23 to Sept. 1. He'll portray a ``crusty old ex-sea captain''
who uses a wheelchair and lives in an abandoned lighthouse with his
``slightly strange, psychotic daughter,'' producer Paul Rauch told
The New York Times.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following item is moving on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A championship tennis match
between Chris Evert and Gabriela Sabatini was marred when someone
threw a glass container of yellow paint onto the court.
   The container shattered about 15 feet from Sabatini, who was
down double match point at 15-40 at Sunday's $300,000 Virginia
Slims contest.
   After a 15-minute delay to clean the court, Sabatini won the
next two points to go to deuce. Sabatini hit a running forehand
into the net, then Evert won the match when the 18-year-old from
Argentina netted a backhand.
   Evert won $60,000 and Sabatini $24,000.
   ``I was scared,'' Sabatini said. ``I think maybe there's crazy
people out there. It was difficult to go out again and play and I
was down two match points.''
   ``This was shocking,'' said Evert. ``I didn't even know what it
was. I was more worried that if they didn't get it up it would get
sticky and the match would be postponed. I just wanted to get it
over with.''
   Tournament promoter Jerry Diamond said police were investigating.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having theater stars like Jessica Tandy and
Hume Cronyn as parents wasn't exactly an open invitation to success
on the stage, daughter Tandy Cronyn says.
   ``The first important reviewer to appraise my work gave me a bad
notice,'' Ms. Cronyn said in in intwerview published Sunday in The
Star-Ledger of Newark.
   ``The part had only six lines and I was one of a group, but this
eminent critic of a leading magazine took the trouble to single me
out for a slam. He never would have noticed me except for my name.
And I didn't choose it either.''
   Ms. Cronyn has advanced beyond that role to play a Jewish girl
in Poland who has survived a concentration camp in an off-Broadway
production of ``A Shayna Maidel'' (A Pretty Girl).
   ``I thought, `How can a WASP like me succeed as that Polish
girl?''' Ms. Tandy said. ``But then I was so taken with the play, I
started acting it in my mind and said, `Why not.'''
</TEXT>
