<TEXT>
   Mayor Sonny Bono is trying to drum
up more business for his city.
   The pop singer-restaurateur arrived in Toronto on Sunday in an
attempt to sell the benefits of the desert city at a convention of
trade associations.
   Bono's first big publicity trip was to New York last month,
where he met with Mayor Edward I. Koch, appeared on television and
radio shows and attended another convention.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Huey Lewis says endorsements of
beer of soft drinks are not for him and The News.
   ``No, we're not going to do anything like that in the future,''
the 38-year-old singer said. ``I'm from the '60s when it used to be
`us' against `them.' ...
   ``If someone does it and donates the money to a worthy cause, I
think that's OK. But I think when you're doing very well and you
don't need the money and you endorse a product that you're not
really into ... as far as the artist, I lose them.''
   Huey Lewis and The News, who sold a combined 15 million albums
with their last two hit LPs ``Sports'' and ``Fore!,'' are on a
world tour to support their new album ``Small World.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gene Simmons' life and work are based on rock
and shock.
   Fifteen years ago he started the heavy metal group KISS, which
became known as much for its wild makeup and antics as its music.
   Now, he's managing Liza Minnelli's recording career and has
started his own record label.
   ``My life is based on shock. I find the idea so interesting,''
Simmons said recently. ``All of that has a lot in common with my
working with Liza Minnelli. Great work should shock you.''
   Simmons recently took on the role of manager for Miss Minnelli,
whose album on Epic is due out this year.
   KISS, which has released 23 albums, is beginning the European
version of the ``Monsters of Rock'' tour. Simmons said KISS will be
joining such rock heavies as David Lee Roth, Guns and Roses and
Halloween.
   Simmons turned down a role in the new James Bond film, ``License
Revoked,'' with Timothy Dalton, to go on the tour.
   At the same time, the 36-year-old entertainer is busy working
with his newly formed record label, Simmons Records, which is
distributed by MCA. He said he founded the company because he has a
good ear for picking new acts and got tired of others telling him
his discoveries couldn't cut it.
   ``I'll never listen to anyone else again,'' he said. ``Maybe I
know something they don't.''
   In September, House of Lords will become the first group to
release an album on the label.
   He is also expecting his first child with girlfriend Shannon
Tweed, a former Playmate of the Year. He said he feels ``numb''
about the whole thing.
   KISS will release a greatest hits album called ``Smashes
Thrashes and Hits,'' by next summer. The album will include two new
songs, ``Let's put the X in Sex'' and ``Rock Hard.''
   ``Rock 'n' roll should be sexy and fun _ with a strong
backbeat,'' he said.
</TEXT>
