<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Letterman,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Butter Sculpture To Melt On Letterman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman fans will watch a butter
sculpture of guest Jack Hanna melt, making more of a mess on the
set than most of the Columbus Zoo director's animal friends have
left.
   Hanna has taken many of his animals on NBC-TV's ``Late Night
With David Letterman,'' and they don't always display the best
manners.
   A crew from the Letterman show last weekend searched the Ohio
State Fair for acts, and selected the butter sculpture of Hanna
holding a lion cub. It will deteriorate over a one-week period on
the show, starting tonight.
   The statue was sculpted by Dan Ross of Columbus.
   Last year's statue of race car driver Bobby Rahal was displayed
intact on the Letterman show.
   Letterman producer Robert Morton said this probably is the last
year Lettterman's crew will search the fair, where butter
sculptures have been displayed since the early 1900s and usually
are broken up when the event ends.
