<DOCNO> AP880815-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--OutnumberedRepublicans     08-15 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Outnumbered Republicans,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Convene In An Overwhelmingly Democratic Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first glance, the Republicans appear to
have gathered in hostile political territory, but an overwhelming
Democratic registration edge masks growing Republican strength in
Louisiana.
   New Orleans Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, a Jesse Jackson Democrat
and a vice chairman of the national Democratic Party, leads a city
where registered Democrats outnumber registered Republicans 189,741
to 34,853.
   Statewide, there are 2,146,867 registered voters and only about
322,000 of them _ 15 percent _ are Republicans.
   In the Legislature, there are 23 Republicans among the 144
members.
   Republicans have been scarce in Louisiana since Reconstruction.
   Populist Democrats like Huey Long, who taxed oil companies to
provide free state services, further cemented the Democrats' hold
on the state. When blacks became a voting force as a result of the
civil rights movement, Democrats broadened their base, despite
occasional defections by white voters to states' rights candidates.
   But things are looking up for the Louisiana GOP. Republicans
have won five of the last eight presidential races in the state.
Half of Louisiana's eight U.S. House members are Republicans now.
   Ten years ago, Republican registration was just 79,900 and the
long-standing joke was that they could hold the state convention in
a telephone booth.
   Chinks in the Democrats' Louisiana fortress first were seen more
than 30 years ago, when the state went for Dwight D. Eisenhower in
the 1956 presidential race. In later years, Louisiana's electoral
votes went to Republicans Barry Goldwater in 1964, Richard Nixon in
1972 and Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   In 1972, Dave Treen, after three losing campaigns, became the
first Republican to win a congressional seat in Louisiana since
Reconstruction.
   Treen later became the first Republican governor since
Reconstruction when he was elected to the post in 1979. Ironically,
he was helped by a law the Democrats had pushed to help themselves
_ the unique ``open primary'' law.
   All candidates from all parties run in one election. If no
candidate wins a majority, the top two finishers, regardless of
party, face a runoff.
   The law was designed to keep Democrats from exhausting their
energies and campaign funds in volatile primary battles against
each other only to face a single, well-financed Republican in a
general election.
   But, since anyone could vote _ regardless of party registration
_ it allowed conservative Democrats to cross party lines and vote
for Republicans.
   
   In addition to GOP House gains, former Republican Rep. Henson
Moore forced Democrat John Breaux to wage a tough, come-from-behind
battle in 1986 to keep Democratic control of the Senate seat left
vacant by the retirement of Russell Long, a powerful Democrat and
son of Huey Long.
   All is not roses for the Republicans in Louisiana, even with the
open primary.
   For example, Democrats remain so strong that the planners for
the 1988 GOP convention yanked Democratic Mayor Barthelemy off the
schedule for their nationally televised opening night ceremonies so
his welcoming remarks would be made during a less conspicuous
morning session.
   After his 1986 loss to Breaux, Moore said he did not think a
Republican could beat a Democrat in a head-to-head match.
   That was three years after Treen was overwhelmingly defeated
when popular two-term governor Edwin Edwards, a Democrat, returned
to politics after a four-year hiatus.
   And, although Edwards' political fortunes fell with the price of
oil and the state's poor economy, it took another Democrat, Buddy
Roemer, to drive Edwards out of office in last year's election.
   Roemer came from the back of a five-man pack to beat Edwards and
Rep. Robert Livingston, the Republican who had been considered a
sure bet for a runoff with Edwards.
   Treen believes the Louisiana GOP's growing strength results in
part from the tenacity of Republicans like him who ran against
enormous odds in the 1950s and 1960s.
   ``If I had the wisdom of my present age, which is 60, when I ran
for Congress, I probably would not have run for Congress back in
1962,'' he said. But he does not regret it.
   ``That race led to the '64 race and the '68 race ... and
eventually to the race I won in 1972.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Governors-Dukakis     08-15 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Governors-Dukakis,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Governors Attack Dukakis' Command At State Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu is leading a
Republican National Convention assault on his neighbor, Michael
Dukakis, saying the Democratic nominee has displayed ``an absolute
incapacity to manage.''
   Sununu, a frequent critic of the Massachusetts governor,
conducted a spirited denunciation of the Dukakis record on the eve
of the GOP convention. And Sununu, who will speak to the convention
Tuesday night, added: ``I'm saving the good stuff.''
   ``It takes an absolute incapacity to manage to have reached the
fiscal chaos that Massachusetts has today,'' Sununu said at a news
conference Sunday following a meeting of Republican governors and
former governors.
   He was joined by a half-dozen other governors as he attacked
Dukakis' management of the Massachusetts budget in the face of a
severe deficit this year.
   He said Dukakis failed to take steps that other governors did to
head off a deficit when they saw indications of an economic
slowdown. To deal with the resulting shortage, Dukakis resorted to
borrowing from the retirement fund for state employee pensions, as
well as tax increases, Sununu said.
   ``The fact is that Michael Dukakis had no handle on his budget.
Michael Dukakis had no capacity to deal with a tough situation that
he created on his own,'' Sununu said. ``Michael Dukakis had no
management understanding, in a timely way, of what should have been
done, and what Michael Dukakis has done since then in order to deal
with next year's deficit is absolutely irresponsible.''
   He used the word ``steal'' to describe the state's borrowing
from its pension system and said the action ``ought to strike fear
in the hearts of anyone who draws a Social Security check.''
   At a brunch earlier, former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee
delivered a plea for the GOP not to forget that states need to take
action to deal with problems, even while the Republicans ``put a
harness on the government in Washington.''
   ``Somebody's got to fix the schools and save the outdoors and
fix the roads and clean the streets,'' he said. ``And you don't get
to be a governing conservative majority by voting `no' in
Washington alone. Most of the work that's done on schools and jobs
and the outdoors is done by governors.''
   Gov. Michael Castle of Delaware, chairman of the GOP governors,
urged a close examination of Dukakis' record during his three terms
as governor of Massachusetts, saying the state had merely benefited
from an economic boom throughout New England.
   ``There is some concern that the `Massachusetts Miracle,' which
has been presented by Michael Dukakis, may not be quite a
miracle,'' Castle said, referring to the Dukakis campaign slogan
for the state's economic health. ``... Perhaps it's a Massachusetts
mirage.''
   At Dukakis campaign headquarters in Boston, spokesman Steve Akey
did not immediately return a reporter's call seeking comment.
</TEXT>
