<DOCNO> AP880815-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-15 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restoration effort this summer is
returning the stately old Minnesota Senate chamber to the way it
looked in 1905 when fellows who carried pocket watches and used
spittoons debated there.
   It'll cost the taxpayers $21 million before it's over in
December, but those purple walls will be a thing of the past. They
will be repainted to a peach tone, to go with the new red rug.
   ``These colors are all wrong,'' said Sen. Donald Moe, who heads
a subcommittee in charge of the restoration. ``The purple should
not be here. We can't find anyone who will admit recommending it.''
It went on in the 1970s.
   The building's exterior also will be cleaned and repaired, and
new gold leaf will be applied to the ball atop the dome.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FULLERTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Orange County say they've
found an almost foolproof way to reduce the number of raucous
parties in their cities: bill the hosts for the time it takes to
break up the noisy get-togethers.
   Eleven Orange County cities have approved ordinances within the
past year enabling police to take such action.
   Under the ordinances, if police have to return after issuing a
warning, the host will be billed for personnel and equipment costs.
   ``It's worked beyond our wildest dreams,'' Fullerton police Sgt.
Gary Miller said.
   ``Since it went into effect, I guess that there are 1,000
parties we've gone to, and I think we've gone back (a second time)
10 times,'' Miller said.
   Hosts, however, have not been overly thrilled about paying up.
   Mike Lasater of La Habra said he has no intention of paying his
bill, even if it is only $16.44.
   ``I ain't paying it,'' he said. ``They can take me to jail for
$16.''
   Lasater, who threw a party for his daughter's high school
graduation in June, said he immediately broke up the party after
his first warning, but some guests lingered in the street and
police had to disperse them.
   ``The city hasn't chosen what to do if people ignore the
billing,'' said Capt. John Rees of the La Habra Police Department.
</TEXT>
