<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0713 08-15 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Police Turn Back Student March For Reunification</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Monday clash. Picks up 9th
graf pvs, `Fewer students ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firing volleys of tear gas, riot
police on Monday broke off a student march to the North Korean
border to press for reunification. Police arrested and beat scores
of protesters.
   About 2,500 students holding red and blue banners tried to march
out of Yonsei University to go to the border truce village of
Panmunjom, about 30 miles away.
   Hundreds of riot troopers in green combat fatigues and
black-visored helmets confronted students as soon as they exited
the main gate.
   Some officers were seen beating students with riot shields and
making flkying karate kicks at fleeing protesters.
   The students did not fight back and most were unarmed except for
a few carrying clubs. Some students hurled a few stones, but the
protesters only fought back with clubs and rocks when the police
charged into the campus.
   Dozens of students seized by police huddled on the ground,
clinging to each other as police hit and kicked them. Some students
cried with pain and senior police officers hit some of their own
troopers to try and stop the beating.
   The students made three atrempts to march out of the main gate.
Each time, they were driven back by charging police and armored
vans firing tear gas.
   The students marched out after a rally to call for reunification
with communist North Korea. They wanted to go to Panmunjom for
talks with North Korean student delegates on reuniting the divided
Korean pensinsula.
   The government banned the march and deployed more than 20,000
riot police to stop it.
   On Sunday, hundreds of students at Yonsei and another college in
central Seoul battled riot police with firebombs and rocks, and
furious residents demanded a halt to the protests to protect the
Olympics.
   Fewer students appeared to be involved than in clashes on
Saturday. The few thousand radicals involved in the protests have
virtually no public support and clashes were confined to two or
three small areas.
   Students tried to stage a number of demonstrations in downtown
Seoul, but handfuls of protesters were dispersed quickly by
hundreds of riot police. Police said more than 5,000 riot troops
were deployed to block the protests.
   National Police Headquarters said hundreds of people were
arrested, but it had no overall figures. Officials said 1,027
protesters were arrested in clashes Saturday and 63 troopers
injured, most in clashes around Yonsei.
   Police halted and searched students entering or leaving Yonsei
on Sunday. Dozens of students were arrested and troops were seen
beating and kicking some detainees.
   Angry residents and shopkeepers staged several counter-protests
to demand that students stop violent demonstrations. Onlookers
heckled student demonstrators in the city. ``No firebombs by
students,'' they shouted.
   About 200 residents went to the main gate of Yonsei Sunday to
demand students end the protest, but the students refused.
   Citizens also argued with protesters near the city's Myondong
Cathedral, accusing them of sabotaging the Summer Olympics
scheduled to begin in Seoul Sept. 17. People told the students
their protests embarrassed the nation.
   A column of about 1,000 people who said they belonged to the
previously unknown ``Youth League for Protection of the Nation''
staged a march in central Seoul, chanting: ``Successful Olympics
and economic development.'' Dozens of onlookers applauded.
   Students attacked some of the group's marchers with sticks and
rocks near Seoul National University Medical School before being
driven off by police.
   President Roh Tae-woo warned Friday that violent protests were a
threat to the Olympics and had to be stopped.
   Radical students have seized on the reunification issue to try
to mobilize public support for their anti-government campaign. The
radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have failed to
gain support because of violent tactics and open advances to the
communist north.
   The students say they are not communists but insist the
peninsula be reunited immediately, with political differences to be
worked out later. Most South Koreans fear the north is determined
to conquer them.
   The radical students also demand removal of the 42,000 U.S.
troops in South Korea.
   The Korean peninsula has been divided since 1945 at the end of
World War II. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to start the
Korean War.
</TEXT>
