<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Plutonium-Terrorism Bjt   08-15 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plutonium-Terrorism, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorist Threat Cited in Nuke Shipments by Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing the potential of terrorist attack,
members of Congress are putting the Reagan administration on notice
that they will strongly oppose any move to permit sea shipment of
plutonium from Europe to Japan.
   ``Here you have an administration that is supposedly waging a
war on terrorism, but promoting a policy that could make terrorism
easy,'' said Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., a member of the House
Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The issue stems from a recently signed U.S.-Japan nuclear
cooperation treaty that authorizes shipments by air of plutonium
from reprocessing plants in Europe back to Japan, where it will be
used to fuel nuclear power plants.
   The plutonium, which also could be utilized for nuclear weapons,
is controlled by the U.S. government because the nuclear fuel
originated in the United States.
   Proceeding with the air shipments was made contingent upon
development of crash-proof shipping casks, which so far has proven
unachievable.
   In the face of that, the Japanese have been seeking to amend the
nuclear cooperation treaty to give 30-year advance approval for
shipment by sea. Such a ``subsequent arrangement'' must be reviewed
by Congress.
   Wolpe said late last week that amending the U.S.-Japan accord
would face significant opposition on Capitol Hill.
   ``Congress will have a 15-day review period when it will be very
difficult for the Reagan administration to explain how, if we are
not shipping plutonium by air because it is not yet safe, we can
consider shipping plutonium by sea, which is a proven danger,'' he
said.
   The Michigan Democrat joined with 13 other House members and
four senators in sending a letter this month to President Reagan,
expressing their concern over reports that his administration has
agreed in principle to allow sea shipment.
   They cited a March 1988 Pentagon study which said ``the Office
of the Secretary of Defense, joint staff and services have
concluded that air shipment via the polar route is preferable to
sea shipment.''
   The study warned that during sea shipment ``the vessel is
accessible and vulnerable throughout the voyage, particularly when
the vessel is passing through channels, straits, and other
restricted waterways (`choke points'), or when it is near the
coast.''
   ``Even if the most careful precautions are observed no one could
guarantee the safety of the cargo from a security incident, such as
an attack on the vessel by small, fast craft, especially if armed
with modern anti-ship missiles,'' it said.
   The only previous sea shipment of plutonium from Europe to Japan
took place in 1984, when the cargo ship was escorted by U.S.,
French and Japanese naval vessels and monitored constantly by
satellite.
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead dealt with the
plutonium issue in a May 30 letter to members of the House Foreign
Affairs and Senate Foreign Relations committees.
   In the letter, Whitehead said: ``The administration will
consider programmatic shipment of plutonium under adequate physical
security pursuant to the implementing agreement. Such an
arrangement would be treated by the administration as a subsequent
arrangement in accordance with Section 131 of the Atomic Energy
Act.''
   A State Department official, who spoke on condition that he not
be identified, said: ``The government of Japan approached the U.S.
government on this issue and requested discussions. Officials of
Japan and the United States met in July to begin the discussions,
and further discussions are taking place in Japan.''
   He said there was no indication how long the talks would
continue.
   The Department of Energy has said it expects that each sea
shipment would involve more than 200 kilograms, or 440 pounds, of
plutonium.
   According to the Nuclear Control Institute, a Washington-based
nuclear non-proliferation policy group, approximately 15 pounds of
plutonium would be enough to make a nuclear weapon.
   ``This transportation controversy underscores the very real
dangers of civilian plutonium commerce,'' said Alan Kuperman, the
institute's issues director. ``It should prompt Japan to reconsider
its commitment to recycling plutonium.''
   Along with Wolpe, House members signing the Aug. 4 letter to
Reagan were Reps. Don Bonker, D-Wash.; Ted Weiss, D-N.Y.; Gary L.
Ackerman, D-N.Y.; Chester G. Atkins, D-Mass.; Peter H. Kostmayer,
D-Pa.; George J. Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y.; James H. Bilbray, D-Nev.;
George W. Crockett Jr., D-Mich.; Gus Yatron, D-Pa.; Howard L.
Berman, D-Calif.; Edward F. Feighan, D-Ohio; Edward J. Markey,
D-Mass., and Mel Levine, D-Calif.
   Also signing it were Sens. William Proxmire, D-Wis.; Rudy
Boschwitz, R-Minn.; Paul Simon, D-Ill., and John F. Kerry, D-Mass.
</TEXT>
