<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Minorities     08-15 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Minorities,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minority Republicans Praise Reagan's Rights Effort, Seek More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black and Hispanic Republicans had kind words
for President Reagan's minority hiring record, but grumbled about
the opening today of a national convention overwhelmingly dominated
by white men.
   ``What we have to do is start making ourselves known at the
local level,'' said George Smith, a black delegate from San Diego.
``Hopefully, four years from now, the dismal, small number will be
increased.
   ``I don't want anyone taking me for granted,'' he said.
   More than 1,000 delegates and activists gathered on the
outskirts of the sweltering convention city Sunday night for an
evening-long tribute to Reagan's role in naming minority group
members to his administration.
   They also gave him credit for boosting the economy, which they
called the best possible program for the poor.
   ``You've got a tremendous record here,'' said Bill Wilson, a
spokesman for the Council of Minority Americans, the group
organizing the tribute. ``You can't get any economic clout if you
can't get a job.''
   But there was an undercurrent of unhappiness about this week's
convention, with just over 92 percent white delegates, compared to
68 percent at last month's Democratic National Convention. Roughly
3 percent of the GOP delegates are black.
   ``It's too low, we all know that,'' said Clarence Thomas,
chairman of the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and a
black Reagan administration appointee honored at the meeting. ``The
party has to do more than just passively sit back. We want to be
critical without being antagonistic.''
   The gathering was held in a sprawling, corrugated metal building
miles from the Superdome where the convention kicks off today. The
building houses floats used in Mardi Gras parades, so activists
milled about under giant papier-mache caricatures of kings and
revelers and occasionally posed for pictures next to the more
outrageous examples.
   At one point, activists argued that Republicans can lure more
black voters, while the strains of ``Dixie'' wafted from the
bandstand. The song, which expresses nostalgia for the old South,
is considered offensive to some blacks.
   Neighbors in the heavily black section of the city looked on
curiously from across the street. The Republican convention city is
55.1 percent black.
   
   There has been criticism over the past week about the tiny
minority population to be seated in the Superdome today.
   Alan Keyes, a Senate candidate in Maryland who is black, said
Republicans are too leery of newcomers regardless of race.
   ``I think there is a problem with the representational structure
of the party,' he said.
   Keyes was in an earlier flap with convention organizers that
underscored the occasionally tense relations between the GOP and
minorities. He is scheduled to address the convention Wednesday,
and publicly complained that organizers wanted him to emphasize his
race in the speech.
   Another criticism of GOP organizers came earlier in the day from
John Rondeno, a New Orleans financial planner running a reception
center for delegates favoring vanquished presidential candidate Pat
Robertson.
   ``I think the Republican Party right now is limited,'' said
Rondeno. ``Unfortunately, the Republican Party has been the party
of `keep it small and keep it all'. Blacks in the Republican Party
were totally excluded from this convention.''
   Most attending Sunday night's dinner and reception, however,
preferred to stress the potential gain for both minorities and
Republicans in a stronger relationship. But they made it clear that
the party's establishment must extend a hand in welcome.
   ``That's what the Republican Party has to do, open up its
doors,'' said Californian Smith. ``The party has to have more
blacks at all levels, at all echelons.''
   ``This is designed to let the convention know there are
minorities who do support the ticket,'' said Lawrence King, an
Omaha, Neb., businessman who organized the group.
   King shrugged off questions about the number of blacks and other
minorities at the convention.
   ``I think that's basically the way things are,'' he said.
``There are not a lot of black Republicans.''
</TEXT>
