<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Color     08-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Color,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Quarter Has More Than ``Strong Drink At Conservative
Prices''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY SHULINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Authentic Democratic Voodoo Dolls'' sold
for $2.98 and Ryan's Irish Pub poured Republican cocktails _
``strong drink at conservative prices; Busch on tap.''
   New Orleans costumed itself in GOP finery for conventioneers
wandering its sultry streets. It stuffed its shop windows with
elephants and its visitors with oysters. And, like a Mardi Gras
reveler, it kept a part of itself under wraps.
   ``I think they might've put some of the bums in jail,'' said
Kathy Hastings, a waitress at the Original Old Absinthe House on
Bourbon Street, where the likes of Mark Twain and Andrew Jackson
once bellied up to the bar. ``I haven't seen the usual prostitutes,
either.''
   Off St. Charles Avenue, the heaps of trash longtime resident
Gary Esolen described as ``an urban horror'' had disappeared. More
dramatic, to French Quarter gallery owner Joseph Sutton, was a
transformed railroad overpass between the airport and downtown New
Orleans.
   ``For 364 days a year, it's got the most disgusting graffiti
you've ever seen,'' Sutton said. ``Now, they have it painted pastel
colors _ peach, lavender and aqua. Suddenly, it is to die! It's
under 24-hour guard to make sure it stays that way.''
   ``The city has never looked better,'' added Sutton, who'd even
heard that mint was being dumped into city sewer lines to further
sweeten things up for the visitors. ``I don't know if it's true.
But it does show the extent to which we feel the eyes of the world
on New Orleans.''
   On Bourbon Street, the carousing capital of the city, waitress
Hastings thought the party was getting off to a slow start. She'd
been looking forward to the Republicans' arrival for weeks. Now
that they're here, ``they're turning out to be cheap.''
   Taxi driver Bob Kendall, on the other hand, had hung a stuffed
elephant from his rear view mirror in tribute to some ``excellent''
tipping.
   And Sutton, a ``Kennedy Democrat,'' was keeping his bases
covered, with a $6,800 gold and ivory elephant prominently
displayed in the front window of his shop.
   It was there, in the heart of the French Quarter, that the
Republicans congregated, sampling the rich gumbo of cultures:
French, Spanish, Caribbean, Italian. They took in the jazz
musicians, the voodoo dolls, and the crabs.
   But Esolen says the more subtle qualities of the quarter must be
appreciated.
   ``As you wander the streets, there's a sense of scale that is
such that a human being is welcome,'' said Esolen. ``You can
imagine yourself in every nook and cranny, in the light of a
balcony window, the glimpse of a patio.
   ``At the same time, much of its architecture looks inward. The
French Quarter is a place of secrets.''
</TEXT>
