<HEAD>Massachusetts Republicans Hope to Provide `Truth' About Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts delegates to the Republican
National Convention hope to offer GOP counterparts from around the
country an inside glimpse of their longtime nemesis, Michael
Dukakis.
   The 52-delegate group will act as a ``truth squad of sorts'' at
the convention, which opens today, said Andrew Card, a former White
House aide and state representative who has rejoined the Bush
campaign.
   ``The people from Massachusetts know Mike Dukakis best, and they
will help call attention to the `Massachusetts Mirage' and help to
describe who Mike Dukakis really is,'' Card said.
   Dukakis has been the chief target of state Republicans since he
won his first gubernatorial race in 1974. He is in his 10th year as
governor, losing a re-election bid in 1978 and returning to office
in 1983.
   Joseph Malone, a delegate who is running against Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., said he has talked to Georgia Republicans ``who
lament the fact that they never really got the message out about
how bad Jimmy Carter would be for America. We don't want to repeat
that mistake.''
