<HEAD>Connecticut Delegates Urged To Preach Virtues Of Moderation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Connecticut Republicans are uneasy with
a homestate congresswoman's suggestion that they promote the
state's brand of moderate Republicanism during this week's national
convention.
   Rep. Nancy Johnson on Sunday told the Connecticut delegation
that more moderate party policies are needed to broaden the party's
appeal.
   ``I don't think it's appropriate,'' said delegate Richard C.
Bozzuto. ``We've determined the candidate, the decision from this
point on is much the candidate's choice.''
   State Rep. Richard Foley of Oxford said Connecticut delegates
shouldn't be preaching to their generally more conservative
counterparts from elsewhere in the country.
   ``Folks in Connecticut ... have a hard time figuring out what's
going on in Oklahoma and New Mexico and California,'' Foley said.
   Mrs. Johnson, a member of the convention's Platform Committee,
on Sunday said some elements of the platform, including its strong
anti-abortion language, are ``constraining, alienating and will
prevent this party in the future from becoming the majority party
if we cannot find a way to speak more broadly to more elements in
the American population.''
   She urged Connecticut delegates to take that message to members
of other state delegations this week.
