<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Zumwalt     08-15 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Zumwalt,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zumwalt: Son's Death Pushes Him To Fight Harder For Compensation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmo R. Zumwalt III, who died of
cancer two decades after his father ordered use of Agent Orange in
Vietnam, once swam through water doused with the defoliant to
collect weapons from Viet Cong boats.
   He won over his crew, but that swim may have marked the
beginning of his last battle, with the cancer that ended his life
Saturday at age 42.
   Retired Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., the American naval commander
in Vietnam who ordered the spraying of the defoliant then thought
to be harmless, said his son's death will only push him to work
harder to force the government to compensate veterans who suffered
from Agent Orange's effects.
   ``There are still many hundreds of veterans who do need help,''
Zumwalt said the day his son died. ``I believe very strongly now
that the evidence is clear that the Agent Orange is responsible for
the problems many veterans are having.''
   His son was diagnosed in 1983 as having non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
Two years later, doctors found he had lymphoma Hodgkins disease.
   His son, Elmo Russell Zumwalt IV, suffers from a congenital
dysfunction that confuses his physical senses.
   The Zumwalts chronicled their battle with cancer in 1986 with
the book, ``My Father, My Son,'' which they wrote with author John
Pekkanen. The book was made into a television movie in May.
   Zumwalt said his son was strong until the end, even joking and
teasing with relatives during Friday evening. He died in his sleep
Saturday morning.
   ``I do not second guess the decisions Dad made in Vietnam, nor
do I doubt for a minute that the saving of human life was always
his first priority in his conduct of the war,'' the younger Zumwalt
once said. ``I have the greatest love and admiration for him as a
man, and the deepest respect for him as a military leader.''
   Zumwalt was commanding a swift boat along the rivers of the Ca
Mau Peninsula when his father, the youngest man ever to serve as
chief of naval operations, ordered the spraying of Agent Orange to
save servicemen from being killed by enemy ambushes along the
waterways.
   Before the spraying, U.S. forces had a 6 percent casualty rate
each month. Afterward, that figure dropped to less than 1 percent.
   Since the war, the elder Zumwalt and his son had pushed for
government assistance to veterans affected by Agent Orange.
   On June 30, the U.S. Supreme Court removed the last legal
obstacle to a $180 million settlement between Vietnam veterans and
the manufacturers of Agent Orange. The justices let stand rulings
that dismissed lawsuits by about 300 veterans who had challenged a
1984 settlement.
</TEXT>
