<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Hirohito     08-15 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Hirohito,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Says Thought Of War Dead Still Pains Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito said today at a ceremony marking
the 43rd anniversary of the end of World War II that ``it still
hurts my heart'' to think of those who died in battle and their
families.
   He also praised Japan's development and expansion since the end
of the war.
   Hirohito, 87, the only surviving leader of the major
participating countries in the war, walked slowly at the public
hall outside the Imperial Palace in central Tokyo.
   The moment of silence traditionally held at noon sharp was
delayed briefly while he shuffled to the microphone. However, he
walked without assistance and spoke in a firm voice.
   ``Today, on the day to honor the war dead and pray for peace, I
think of those who died in battle in the last war and their
bereaved families, and it still hurts my heart,'' he said.
   ``Time flies fast, and in the 43 years since the end of the war,
the country has developed due to people's efforts,'' he said.
   The emperor underwent surgery last year so doctors could perform
a bypass around a growth in his pancreas. Since then, his public
appearances have been limited.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who also attended the ceremony,
said it is Japan's duty to help maintain peace and not let war
recur.
   The ceremony, held on the 43rd anniversary of the day Japan
surrendered, was attended by about 7,000 people, including members
of the Cabinet.
   Meanwhile, thousands of Japanese went to the Yasukuni Shrine,
dedicated to the Japanese war dead. Among them were many
politicians and several members of the Cabinet.
   However, Takeshita decided not to go, following a policy set by
his predecessor, Yasuhiro Nakasone.
   Among the 2.4 million Japanese war dead enshrined there are 14
Class A _ or major _ war criminals, including wartime Prime
Minister Hideki Tojo.
</TEXT>
