<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Riot,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concert Crashers Go On Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of youths barged into a music concert
without paying and went on to loot shops, rob bus and subway
passengers and shower riot police with rocks and bottles, police
said.
   Nine people were arrested and one subway passenger was taken to
the hospital with facial cuts, but no serious injuries were
reported in the Sunday night melee in west London, police said.
   Scotland Yard spokesman Mike Cobb said about 300 youths forced
down a perimeter fence and barged into a soul music concert at a
park in Shepherd's Bush without paying the $11 entrance fee.
   Organizers ended the 8-hour concert 1{ hours early at 8:30 p.m.
and the 300 people who paid to attend the concert left peacefully,
Cobb said.
   But the same group that barged into the concert spilled into the
streets, ransacking and looting shops in the area and mugging some
passers-by, he said.
   Acting Chief Inspector Jim McFarlane of the British Transport
Police said that at about 9 p.m. about 200 of the youths boarded a
Central Line subway at White City ``and systemically went through
the train, through the connecting doors, robbing people on their
way.''
   He said 14 people reported being robbed and one passenger
suffered facial cuts, McFarlane said.
   Scotland Yard said about 20 youths armed with knives and chains
jumped onto a bus, assaulted the driver and robbed passengers of
cash and jewelry.
   Youths hurled rocks and bottles at riot police during the
disturbances, which lasted nearly two hours, police said.
</TEXT>
