<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0552EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HardwareShow     08-15 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hardware Show,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Offers Oddities, Lawn Care Products for Do-It-Yourselfers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-tech toilet seat that lowers automatically
and a speaking smoke detector that gives warnings in English or
Spanish are among the 250,000 products being displayed at the
National Hardware Show.
   With a push of the button, the seat can automatically move up or
down. It also can remove odors with its fanning mechanism and
charcoal filter, adjust its temperature to suit any posterior and
can kill germs with an ultraviolet light.
   While the seat does eliminate some age-old conflicts between men
and women, there is a catch. It retails for $350.
   ``The price is too high,'' acknowledged Keith Chiu, who
developed the device and is director of Eletto Industries Inc. of
Monterey Park, Calif. ``Most people won't pay $350 for what this
can do. At that price, I doubt if I'd buy it myself.''
   The four-day show, which began Sunday, is the biggest in its
43-year history and the country's largest trade show, said manager
Pat Dolson.
   About 70,000 retailers are expected to attend.
   William Farrell, executive director of the American Hardware
Manufacturers Association of Schaumburg, said do-it-yourselfers are
fueling the industry.
   They spent $52 billion last year at hardware, home center and
building supply outlets, and the market is expected to grow by 12
percent annually, to total $100 billion by 1990, he said.
   ``Do-it-yourself people are moving the home improvement industry
outdoors,'' said Ms. Dolson. ``It's a recreational thing for the
yuppie generation and we see tremendous growth in this area.''
   One prominent item for the outdoors do-it-yourselfer is a new
version of an old standby: the push lawnmower.
   American Lawn Mowers, a family-owned company based in
Shelbyville, Ind., is displaying its line of cast-iron push mowers
retailing for $69 to $99, which it says are ideal for the small
patch of grass around the condo patio.
   ``It's the lawnmower for the lifestyle of the new generation,''
said Teri McClain, a company sales representative. ``Joggers and
people into aerobics can get a workout mowing the lawn.''
   Ms. McClain said sales of the push mower are up 47 percent
during the past two years, after a lightweight 17-pound model of
the 50-year-old traditional design was introduced several years ago.
   For the non-athletically inclined, the show offered a
top-of-the-line Volvo lawnmower, a $5,000 riding vehicle with
four-wheel steering from Swedish maker Husqvarna.
   And then there's Vocalert, a computerized smoke detector that
not only sounds an alarm signal but can offer instructions in a
calm, authoritative voice.
   It has a built-in bilingual English-Spanish vocabulary of 100
words and phrases _ that can be programmed to tell people what to
do to escape _ such as ``stay calm'' or ``drop to the floor,''
depending on the intensity of the fire, which its sensors pick up.
   ``It has an intelligence to it and is good for situations in
which people are disoriented like children and the elderly,'' said
its inventor, Joseph Sansonetti, chief executive officer of Pioneer
Manufacturing Inc. of St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Sansonetti said about 1.2 million are being produced, with the
suggested retail price $89.95. He said it should be available in
store by mid-fall.
   ``It's going to eliminate the confusion for everyone,'' he said.
</TEXT>
