<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DavyCrockett     08-15 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Davy Crockett,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studio Searches For New Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanted: A new king of the wild frontier.
Being born on a mountaintop in Tennessee helpful, but not required.
   Walt Disney Studios and NBC are bringing back Davy Crockett and
held an open casting call Sunday to expand the search for an actor
to fill the role played on television by Fess Parker in the 1950s.
   William Blinn, the executive producer of the show that will be
part of ``The Magical World of Disney,'' said the search has gone
on for more than five months and has auditioned more than 800
people.
   ``It's a quality of strength and intelligence and a kind of
implied humor that Fess always brought to it, and a kind of droll
warmth. That's hard to find,'' Blinn said.
   The producer said he wasn't interested in a ``Rambo'' sort of
hero or the muscle-bound characters played by Arnold Schwarzenegger.
   ``They don't offer humor in their portrayal, nor do they offer
to me a guy that is at ease with himself _ they have a great deal
of tension,'' Blinn said.
   The series, scheduled to premiere in November, is based on the
life of Crockett, a frontiersman who fought river pirates and
Indians and served in the Tennessee Legislature in the 1820s and
1830s.
   The old show's theme song identified Crockett as the frontier
king who was born on a mountaintop in Tennessee.
   Kevin DuBay, one of the more than 75 actors at the casting call,
said he had a coonskin cap and watched reruns of the series as a
child.
   ``It was important when you played cowboys and Indians to know
who Davy Crockett was,'' the 25-year-old said.
   Joel Mills, 27, said he shares a love of the outdoors with
Crockett and believes it is important to have old-fashioned heroes
like Crockett.
   ``I think our children deserve better than Rambo,'' he said.
   Parker will appear in the first two-hour episode as an elder
statesman reflecting on his youth.
   The new ``Davy Crockett'' will be rotated on NBC's weekly ``The
Magical World Of Disney'' with other features, including cartoons
and a re-creation of ``The Absent-Minded Professor'' with Harry
Anderson in the title role.
</TEXT>
