<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WalrusDies     08-15 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walrus Dies,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Oldest Walrus in Captivity Dies at Age 27</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOKFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sad-eyed, white-whiskered Olga, the
nation's oldest walrus in captivity, has died.
   The 27-year-old Atlantic walrus died of old age Sunday, said
veterinarian William Torgerson. Olga, who weighed about 2,700
pounds, had been at the Brookfield Zoo outside Chicago since 1962,
when she was a 6-month old pup.
   ``She was quite a character,'' said zoo spokeswoman Linda Elbert.
   Olga gained national attention in 1979 when zoo officials were
seeking ``zoo parents'' to help underwrite costs. At that time, the
tab for Olga's fresh-frozen mackerel and herring diet _ 60 pounds a
day _ was $13,000 a year.
   More than $20,000 in contributions came in from some 1,000
``parents'' across the nation.
   ``We used to celebrate her birthday each year with her adoptive
parents and Olga was one for shows,'' Ms. Elbert said. ``She'd
whistle, blow kisses, wave her flippers and spray the crowd when
nobody expected it. She was just a real joy.''
   Olga, who came to Brookfield from the Copenhagen Zoo in Denmark,
began suffering kidney problems late last month.
</TEXT>
