<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0481 08-15 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Iran Doing All Possible To Release Britons, But Wants
Reciprocity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Runcie aide cautious about
quick release of hostages. Adds detail on missing Iranians. Picks
up 11th graf pvs ``Iran has...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government-run newspaper says Iran will do
all it can to secure the freedom of British hostages in Lebanon but
is requesting in return that Britain help find Iranians missing
there.
   The word came in a Sunday editorial in the English-language
Tehran Times and coincided with a visit by British diplomat David
Reddaway, who said Foreign Ministry officials told him he will be
able to meet this week with an Englishman being held on spying
charges.
   In London, a senior aide to Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie said today he is cautious about a quick release of hostages
following talks with an Iranian diplomat in London.
   The Tehran Times editorial said: ``Undoubtedly the Islamic
Republic of Iran will spare no effort to press ahead with the
release of British hostages, particularly Terry Waite,'' referring
to Runcie's envoy.
   ``Yet what Iran legitimately expects of Britain is to provide
Iran with all the information possible about the fate of four
Iranian hostages'' believed held by Christian militia ``under the
influence of Britain,'' it added.
   Four Iranians disappeared in a Christian-controlled area of
Lebanon in 1982. No group ever claimed to hold them and some
reports have said they were killed.
   Waite and two other Britons are among 18 foreigners believed
held by groups affiliated with the pro-Iranian and Shiite Moslem
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in Lebanon. The 18 include nine
Americans.
   The editorial also follows talks in Britain last week between
Runcie, spiritual leader of the Anglican Church, and Mohamed Reza
Said Mohamedi, an Iranian Foreign Ministry official.
   John Lyttle, Runcie's senior assistant, said in London today
that whether Iran chooses to pressure for the release of the
British captives remains to be seen.
   ``I don't think this is the time to talk about either assurances
or promises,'' Lyttle said in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio
interview.
   ``I'm optimistic that he (Terry Waite) is alive and that the
other British hostages are alive. As to whether anything is going
to happen quickly, I'm rather more cautious,'' he said.
   Lyttle said he and the archbishop made clear to Mohamedi that
the church has a limited role as far as the hostages are concerned.
   ``We want to make it quite plain that the church cannot be an
alternative diplomatic channel, but that its interest is a
humanitarian one and a rather particular one. We may be able to oil
a wheel here and there, but we certainly can't act as an
alternative diplomatic channel,'' he said.
   Reddaway said he met with Foreign Ministry officials twice on
Sunday and they told him he would be able to meet jailed Englishman
Roger Cooper this week. He gave no other details.
   Cooper, 52, a nephew of the late British poet and novelist
Robert Graves, was arrested in December 1985 and has been held in
Tehran's Evin Prison.
   Before leaving London on Friday, Reddaway said he would speak
with officials about the foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   In July, an Anglican bishop went to Lebanon to initiate
inquiries among Christians about the fate of the four Iranians
missing in Lebanon.
   Iran has been making conciliatory statements about relations
with Western nations since it announced July 18 it was accepting a
U.N. call for a cease-fire in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   The cease-fire is scheduled to take hold Saturday.
   Last summer, Britain withdrew all its diplomats from Iran and
virtually severed ties after a British diplomat was detained and
beaten in apparent reprisal for British police arresting an Iranian
envoy on shoplifting charges. One Iranian diplomat remains in
London.
   Waite disappeared in January 1987 while trying to secure the
release of American hostages. The other two British citizens
believed held in Lebanon are journalist John McCarthy, kidnapped on
April 17, 1986 and university professor Brian Keenan, kidnapped
April 11, 1986. Keenan also holds an Irish passport.
   Britain says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a New
York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim
they killed him. His body was never found.
   The foreigner held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was abducted
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
