<DOCNO> AP880815-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BarkFirst     08-15 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bark First,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Dogs Taught To Bark Before Biting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police department is training police
dogs to bark instead of bite _ but a civil rights activist says
many people will never forget the news images of protesters being
mauled in the 1960s.
   ``Unfortunately, the 25-year-old image of police dogs (in
Birmingham) still lives,'' said the Rev. Abraham Woods, pastor of
St. Joseph Baptist Church.
   Sgt. Cameron Guy said the program is part of the department's
minimal-force arrest policy, under which a suspect will be given
every chance to surrender peacefully.
   ``A felon breaking into a business deserves to be off the
street, but he does not need to be dog-bitten,'' said Guy, who
directs the canine unit.
   Guy said the policy is a move to boost professionalism in the
department.
   During civil rights protests in Birmingham in the 1960s, newsmen
filmed snarling police dogs biting protesters. Those films have
been shown frequently since then.
   Woods said he has been invited to watch the department
demonstrate its new policy.
   The dogs are being trained to sprint toward the suspect and,
instead of sinking their teeth into the suspect's arm, veer off at
the last moment, blocking any escape attempt, while barking loudly
and baring their teeth.
   Guy said the dog will bite if a suspect tries to attack the
accompanying officer or the animal.
</TEXT>
