<DOCNO> AP880815-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FairContest     08-15 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Contest,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Shortage Of Competitors At Illinois State Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who weren't too chicken to crow
like roosters or cackle like hens held the spotlight at the
Illinois State Fair, along with wives calling their husbands and
men their calling hogs.
   For as much as $75 in prize money, contestants could imitate
roosters and hens, or be the best at calling their husbands or hogs.
   ``I figured for $75 I could make a fool of myself,'' says Phil
Bartz, winner of Saturday's rooster crowing contest.
   He donned a white hood complete with red comb before crouching
down to scurry around in front of a crowd of people and crow like a
rooster.
   He wasn't the only one of the 15 contestants in the fair's first
rooster crowing and hen cackling contests who was in it for the
money.
   ``Cold, hard cash,'' was how Frank Nordike of Carlyle described
his motivation for entering the contest.
   Nordike won a $10, third-place prize for his rooster imitation,
which included some amorous advances toward a woman who was
supposed to be a hen.
   The winners in the husband and hog calling contests said they
weren't in it for the money.
   ``I enjoy it and I love pigs,'' said Marvin Routzong of
Springboro, Ohio, who was named Grand Champion Hog Caller for a
third consecutive year on Sunday.
   The factory supervisor's routine combines realism with whimsy as
he enters the arena, dumps some corn from a bucket and begins
hitting the bucket with an ear of corn.
   That ``is how you really call a pig,'' he said.
   Then Routzong hit the highlight of his performance with a chorus
of ``Pig-o-lo, pig-o-lo, pig-o-lo, pig,'' in an operatic baritone.
   The Grand Champion Husband Caller was also a three-time winner.
   Paula Tyler of Chillicothe won the prize by dressing like a hag
and reading an instruction manual on how to call a husband. ``When
it comes time to yell don't be shy, just open your mouth and let
her fly,'' she screamed as she read from the manual.
   And she did.
   ``Donnnnnnnald,'' rang from the rafters in the Swine Barn.
   And out scurried Donald, Mrs. Tyler's husband, who ran up and
gave her a kiss.
   He wore a ``husband'' sign around his neck so spectators would
know who he was.
   Tyler said he wasn't embarrassed by all the attention.
   ``Something to do on a Sunday afternoon,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
