<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SanDiegoSlayings     08-15 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-San Diego Slayings,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coroner Changes Policy To Aid Police Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified women slain in San Diego County no
longer will be cremated in order to preserve evidence for police
investigating links between a serial killing spree here and
Washington's Green River slayings.
   County coroner David Stark also said his office will perform
more extensive tests on the bodies of unidentified women that may
be linked to the deaths of at least 10 other women in San Diego
County since 1985.
   The policy was prompted by criticism last week from homicide
detectives. Detectives from both states have been studying
similarities between the two murder cases for at least 18 months
but said no conclusive link has been made.
   One body was cremated before being linked to the San Diego
County case, Stark said.
   ``We will change our procedure,'' Stark said. ``When the
circumstances of a death clearly indicate that a homicide situation
has occurred _ even though we can't establish a cause of death _ in
the future we will request that the person will be buried.''
   In San Diego, unidentified bodies normally are cremated after
three months. In King County, Wash., where the Green River
investigation is based, unidentified remains are held in an office
or buried after extensive body X-rays.
   Unidentified remains that are buried or stored can be exhumed
later for future examination.
   The Green River case has been described as the nation's worst
unsolved serial murder case.
   The remains of 40 young women have been found around Seattle and
Portland, Ore., and eight missing young women are thought to have
been slain by the killer, who mostly preyed on women linked to
prostitution or other street life.
   The last slaying linked with the Green River killer occurred in
1984.
   Since June 1985, 30 slain women have been found near freeways in
San Diego County. Authorities say between 10 and 18 are the work of
the same killer.
</TEXT>
