<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingDocuments     08-15 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Documents,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Probe Finds Intelligence Messages Lost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 secret Navy documents, including
decoding materials and details of sensitive electronic-warfare
equipment, were lost by engineers and officers at an installation
here, a newspaper reported.
   No evidence was found that the documents were sold to or
obtained by hostile agents, but it ``cannot be discounted that the
unaccounted-for secret material may have been subjected to
compromise,'' said a Navy report obtained by The San Diego Union.
   Navy officials declined comment because the report is under
review, the newspaper reported Sunday.
   In March, then-acting Navy Secretary Lawrence Garrett blamed the
lost documents on poor bookkeeping and lax supervision.
   Navy investigators discovered that 158 documents were missing
after an audit of recordkeeping last year at the Naval Electronic
Systems Engineering Center at Air Force Plant 19, the report said.
   Among the missing materials were manuals on Sea Nymph submarine
sensors designed to pick up enemy radar and conversations and data
about anti-missile early-warning devices, the newspaper said.
   Also unaccounted for were ``key cards,'' or cryptography keys to
encoding and decoding military communications.
   The missing documents were from 1979 through 1984.
   The report strongly criticized Capt. Kirby W. Hansen, commander
of the center during much of that time, but recommended no
discipline against him. He retired in 1986.
   However, disciplinary action is pending against John E. Hassett
of Chula Vista, a civil servant who was supervisor of the
classified mailroom vault at the command from 1981 until 1987, the
newspaper said.
   Hassett said he noticed documents were missing but added, ``I
didn't think there was anything clandestine, just poor accounting
of the publications by the various departments.''
   The report called for a new computer system for tracking
classified documents. The system already has been implemented, Navy
officials said.
</TEXT>
