<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0424 08-15 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0534 to restore CVN designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says Pressure Mounting But He Can Handle It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 14 grafs with Bush quotes today, picking up in
6th graf pvs, Aides said; trims at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, intentionally staying behind as
the opening spotlight plays on President Reagan, said today that
``pressure is mounting'' on him as time grows short before his
Thursday night acceptance speech as the Republican presidential
nominee.
   However, the vice president indicated he felt no pressure to
reveal the one big secret of the party's convention _ the name of
his running mate.
   Making the rounds of the morning network interview shows, he
said he was still ``getting it clear in my mind'' and reiterated
his vow to tell no one his choice in advance after he does decide.
   Campaign aides insist that Bush will withhold the announcement
until Thursday morning _ partly to build suspense and coax a larger
television audience for the Thursday night speech.
   He said there are still multiple contenders for the No. 2 spot.
   ``I have not decided. And I probably will say when I have
decided,'' he said on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   On ``CBS This Morning,'' Bush said, ``I have not told a soul
what I'm thinking and I literally mean that _ not Jim Baker (his
new campaign chairman), not Barbara Bush. Nobody.''
   Bush told NBC's ``Today'' show that once he does make up his
mind, ``I think my choice will be widely accepted'' at the
convention.
   He said that he feels pressure as the night of his speech nears
_ a night that both Republican and Democratic leaders say will be
important for the fall campaign _ but he also said, ``I'm an
athlete'' and can handle pressure.
   Bush was working on his acceptance speech again today. He
arrives in New Orleans on Tuesday.
   Asked if he was concerned that people would compare him with
Reagan, Bush said such comparisons were inevitable.
   But, he told ABC, ``I've got to be what I am and I'm not going
to try to be somebody else.'' He called the convention ``a big
moment for me, the culmination of a lot of years of politics.''
   He told CBS that he planned to have his entire family with him
at the convention. ``Gov. Dukakis did a good job on that (showing
off his family) at the Democratic convention. But we've got a
stronger bench. And we've got a great family.''
   Spokeswoman Sheila Tate said Sunday that Bush already had been
through three drafts of the speech, written with speechwriter Peggy
Noonan, and had practiced it Sunday afternoon at his official vice
presidential residence with media consultant Roger Ailes.
   Bush also had lunch Sunday with Baker, the outgoing Treasury
secretary.
   Aides said Bush still hopes to delay a final announcement of his
vice presidential choice until Thursday morning. However, one
source said aides are considering whether to unveil the choice
Wednesday night.
   Names being most frequently mentioned are Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas and his wife, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole; Rep. Jack Kemp of New York; Sen. Alan
Simpson of Wyoming; Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana; Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh of Pennsylvania; and Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New
Mexico.
   Many of the would-be candidates made the rounds of television
talk shows Sunday. Simpson, on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' disclosed
he had asked Bush to remove his name from the list.
   ``I would be a liability for George,'' Simpson said, citing his
support for limiting Social Security benefit increases and his
belief that the next president will have to increase taxes to trim
the federal deficit as among the positions he had taken that would
``fail the litmus test.''
   However, a top Bush campaign official, who insisted upon
anonymity, said on Sunday that Simpson was sending ``mixed
signals'' and that his comments were not necessarily an indication
that he would be dropped from Bush's short list.
   Bush, in making his final selection, is not necessarily limiting
himself to those whose names have been frequently mentioned, the
official said.
   In a separate appearance on ABC's ``This Week with David
Brinkley,'' Quayle, at 41 the youngest of those believed to be
under consideration, said, ``I would like to believe that I would
be acceptable to the whole party.''
   And Dole declared, ``I am not running for vice president.''
Then, referring to his wife, he added: ``I'm not campaigning for
anyone, but she would be a great addition to the ticket.''
   Thornburgh, meanwhile, said it was ``very flattering'' to be
mentioned but ``I have a job to do for this president.''
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, said on ``Meet the Press''
that Thornburgh would ``make a good attorney general'' but quickly
added, ``I didn't say for how long,'' suggesting his remarks
shouldn't be interpreted to suggest Thornburgh was no longer under
consideration.
   Meanwhile, the vice president, not generally known for his
prowess as a public speaker, continued to focus attention on his
acceptance speech. In addition to his practice in Washington, time
has been set aside in New Orleans for a rehearsal in the Superdome,
aides said.
</TEXT>
