<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraq-Tourism     08-15 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Tourism,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Abolishes State Tourism Organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced today it will
abolish the state tourism agency and said major hotels, restaurants
and other facilities will be sold or leased to the private sector.
   The Revolution Command Council, which passed the decree Aug. 2,
said state-run assets to be privatized included seven hotels in
Baghdad, as well as properties in the war-battered southern port
city of Basra and the northern city of Mosul.
   Hotels not sold will be leased for 25 years to private
companies, the council said.
   The Basra Sheraton Hotel was damaged by shell and rocket fire
during a Iranian offensive in early 1987, when some of the heaviest
fighting in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war took place.
   The state-owned facilities also include a tourist complex in
Habaniya, west of Baghdad, and several modern resorts in the
northern mountains, the scene of heavy fighting in the war.
   The managers of the hotels said they did not know if the
facilities will be sold to Iraq's private sector or to their parent
companies.
   Officials said the hotels are to be run by their parent chains
in accordance with an agreement signed with the Iraqi government.
   Tourism in Iraq, which is rich in archaeological sites, has
diminished as a result of the conflict, but no statistics were
available.
   The move to sell the facilities is part of President Saddam
Hussein's drive to stimulate the economy. The announcement came as
Iranian and Iraqi leaders prepared to meet in Geneva Aug. 25 for
peace talks under a United Nations-mediated cease-fire.
</TEXT>
