<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeatRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0515 08-15 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heat Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0515,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Breaks Over The Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CLARIFY that utilities warned of blackouts,
raises reference to warning. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THEASA TUOHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A heat wave that set records from Arizona to the Atlantic was
blamed for a riot that injured eight at a sweltering Massachusetts
jail, and utility officials in New England warned of blackouts
today unless users conserve.
   In Texas, 35 Salvadoran aliens spent five hours Sunday locked
inside a broiling boxcar with almost no ventilation and probably
would have died had they not been discovered, U.S. Border Patrol
officials said.
   In New York City, a carriage horse collapsed from the heat on a
main thoroughfare but got up the strenth to move on after being
hosed down.
   New York's Road Runners Club, spurred by the heatstroke deaths
of two joggers during the past five weeks, took down the clock for
a Central Park race so runners wouldn't be tempted to push
themselves. No problems were reported.
   In Boston, the temperature jumped from 78 to 92 degrees in 10
minutes. Sunday was the fifth consecutive day of record heat for
Beckley, W.V., and in Arizona, where Phoenix had the nation's high
at 113, it was 89 after midnight.
   Milwaukee exeeded 90 for the 34th day this year, breaking the
33-day record of 1955. Madison recorded 95 degrees, a record for
the date in Wisconsin's capital.
   Temperatures topped 90 for the 17th straight day in northern New
Jersey. Newark tied a 1944 record of 98 Sunday, the 40th day of
90-degree temperatures this summer. That equals the record for the
most 90-degree days in one year.
   In New York City, where the high was 97 degrees, Sunday was the
31st day this summer that temperatures have peaked above 90. The
record is 37 days.
   ``The heat's gonna kill people,'' said Mary Morena, a palm
reader and spirtual adviser. ``People are too nervous, too cranky,
too hot. It's very bad for your sex life.''
   Inmates aggravated by the heat, overcrowding and the food twice
set fire to a 144-year-old granite jail in Lawrence, Mass. One
blaze at the jail, which has no air conditioning, destroyed a wing
containing 36 cells, about a quarter of the jail.
   Nearly 200 of the 250 inmates were relocated to other prisons
around the state, said jail Superintendent William Mageary.
   As New Yorkers returned from weekend activities and cranked up
the air conditioning, power demand hit a record for a Sunday,
according to Consolidated Edison.
   New England power officials warned Sunday night that blackouts
could occur throughout the six-state region today unless users
conserved electricity.
   A shutdown this weekend of the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant
and one of four generators on Salem Harbor in Massachusetts has
made things worse.
   ``If we don't get a considerable contribution by our customers,
as we did a number of days last week, we may not be able to provide
uninterrupted service,'' said Bill Sheperdson, a spokesman for New
England Power Pool, which serves Massachusetts, Maine, Rhode
Island, Connecticut, Vermont and New Hampshire.
   Die-hards who thought they could live without mechanically
cooled air begged for mercy from air conditioner salesmen who long
since had sold out their stock.
   ``It's not really for me, it's for my piano,'' said Kent Tritle,
a customer in Uncle Steve's electronics store. Tritle said he was a
musician whose $7,200 Steinway couldn't take it anymore. ``The
piano is screaming for relief. The keys stick, the response is all
mucked up, the music is slow.''
   Salesman Ira Parker said he'd sold everything, including demos
and displays.
   Entomologists in the New York metropolitan area said the
mosquito population had surged to four times its normal level
because of too little rain in June, too much rain in July and high
humidity in August.
   The 35 aliens found in Kingsville, Texas, were being held Sunday
night, Border Patrol agent Ramiro Gonzalez said.
   ``It was well over 100 degrees (outside) when we found them,''
Gonzalez said. ``It was probably another 20 to 30 degrees hotter
inside the car.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
