<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--MeetTheFamily 1stLd-Writethru a0447 08-15 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Meet The Family, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention to Be Family Affair for Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with quotes from Bush, son, picking up
in 9th graf pvs, Grandson</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, aware of the warm images of
hearth and home evoked by Michael and Kitty Dukakis in Atlanta last
month, promised today to show America ``exactly how much my great,
strong, big family means to me.''
   Bush, who has four sons and a daughter, concedes Dukakis did a
good job at the Democratic National Convention with his speech and
``showing those wonderfully warm pictures'' of his family.
   Now the vice president said, it is his turn.
   ``You know, on family ... I've always tried to hold that a
little bit close,'' he said on ABC-TV. ``And yet, I think I have to
share now with the American people exactly how much my great,
strong, big family means to me.''
   Earlier, the vice president said the Bushes ``come out of a
little more conservative tradition. We haven't been able to speak
as glowingly and as warmly, not because we didn't believe, because
it was different somehow.''
   Marvin Bush, one of Bush's sons, said today on NBC-TV: ``Mike
Dukakis has nothing on George Bush when it comes to real family.''
   In Atlanta, Dukakis' voice caught as he talked about his
deceased father. And there were warm words for his mother Euterpe,
an introduction from his cousin Olympia and fond embraces between
the Massachusetts governor and his wife.
   Bush's children _ all of whom are delegates _ are making the
rounds in New Orleans, talking to other delegates, attending
receptions, working behind the scenes, generally stoking the fires
for Dad.
   Grandson George Prescott Bush will lead the Pledge of Allegiance
on Tuesday. Son Jeb Bush will address the convention on Wednesday
night and on Thursday, Bush's wife of 43 years, Barbara, will speak.
   All told, there will be more than 60 Bush relatives here.
   After a Bush clan dinner Wednesday, Bush's eldest son George _ a
Texas delegate and a top strategist in his father's campaign _ will
announce the delegation's 111 votes that will put Bush oer the top.
   ``To have his son of the same name put him over the top speaks
about family and the commitment of our family to work hard for the
person we love,'' George Jr. said in an interview.
   Issues such as day care, health care for the elderly, parental
leave and other family-related concerns have become important in
the 1988 campaign, and the Republicans don't intend to concede that
ground to the Democrats.
   Great pains will be taken to portray the nominee as a family
man. Much of that testimony will come from his children, all
actively involved in the campaign and some of them expert
campaigners in their own right.
   ``Up to now, George Bush has been reluctant to talk about his
family, his religion, things of a personal nature,'' George Jr.
says. ``Obviously the American people are demanding more than just
issues. Part of the convention will be George Bush opening up, his
family speaking out about love.''
   George Jr., 42, admits to being a seasoned politician. He ran
for Congress unsuccessfully and now is a Bush campaign strategist.
Jeb Bush, 35, is secretary of the Florida Department of Commerce
and worked in his father's 1980 presidential campaign.
   Neil Bush, 33, lives in Denver and worked on his brother
George's congressional campaign and on the 1980 presidential
campaign. Marvin Bush, 31, has his own investment consulting firm
in Alexandria, Va.
   Dorothy Bush LeBlond will turn 29 on the day her father accepts
his party's nomination for president. Described as an
``aggressive'' campaigner, she currently lives in Cape Elizabeth,
Maine.
   The vice president's two brothers, Prescott and Jonathan, and
sister, Nancy Ellis, will be in attendance this week, as will an
assortment of cousins, nieces, nephews and Bush's 10 grandchildren.
His immediate family will surround Bush as he accepts the
nomination.
   ``I have goose bumps,'' said Dorothy Stapleton of Greenwich,
Conn., Bush's first cousin who is also a delegate. ``A lot of us
have been working for this for a long time.''
   George Bush Jr. says the family display at the convention,
choreographed though it may be, won't be ``put on.''
   ``It'll be a very sincere expression of love,'' he says.
   But as for Bush and his wife, convention-viewers should not
expect to see the kind of embraces or affectionate moments the
Dukakises are fond of _ once they were spotted dancing at an
airport in the absence of music. The Bushes aren't given to that
type of display and seem to be a bit touchy about the subject.
   ``I'm not going to dance with her ... with no music. I'm not
going to go that far,'' the vice president said. ``I don't like to
dance anyway, and she knows I'm lousy at it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
