<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TornadoAwaited     08-15 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tornado Awaited,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congregation Keeps Vigil For Tornado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve people have lived in a house converted
into a church for more than seven months awaiting a tornado they
believe will strike the area.
   They have put jobs, educations and families on hold since Jan. 3
and leave the Repairer of the Breach Church of God in Christ only
to purchase food and supplies.
   The tornado shall ``kill many but spare the righteous,'' said
Annie Sims, wife of the church's pastor, Elder M.L. Sims.
   Since Mrs. Sims' prophesy in December, five people have been
removed from the church by court order.
   Rushell Harris, a teacher, and her 16-year-old daugther were
taken from the church for psychiatric treatment after complaints by
relatives. They were found mentally fit and returned to the church.
   Mancy Scott, 51, was forced to leave for kidney dialysis after
friends and medical authorities got a court order. He later moved
in with relatives.
   Lake County Welfare Department officials removed two boys, ages
12 and 13, for not attending school and placed them in foster case.
State law requires children to attend classes until age 16.
   ``God will take care of it all,'' Sims said recently. ``We will
stay here until it (the tornado) comes.''
   Sims' wife had prophesied the tornado would come Jan. 3, and
when it didn't, she predicted it would hit Jan. 24. When it failed
to appear, Sims said God delayed the twister because he wanted more
people to know about it.
   Sims refused to say how he and the other congregation members
survive financially.
   Johnnie Mae Walker, Harris' sister-in-law, said Harris ``saved a
lot of her money. My niece also receives $600 a month from Social
Security. They could be using that to live on.''
</TEXT>
