<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     08-15 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rangoon Reported Calm; Analysts See Little Hope for Dramatic
Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite calls for continued
anti-government demonstrations, returning travelers reported calm
in Burma's capital today. Analysts predicted few dramatic changes
in its authoritarian system.
   Legislative and political party meetings are scheduled on
Friday, presumably to choose a successor to President Sein Lwin,
who resigned last week after violent nationwide demonstrations.
   Travelers returning from Rangoon said throngs of people waited
to withdraw money from the National Bank and others read a list of
the dead and wounded pasted at the entrance of Rangoon General
Hospital.
   ``There were heaps of names,'' said Kate Meehan, a teacher from
Sydney, Australia. On another wall was a cartoon showing a headless
president and vice president with the caption in Burmese reading,
``Burma is being run by no one.''
   By official count, at least 95 people were killed and 240 people
wounded in last week's protests. Unconfirmed reports say hundreds
of people were killed.
   Travelers quoted Burmese as saying they were anxiously awaiting
the Friday party meetings.
   ``There are many things to be done by the new president,'' an
Italian tourist, Antonella Mantica, quoted residents as saying.
   Sein Lwin was widely held responsible for ruthless suppression
of dissent over the past quarter century.
   Leaflets over the weekend had called for more protests for full
democracy from the government, and Japan's Kyodo News Agency had
reported that demonstrations were set for today. But the returning
travelers and Burma's official Radio Rangoon reported no protests.
   In a Bangkok conference on Burma, analysts predicted few
dramatic changes from the 26-year authoritarian rule of Ne Win.
   ``Ne Win will probably pick a second Sein Lwin who will not be
such a hardliner but still do everything commanded by Ne Win,''
said Zaw Wai, a Burma-born businessman and a spokesman for the
large Burmese emigre community in Bangkok.
   Chayachok Chulsiriwongse, a Thai expert on Burma, said he
believed former strongman Ne Win remained as the ``elder
statesman,'' working behind the political scenes.
   Ne Win was succeeded as chairman of the Burma Socialist Program
Party on July 26 by Sein Lwin, a retired army general.
   On July 30, Burma detained 10 people, including a prominent
government critic, Gen. Aung Gyi. Also detained was Sein Win, the
Burmese correspondent of The Associated Press.
   Chayachok and others said a successor to Sein Lwin might be more
acceptable to some Burmese but would be picked from among the top
military or retired military officers who were part of the former
Ne Win hierarchy.
   Students demands have included a multi-party system, restoration
of basic human rights, the release of political prisoners and the
right to set up their own organizations.
   Burma's state-owned official media meanwhile said leaders of
student demonstrations are promising ``to avoid similar acts in the
future.''
   The Guardian newspaper said in its editorial today that it was
``satisfying to see the situation in Rangoon improving day after
day.''
</TEXT>
