<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Brother     08-15 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Brother,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother of Afghan Leader Says Government Cannot Survive Withut
Soviets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Najib and Siddiquallah use one name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rebel brother of Afghan President
Najib said today the communist leader knows he cannot rule
Afghanistan without help from Soviet troops.
   Najib's brother Siddiquallah, 35, met with reporters for the
first time since defecting to Moslem guerrillas 11 months ago. He
arrived in this Pakistani border town this month, reportedly to
seek political asylum in the West.
   ``He (Najib) knows he cannot rule Afghanistan without the
Soviets,'' Siddiquallah told a news conference at the
heavily-guarded headquarters of the Afghan Guerrilla Alliance.
   The news conference was timed to coincide with the Aug. 15
deadline for Moscow's withdrawal of half of its estimated 100,000
troops in Afghanistan. The deadline was set in a U.N.-brokered
accord in April.
   The Kremlin said it had met its deadline. Military officials
said their troops remained only in a few Afghan provinces, mainly
from the capital, Kabul, to the north.
   The rest of the Soviet troops are to be out by Feb. 15, 1989.
The Kremlin began its pullout in May.
   Some Western, Pakistani and guerrilla sources have predicted
Kabul's Communist government will fall quickly after the Soviet
troops leaves. A former Soviet military adviser in Afghanistan,
Maj. Gen. Kim M. Tsagolov, has expressed doubt the Afghan army can
hold its own after the pullout.
   Siddiquallah refused to comment on whether he was seeking asylum
in a third country. But guerrillas who harbored him said he was
trying to obtain entry to the United States.
   The U.S. Embassy in Islamabad declined comment on the report.
   Siddiquallah said he was a committed member of the Communist
Party in the late 1960s, but grew disillusioned over the next
decade as the party became the People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan.
   The party seized power in a bloody 1978 coup, sparking
widespread Moslem resistance. Soviet troops intervened in December
1979, replacing one communist regime with another.
   Sidiquallah said he tried to escape to the West in 1981 but was
drugged in West Germany and hauled back to Afghanistan.
   He said Najib, 43, a physician and former chief of the Afghan
state security police, had him imprisoned in 1987 after failing to
squelch his criticism of the government. He was released a few
months later.
   Siddiquallah said he defected to the Moslem guerrillas in
September 1987.
</TEXT>
