<HEAD>Thunderstorms And Showers Stir Through Much of Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with tornadoes in Florida and
Michigan; PICKS UP 5th graf, `This morning ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms fell on much of the nation today after
damaging winds whipped through southern New England and the Ohio
Valley.
   The storms extended this morning from western New York across
northern Ohio, southern Michigan and northern Indiana, over Florida
and southern Georgia, east, central Louisiana, northeastern North
Dakota and central Arizona.
   A tornado Sunday ripped the roof from a gas station and uprooted
trees in St. Petersburg, Fla., and rough weather from a dying
tropical depression pounded much of Florida. No injuries were
reported.
   On Sunday evening, thunderstorm winds extended from east,
central New York across New Hampshire and northern Massachusetts.
Winds reached 71 mph at Buffalo, N.Y., and damaged trees and power
lines near Hamlin, N.Y.
   In Michigan, winds gusted to near 60 mph across northern
Kalamazoo County. Severe thunderstorms in the state's southern
Lower Peninsula unleashed a tornado that leveled two barns, killed
15 cows and knocked out electricity to thousands, including state
police. There were no injuries.
   This morning, thunderstorm gusts reached 55 mph over northern
Ohio, 60 mph near Lagrange, Ind., and near 60 mph at Tucson, Ariz.
   Heavier rainfall early today included more than an inch at
Lansing, Mich., and Miami.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
through northern New England and northern New York along the South
Carolina and Georgia coast over Florida across the lower Texas Gulf
Coast and over central Arizona.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 90s for much of the
nation; in the 60s and 70s through northern New England and the
central coast of California; in the 70s across much of Washington;
in the 70s and 80s over the rest of northern New England, much of
New York and around Lake Superior; in the 70s and 80s over the
northern plateau, the Great Basin and the Southern Plateau; in the
upper 90s to about 105 degrees over the Plains and the central
Mississippi Valley; and near 110 through the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 89 degrees at
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 fair; Boston 73 hazy; Buffalo 74 showers;
Charleston, S.C. 78 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 74 fair; Cleveland 75
partly cloudy; Detroit 72 cloudy; Miami 76 cloudy; New York 77
fair; Philadelphia 80 fair; Pittsburgh 78 fair; Portland, Maine, 63
foggy; Washington 80 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 70 fair; Chicago 82 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 83 fair; Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 77 fair;
Indianapolis 74 fair; Kansas City 80 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71
fair; Nashville 74 fair; New Orleans 74 fair; St. Louis 83 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 74 partly cloudy; Anchorage 56 cloudy; Las
Vegas 76 fair; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 86 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 68 fair; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 58 cloudy;
Seattle 54 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 66 foggy; Toronto 72 fair.
</TEXT>
