<2ND_LINE>PM-Miracle Service, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilgrims Come to Church for Spiritual, Physical Healing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with service this morning, Picks
up 3rd graf, `On Sunday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Roman Catholic pilgrims
prayed today at a church here in preparation for a service tonight
that many expect to bring miracles of healing.
   Officials estimate more than 20,000 people have journeyed from
across the country to worship at St. John Neumann Catholic Church.
   About 5,000 people attended the first of five rosary services
this morning. Hundreds camped out overnight on a grassy hillside
outside the church, many bringing pillows, coolers and beach
umbrellas. The temperature was expected to hit near 100 degrees
today.
   On Sunday night, a Mass and rosary service was moved outdoors to
accommodate about 2,500 people. Worshipers crowded onto the grassy
slope beneath a huge altar built atop the church office for the
weekend of worship and prayer.
   Rosary services at St. John Neumann, a church built underground,
became the focus of nationwide attention after three parishioners
claimed to have received messages from the Virgin Mary during
weekly rosaries.
   The three, Mike Slate, Mary Constancio and Theresa Werner, said
that Mary told them to expect a miracle on today's Feast of the
Assumption, the day Catholics celebrate the ascension of Mary into
heaven.
   Mrs. Constancio, a former hospital therapist, said she and her
husband quit their jobs to spend more time praying.
   While many handicapped people have come to the church hoping for
physical healing, others said they seek spiritual renewal.
   Roberto Garcia, his wife, niece and 11-year-old son drove from
Fort Morgan, Colo., and attended Sunday's Mass.
   ``My son has been sick a long time,'' Garcia said. ``Last year I
had to carry him in my arms. Now he can walk, but he's still sick.''
   ``Maybe my son can get better,'' he said.
   Cindy Lewis of Miami said she came to strengthen her faith.
``Like they said in church, that so many people would come here to
pray together is a miracle,'' she said. ``It really doesn't matter
what happens.''
   The throng of worshipers Sunday sparked concern from officials
about crowd control for the evening service. Parking lots
surrounding the church were full with the morning Mass crowd, which
police estimated at about 1,300.
   ``I've seen people leave their car in the middle of traffic if
they're late for a (football) kickoff,'' said police Col. Ray
Huffman. ``You can just imagine what would happen if they're late
for a miracle.''
</TEXT>
