<2ND_LINE>PM-Shark Patrols,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Shark Patrols In Six Years Off Stinson Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STINSON BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first shark patrols in six
years continue off Stinson Beach after a great white shark was seen
eating a seal.
   Sharks may be entering the area to feed on sick or dead sea
lions and seals, which have been stricken in an epidemic of a
kidney disease, said Dr. Ray Deiter, a veterinarian with Coast
Watch, which monitors marine mammal life.
   Last week a surfer survived a shark attack near Eureka, about
300 miles north of Stinson, a popular beach just north of San
Francisco.
   Lifegaurds are cruising the area once or twice a day for signs
of sharks, said lifeguard Steve Hills. No sharks have been spotted,
he said.
   The patrols began Wednesday after a fisherman reported seeing a
shark more than 13 feet long feeding about 300 yards off shore,
Hills said. The beach will remain open unless a shark is spotted
closer in, he said.
   No one has ever been attacked by a shark at Stinson, Hills said.
</TEXT>
