<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Morning in America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with convention under way, picks up 8th graf
pvs, The best-known x x x</NOTE>
<HEAD>Early Arrivals Promised Cool Reception At Superdome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republicans, whose only task this week is
to take a foregone conclusion to a foot-stomping anti-climax, found
it necessary today to hold a morning session to start things off.
   This is what they meant by ``Morning in America''?
   There even were delegates in the cavernous Superdome when the
opening gavel fell at 10 a.m., attracted possibly by the routine
business at hand but more likely because the Superdome is the
coolest place in town. The weather in New Orleans is such that
flies have been known to faint from the heat.
   Did the morning session really count since Dan, Tom and Peter
were not peering down from their anchor booths?
   The program, to be charitable, seemed to have come out of files
marked ``Not Ready for Prime Time,'' or, ``America, Isn't It
Wonderful?''
   The schedule was drawn to pay homage to Japanese-Americans,
Hispanic-Americans, College Americans, Black Americans, Teen-age
Americans Female Americans, Jewish-Americans and Americans Abroad.
There also was a salute to youth.
   All this in barely two hours along with the call to order, two
ROTC color guards, the national anthem, the invocation and the
pledge of allegiance led by Soviet expatriate comic Yakov Smirnoff.
   He was introduced by party chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr., as
a man who came to the United States seeking freedom and ``like so
many Americans has given more than he received _ he's given us the
gift of laughter.''
   Smirnoff did his stint and ended with his trademark, ``What a
Country!''
   The best-known of the speakers were Alexander Haig, the former
secretary of state who made it almost to the first primary before
dropping out of the presidential race, and former Gov. Pete du Pont
of Delaware, who pocketed two delegates in the first primary and
then gave up.
   For their efforts, the two men were penciled in for 10:40 a.m.
to 11 a.m., which is about as far out of the spotlight as you can
get at a political convention.
   Maureen Reagan, the outspoken daughter of President Reagan and a
Republican Party stalwart, didn't fare much better: she had an
early starting time, when she could be as blunt as she likes
without offending too many.
   This was all a warm-up for the big finale at high noon: speeches
by candidates for the Senate and House from Virginia, New Jersey,
Tennessee, North Dakota, Vermont, Montana, New York and New Mexico.
   A far piece from prime time? Yes. But you can bet that their
campaign commercials will take full advantage of those clips of
glory. Without showing the clock, of course.
</TEXT>
