<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Bush-VP 4thLd-Writethru a0560 08-15 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Bush-VP, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0560,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naming Of VP May Be Moved Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with fresh quotes, today's activities, subbing 14
grafs for grafs 11-20 pvs, But at ... Thursday; trims at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campaigning for the Republican vice
presidential nomination reached a fever pitch today in this
convention city, as the one-man audience back in Washington _
George Bush _ declared he has still not made up his mind on a
running mate.
   The Republican nominee-to-be stuck to his vow of silence on the
choice, which he described as ``very important'' but not the
decisive factor in the fall election.
   ``No. I have not decided,'' the incumbent vice president said on
ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' ``I probably will say when I have
decided.''
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said a bit later in the
morning that Bush may well have made his decision.
   ``I think he felt like going into this weekend that he had
received the input he wanted to,'' Atwater told reporters.
``Sometime over the weekend _ I include today in the weekend _ he
was going to make his decision before he got down here'' Tuesday
morning.
   Bush said he would be ``making a decision in private and then
presenting it at the appropriate time.''
   The timing for Bush's announcement of his choice may be moved up
from Thursday morning. A source said aides are discussing unveiling
the choice Wednesday night, with Bush and his running mate coming
to the Superdome after Bush formally wins the presidential
nomination that evening.
   Asked if he were leaning toward one person, Bush said: ``Yes, of
course _ but some people I'd say.''
   He brushed aside suggestions from Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New
Hampshire that conservatives could be upset by his decision.
   ``I think my choice will be widely accepted _ when I decide on
who that choice is,'' he said on NBC's ``Today'' show.
   But at the moment, the choice is a mystery, the only one left as
the delegates gathered in the Superdome today for the convention's
start.
   The woman and men on the list of contenders were waiting for the
telephone call from Bush, even as they rushed from reception to
interview to rallies amid the trappings of full-fledged campaigns.
   Those thought to be under consideration included Sen. Bob Dole
of Kansas, Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, former
White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker and Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh.
   Kemp of New York made it crystal clear he wants the job, even as
others took a different tack.
   ``If I were to be asked, I would be a terrific campaigner, and a
terrific candidate and a terrific vice president,'' Kemp said
today. ``But I came here not expecting it, I don't expect it today,
I'm not sitting by the telephone.''
   ``I do not expect to be asked to be vice president. ... I do
expect to help,'' said Mrs. Dole on ``CBS This Morning.''
   Others joked about the call to come.
   ``Communication is very important. In fact, if the system breaks
down, nobody will get a call and Bush will run alone,'' joked Sen.
Dole.
   With both him and his wife on the list of possibilities, their
telephone is especially crucial.
   ``We finally had to leave Washington to come down here so we got
a recording on the machine at home, just in case they got the wrong
number. It just says, `I accept,''' Dole said at a breakfast.
   Quayle, on his way to speak to the Ohio delegation, told
reporters: ``I haven't gotten any phone calls _ except from home.''
   Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming tried to take himself off the list,
saying, ``I would be a liability for George'' in an interview on
NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday.
   But Bush said today that such public statements from prospects
may not indicate he has taken them off his private list. ``I
wouldn't say that at all,'' he said on NBC, ``I haven't made up my
mind yet.''
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, mentioned as a
possibility, flew out of the city Sunday, saying ``If I'm on
anyone's list, it's a list no one's told me about.''
   But Tennessee still was not out of the running. Republican
insiders have been urging Bush to consider former White House Chief
of Staff Baker. The former Tennessee senator was due here today.
   The choice may not be any of these, warned New Jersey Gov.
Thomas Kean, a friend of the vice president. After talking to Bush
on Saturday, Kean said the vice president is thinking about some
other names.
   ``I know there are some people who have not been on those lists
who are still in his mind, so it could be a surprise,'' said Kean,
who will give the convention keynote speech on Tuesday night.
   Dole and Domenici denied seeking the No. 2 spot, while Kemp had
a campaign mini-rally attended by former presidential hopeful Pete
du Pont.
</TEXT>
