<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Mary     08-15 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Mary,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Closes Marian Year With Mass in St. Peter's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II closed the Roman Catholic
Church's Marian Year on Monday with a Mass in St. Peter's Basilica,
exhorting the Virgin Mary to help fight ``the threats which hang
over the entire great human family.''
   About 20,000 people crowded the church for the solemn 2{-hour
ceremony on the Feast of the Assumption, which marks the day the
Virgin Mary was received into heaven.
   The ceremony, broadcast to 24 countries on four continents,
concluded the Marian Year, a period designated by the Polish-born
pontiff for special devotion to the mother of Jesus. The period
began on Pentecost Sunday, June 7, 1987.
   Sunday's liturgy was celebrated in the traditional Latin rite,
but also included chants, hymns and prayers in 16 languages,
including Albanian, Arabic, Russian and Swahili.
   ``Oh Mother ... be always with your children,'' John Paul said
in his homily in Italian. ``Help man, people, nations and humanity
to rise up. Such a cry of the Marian Year resonated in various
places in the world ... which feels in a particularly acute way the
threats which hang over the entire great human family.
   He also underscored the urgency of his last encyclical, ``Social
Concern of the Church,'' which called for action against economic
and social injustices in the world.
   In a separate message at the end of the service, the pontiff
looked ahead to the third millennium.
   ``Today, let us trustfully place the goal of the year 2000 and
the prospects for the third millennium under the watchful
intercession of the Virgin Mary, sister and mother of the church,''
John Paul said.
   The ceremomy also included liturgies from the Eastern churches,
with hymns sung by Syrian, Greek, Albanian and Coptic-rite monks.
One Ethiopian group chanted African songs to the beat of tribal
drums. A group of Sicilian girls in traditional costumes threw
thousands of rose petals on an altar representing the tomb of Mary.
   The Vatican has said Catholics can gain indulgence, or the
pardon of temporal punishment for sin, by devoutly participating in
seminars and special pilgrimages to mark the Marian Year.
   In conjunction with the Marian Year, the pope is scheduled to
release in the next few weeks a major document on the role of women
in society and the church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
