<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea Bjt   08-15 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, Bjt,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Stop Students from Marching to Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL2,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police used tear gas and beatings
Monday to disperse thousands of radical students trying to march to
the border for unification talks with North Korea. At least 1,300
were arrested.
   President Roh Tae-woo told the nation his government will not
tolerate violent campus protest. He said unchecked student activism
would endanger the Olympic Games, which open Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   Officers were seen taking away hundreds of protesters who tried
to march from Seoul to the border truce village of Panmunjom, 35
miles north of the capital, for talks with North Korean student
leaders.
   Witnesses saw dozens of protesters and policmen injured but no
injury statistics were available. Authorities said they arrested
1,300 students but released many after warnings.
   Riot police fired tear gas at Yonsei University in western Seoul
and charged into a crowd of students. They kicked protesters, beat
them and dragged about 200 away.
   In a speech marking the 43rd anniversary of Korea's independence
from Japanese colonial rule, Roh said: ``We cannot any longer
tolerate activities which destroy free democracy, our way of life,''
   He said the Olympics will bring East and the West together, and
``peoples around the world are praying for the success of the
Games. Therefore, the people and the government will not forgive
anyone who spoils the festival through mob action or the throwing
of firebombs, no matter for what plausible cause.''
   Roh delivered a similar warning Friday, accusing radical
students and dissidents of siding with North Korea and trying to
overthrow the government.
   In the speech Monday, he also proposed a summit with President
Kim Il Sung of North Korea to discuss the future of the peninsula,
which was divided at the end of World War II. Similar proposals in
the past have led nowhere, but the two Koreas are considering
parliamentary talks on easing tension.
   A few hours after the speech, thousands of radical students
rallied at Yonsei and tried to march into the streets on their way
to the border.
   Troopers in green combat fatigues and black-visored helmets
fired tear gas and charged the protesters, who shouted ``Unite the
fatherland!'' and ``Yankee go home!''
   Students who did not resist huddled in groups on the ground,
clinging to each other as policemen beat them with fists and even
riot shields.
   Senior officers hit and slapped their own men in an attempt to
stop the beatings. One commander slashed at troopers with a riding
crop.
   Many students apparently decided to let themselves be arrested,
a change from their normal tactic of violent resistance. About 100
members of the ``unification vanguard'' tied themselves together so
police would have to arrest them as a group.
   Among those detained were 12 leaders who were to have
represented South Korea at the talks Monday in Panmunjom.
   Police blocked a similar march to Panmunjom on June 10. About
3,000 radical students tried to march Monday, a much smaller number
than in June, and there was virtually no evidence of public support.
   The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have
seized on national unification in their campaign against the
government.
   South Korean authorities declared Monday's march illegal and
deployed 25,000 riot police in Seoul to stop it. They insist that
all dialogue with North Korea be conducted through government
channels.
   When their march from Yonsei was blocked Monday, students
regrouped on campus and surged out with rocks and firebombs to do
battle for an hour with about 7,000 riot police. Volleys of tear
gas were fired from armored police vans.
   About 600 protesters were arrested downtown and in other parts
of Seoul. In one confrontation in the heart of the capital, 700
students lay down on the pavement with their hands interlocked as
police charged, and 200 were taken away.
   Student leaders told a rally at Yonsei they would not stop
trying to oust the Roh government and reunite Korea. Dozens of
students cut their fingers with razors and wrote four Korean
letters meaning ``national unification'' in blood.
   They denounced the United States, saying Washington supports
military rule in South Korea, and demanded withdrawal of the 42,000
U.S. troops based here under a mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
