<2ND_LINE>PM-Empire State,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Fire In Three Days at Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second fire in three days broke out today in
the 102-story Empire State Building, this time on the 50th floor,
forcing the evacuation of dozens of office workers, the Fire
Department said.
   The fire was brought under control just after noon, about a half
hour after it was reported, but firefighters continued checking all
floors to make sure the flames hadn't spread, said department
spokesman Efrain Parrilla.
   No injuries were reported.
   The cause of the fire was not immediately known.
   The Fire Department said the blaze was in an electrical conduit
in a 50th floor stairwell. However, a building spokesman, Frank
Corbin, said the fire was in trash in a stairwell between the 51st
and 53rd floors.
   Five floors of the building's midsection were evacuated because
of heavy smoke, a spokesman for the management said.
   On Friday, a fire broke out in an 86th floor shaft. After it was
brought under control, firefighters discovered that it had climbed
to the 102nd floor. The observation decks at both those levels were
closed and some 1,500 tourists evacuated.
   That fire also put off the air for several hours eight radio
stations whose antennas are atop the building.
</TEXT>
