<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Glemp     08-15 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Glemp,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Primate Ignores Politics, Blasts Abortion, Pornography</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CZESTOCHOWA, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp on Monday
condemned abortion, pornography and sexual promiscuity in a speech
that ignored the nation's pressing social and economic problems.
   The primate's address to 150,000 pilgrims who had gathered at
the Jasna Gora monastery outside Czestochowa marked a significant
departure from sermons in recent years that have taken Poland's
communist leadership to task on a variety of issues.
   The sermon came three days after Glemp met with Polish leader
Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski to discuss ways to speed up economic and
political reforms.
   Glemp made no reference to the banned trade union Solidarity,
which this month marks the eighth anniversary of the strikes that
launched the outlawed federation, but scores of red-and-white
Solidarity banners covered the iron gates below the monastery.
   A white flag with ``Solidarity'' lettered across it in red was
raised by Warsaw Solidarity activist Seweryn Jaworski. The homemade
banner flew in full view of church dignitaries seated on a
temporary outdoor platform and could be seen by the pilgrims massed
in a field below.
   Throngs of Polish pilgrims from across the nation come together
for the feast day of Our Lady of Czestochowa, regarded as Poland's
patron saint. They huddled under umbrellas for protection from the
heat, but dozens fainted.
   The 14th century monastery is the home of the Black Madonna
icon, an age-darkened painting of the Virgin Mary dating to the 8th
or 9th century which some believers credit with miraculous powers.
It is Poland's most revered religious symbol.
   In the 20-minute sermon, Glemp made no mention of the event many
Poles consider the miracle of the 20th century: the Aug. 15, 1920,
victory by Jozef Pilsudski over the Red Army in a battle known as
the ``miracle on the Vistula,'' referring to the river which cuts
through Warsaw that the Soviets failed to cross.The victory then
saved Poland from Soviet rule.
   Glemp in June attended celebrations marking the 1,000
anniversary of Christianity in the Soviet Union and he hopes to
visit the Soviet Union again, perhaps as early as this fall.
   In the past, Glemp has used the feast day sermon as an occasion
to deliver major Polish church policy statements.
   Last year, the primate urged the Polish government to work
toward establishing diplomatic relations with the Vatican. In 1986,
Glemp warned Polish leaders not to embark on a campaign to teach
atheism in the nation's schools.
   In Monday's sermon, however, Glemp followed church teachings
against abortion, pornography and sexual promiscuity, and urged the
pilgrims to practice ``sexual purity.''
   His strongest attacks were leveled against the practice of in
vitro fertilization and abortion.
   ``Every destruction of joined human cells is the killing of a
human being,'' Glemp said.
   The church estimates that 94 percent of the nation's 37.5
million people are Catholics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
