<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Stolen Trees,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Peasants Raid Forest, Cut Down Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peasants in southern China have cut down and
stolen more than 10,000 trees from a state-run forest since the
beginning of this year, an official newspaper said Monday.
   The Legal Daily said thousands of peasants have entered the
Wugong Mountain forest in Jiangxi province, felling and stealing
trees to be used in construction and for fuel. In one incident in
April, the falling trees injured forest rangers.
   The report said illegal logging has been increasing because
officials fine only the most serious offenders, while others are
asked to write self-criticisms.
   Last year, 247,100 acres of forests in China were destroyed by
illegal logging and $24.5 million in trees stolen, the China Daily
reported in March.
   In a related incident Aug. 6, about 30 farmers were injured when
they tried to stop 20,000 peasants from picking clean a field with
almost $600,000 worth of watermelons, the Legal Daily said.
</TEXT>
