<HEAD>Haig Addresses GOP Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to remove extraneous words</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Haig, a former GOP presidential
candidate, today contrasted George Bush's ``safe and progressive''
policies with those of Michael Dukakis, whom he called the
``diminutive clerk from Massachusetts.''
   In a morning adress to the Republican National Convention, Haig
said Bush would pursue Reagan administration's policies that have
put the United States in a stronger position worldwide.
   Haig, who served as President Reagan's first secretary of state,
dropped out of the Republican presidential race on Feb. 12, four
days before the New Hampshire primary.
   At the time, he endorsed Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas for president
and made little effort to conceal his dislike of Vice President
Bush, the party's designated presidential nominee.
   Today, Haig backed Bush, saying the vice president represented
``safe and progressive change, safe in that George Bush will build
on the solid accomplishments of the Reagan presidency.''
   He said Americans are in a better position now than they were
eight years ago before Reagan was elected.
   ``When I last spoke to a Republican convention in 1980, we saw a
nation thrown off balance by blunder and gloom,'' Haig said.
``Today, eight years later, the policy of peace through strength
has begun to pay off.''
   Haig stressed the differences between Dukakis, the Massachusetts
governor chosen as the Democratic presidential nominee, and his
running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   ``You have to admit Atlanta was good theater,'' Haig said,
referring to the Democrats' convention last month. ``It was an
off-Broadway revival of `The Odd Couple,' starring the diminutive
clerk from Massachusetts and the tall stranger from Texas.
   ``But when you look at the real Dukakis-Bentsen foreign
policies, you have to ask `are they running against us or against
each other?''' The two men differ on some foreign policy issues,
including military aid for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. Dukakis
opposes the aid; Bentsen supports it.
   Haig also compared the Democratic Party to a bat ``flying
erratically for brief periods at low levels and hanging upside down
for extended periods in dark, damp caves up to its navel in guano.''
</TEXT>
