<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Kemp'sCampaign     08-15 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Kemp's Campaign,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp: `I Can Be A Good Second String Quarterback for Bush'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kemp's friends gave him a football
jersey that had the number ``2'' on its back _ not the former
professional quarterback's playing number but the one of the job he
seems to be seeking.
   ``Could I be a good vice president? You bet,'' Kemp, the New
York congressman, said Monday as the Republican National Convention
was opening.
   ``I was a good second string quarterback, and I can be a good
second string quarterback for George Bush.''
   Like the rest of the convention, Kemp is awaiting Bush's word on
a running mate for the Republican ticket this fall.
   Kemp, who dropped out of the race for the Republican
presidential nomination after failing to win a primary, is taking a
highly visible role in New Orleans during the convention _ all the
while insisting he's not campaigning for the vice presidential
nomination, not expecting it, not sitting by the telephone.
   But Kemp's enthusiastically loyal conservative followers have
been campaigning on his behalf, and hundreds of them jammed a New
Orleans hotel Sunday night to cheer wildly his every word and
present the jersey to the former quarterback for the San Diego
Chargers and Buffalo Bills.
   ``Hey, my number was 15,'' he said feigning surprise.
   Speaking to reporters a day later, Kemp said he wasn't
campaigning for the job, while with his usual enthusiasm suggesting
he'd really like it.
   ``If I were to be asked, I would be a terrific campaigner, and a
terrific candidate, and a terrific vice president,'' Kemp said.
``But I came here not expecting it, I don't expect it today, I'm
not sitting by the telephone.''
   ``I'm going to campaign just as vigorously for George Bush off
the ticket as I would on the ticket,'' Kemp said.
   ``If he asks, I would want it. If he doesn't ask ...'' said
Kemp, not finishing his thought.
   Kemp, who likes to deliver a message that combines economic
conservatism with an appeal to broaden the party to include
minorities, never won more than 13 percent of the vote in the
initial Republican primaries. That was in spite of his emergence as
a favorite of many of the party's conservative wing.
   Conservative activists pushing his candidacy point to his
youthful appearance, his appeal to blacks and other minorities, and
to his background in California, where he was born and educated, as
potential boosts to the ticket.
   Some supporters acknowledge, however, that Kemp might not be
best suited to the role of a negative, attacking campaigner if that
is what the Bush campaign decides it wants in a vice president.
   Kemp suggested that himself when he said, ``I do not believe the
purpose of the vice president is to tear down, to diminish, to show
disdain, to show disrespect, to bash.''
   One leading Kemp booster around New Orleans has been Sen. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., who has led a campaign pressuring Bush to pick a
running mate that is from the party's most conservative wing. Kemp
would fill that description.
   ``If Bush was watching tonight, or the Bush operatives, they'd
have to be impressed,'' Humphrey said as he left the huge reception
Kemp sponsored. ``It was almost climactic.''
   With Bush keeping silent on his choice, much of the speculation
has centered around other names. One questioner asked Kemp if it
didn't appear that Bush seemed to be suggesting he wants to pick
someone like Kemp _ but not Kemp himself.
   Kemp's answer recalled Democrat Jesse Jackson's measured
response after he was passed over for the No. 2 spot on that
party's ticket last month.
   ``I am too cool, I'm too collected, I'm too qualified to answer
that question,'' Kemp said. ``Who knows?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
