<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Reforms     08-15 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Reforms,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China to Link Wage Raises With Price Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China soon will give its workers a large raise
and link further pay increases to its inflation rate to stave off
growing unrest in its cities, sources said Monday.
   The move marks a step back from ambitious price reforms
undertaken in the last few years. But the plan still should be
considered a victory for liberal-minded reformers such as Communist
Party leader Zhao Ziyang, the Chinese sources said.
   The sources said Premier Li Peng, Vice Premier Yao Yilin and
other conservatives have called for a freeze on reforms which are
slowly opening the economy to market forces.
   Both sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, recently
attended meetings of top government officials in the resort town of
Bedaihe.
   The sources said the new plan to link pay with price rises would
be announced in about a month.
   ``It will allow the reforms to continue and that is the critical
point,'' said one source.
   He estimated that the average worker's annual salary of $246
would go up at least 8 percent. The other said urban workers could
be getting a 28 percent raise.
   If prices rise, they said, the workers would be given further
wage increases.
   The sources said the pay increases would replace subsidies of
about $2.70 a month that the government has been giving urban
workers to offset inflation, the highest in China's 39-year history
as a communist nation.
   Prices in June were 19 percent higher than they were in June
1987, according to the State Statistical Bureau.
   The inflation has hit urban workers the hardest. Peasants, who
make up 75 percent of China's 1.07 billion people, generally have
missed some price increases because they produce their own food.
   Inflation has been rising in China because the government has
pushed far-reaching economic reforms aimed at ending state controls
over prices and allowing the value of goods to be controlled by the
market.
   In May, the government raised the state-set prices of
vegetables, pork, sugar and eggs by about 60 percent. In late July,
it increased the price of brand-name cigarettes and spirits by as
much as 790 percent.
   The elimination of government-fixed prices has caused the cost
of some goods to soar as the economy fails to keep up with rising
consumer demand.
   In addition, interest rates in Chinese banks are much lower than
the inflation rate, so consumers want to spend now before their
money loses too much value.
   The Chinese sources said that under the plan banks will also
raise their interest rates to encourage saving. The Economic Daily
ran a front-page editorial Monday calling for such a move.
   In May, the official Xinhua News Agency quoted Li Peng and other
Chinese officials as saying riots and other signs of social turmoil
were on the increase in China.
   The sources said that in addition to placating workers, the
goverment was raising salaries to increase worker productivity.
   ``We can't continue with the reforms if the economy isn't
growing,'' said one source.
   The Chinese sources, interviewed separately, described
themselves as members of Zhao's liberal camp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
