<HEAD>DUI-Manslaughter Charges Filed Against U.S. Diver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Olympic diver Bruce David Kimball was
charged with alcohol-related manslaughter today over an auto
accident Aug. 1 that killed two teen-agers and injured six.
   Kimball, 25, a silver medalist in 1984, is in Indianapolis where
the Olympic swimming trials leading up to this year's games in
Seoul, South Korea, are being held.
   The Hillsborough State Attorney's office charged him with two
counts of manslaughter while driving under the influence of alcohol
and three counts of driving under the influence with serious
personal injuries.
   Arraignment is scheduled for Aug. 26.
   Kimball killed two teen-agers, severely injured two and hurt
four more when his speeding car plowed into a crowd at a teen-age
hangout, sheriff's deputies said.
   Kimball admitted drinking at least four beers before the
accident, according to investigators.
   State Attorney Bill James today refused to make public the
blood-acohol test. A motorist with a reading of 0.10 percent is
considered legally drunk in Florida.
</TEXT>
