<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma Bjt   08-15 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, Bjt,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rangoon Quiet; People Search List of Casualties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rangoon was quiet Monday and Burmese
crowded in front of a hospital to search for names of friends and
relatives on a list of the casualties in last week's violence, a
Western tourist reported.
   There were calls for more protest, and Thai officials said
Burmese authorities closed a crossing between Thailand's Ranong
province and the market town of Victoria Point in Burma's
southernmost province of Megui.
   Last week, security forces in Victoria Point were said to have
turned against the authoritarian military government and allowed
thousands of protesters to march unhindered.
   Analysts said they doubted the new Burmese leadership expected
to be chosen Friday will make dramatic changes in the one-party
system Ne Win installed 26 years ago.
   Hard-liner Sein Lwin resigned Friday as Burma's president and
chairman of the Burma Socialist Program Party after five days of
rioting in Rangoon and two dozen other towns and cities across the
Southeast Asian nation. State-run Rangoon radio said the party and
legislature would meet on Friday.
   Ne Win resigned last month and was replaced by Sein Lwin, whose
17 days in office produced a popular uprising against the
quarter-century of repression, economic disaster and isolation.
   Rangoon radio said at least 95 people were killed and 240
wounded last week, but Western diplomats believe the toll was
several times greater. They said it appeared most victims were
unarmed, hit by bullets fired into crowds by soldiers and police.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
the United States was joining an international effort to donate
medical supplies through the International Committee of the Red
Cross.
   Kate Meehan, a teacher from Australia, said she watched people
read a list of casualties Monday that was posted at the entrance of
Rangoon General Hospital. ``There were heaps of names,'' she said.
   Also in front of the hospital compound was a crude shrine
residents built on the spot where they said security forces shot
doctors and nurses. Various sources have confirmed shooting and
casualties in the area, but no reliable details are available.
   Peter Swan, an Australian moviemaker, had told The Associated
Press he visited the hospital Saturday and saw about 300 people who
were wounded in the rioting.
   Ms. Meehan and other Western tourists who arrived Monday from
Rangoon described the city as quiet, with most barricades removed
but the city hall still off-limits. They said people pushed back
barbed-wire barriers and helped clear streets in the Bogyoke market
district.
   Rangoon remains under martial law, imposed Aug. 3, and an 8
p.m.-4 a.m. curfew decreed six days later.
   The state-run radio also reported calm and said student leaders
in some areas reported to authorities for ``pledge-making
ceremonies,'' at which they promised ``to avoid similar acts in the
future.''
   Leaders of the Christian and Hindu communities met Monday with
the deputy minister of home and religious affairs, Kyi Myunt, and
appealed for peace and the rule of law, the radio said. It reported
a similar meeting Sunday involving Islamic leaders.
   On Sunday, Western diplomats reached by telephone in Rangoon
said students were handing out leaflets calling for pro-democracy
protests now that they had achieved the resignation of Sein Lwin, a
former general hated for brutally suppressing dissent during the Ne
Win's rule.
   Student demands include a multiparty system, restoration of
civil rights, release of political prisoners, student unions and
control of inflation.
   Japan's Kyodo news service said Sunday that protests were being
planned for Monday in several major cities.
   Western diplomats and tourists said many Burmese apparently were
waiting to see what leaders emerge from Friday's meetings before
eciding to risk another round of riots.
   Analysts participating in a panel discussion Monday at
Chulalongkorn University in Bangkok were not optimistic about
meaningful change in Burma.
   ``Ne Win will probably pick a second Sein Lwin who will not be
such a hard liner but still do everything commanded by Ne Win,''
said Zaw Wai, a businessman who speaks for Bangkok's large
community of Burmese emigres.
   Chayachok Chulsiriwongse, a Thai scholar, said Ne Win remains as
``elder statesman'' behind the scenes, and Sein Lwin's successor
probably would come from the serving or retired military officers
who formed his hierarchy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
