<HEAD>Dukakis Proposes Cabinet-Level Space Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis, proclaiming that the U.S. space effort has ``lost its
sense of purpose, vision and pride'' under President Reagan, today
proposed the creation of a Cabinet-level post to direct the
nation's space program.
   ``Despite an annual NASA budget of over $10 billion per year,
our space program is in disarray. It suffers from a lack of a
clearly defined purpose and ineffective top management and our
space policy is lost in a maze of bureaucratic committees,''
Dukakis said in a statement issued at a luncheon he attended with
local elected officials and labor and business leaders.
   Dukakis, echoing comments made earlier in the day in Houston by
his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said he would also
back continued development of a permanent manned space station and
would re-establish a Cabinet-level National Aeronautics and Space
Council, to be chaired by Bentsen.
   Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, was in Worcester as part
of a two-day visit to the central part of the state. Arriving here,
Dukakis was met by about 100 protestors, about half anti-abortion
and half opponents of his plan to locate a prison in central
Massachusetts.
   He was also hosting an event marking the start of the first
phase of implementation of Massachusetts' universal health care
law, which will guarantee health insurance to virtually all workers
by 1990.
   Dukakis will spend the night at home in Brookline, outside
Boston, and return to several other central Massachusetts
communities Tuesday.
   On Wednesday, he embarks on a four-day campaign trip, with stops
tentatively scheduled in Florida, Minnesota, Illinois, Missouri,
Arkansas and Texas.
</TEXT>
