<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 08-15 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0556,710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Dukakis comments after 3rd graf pvs,
``We will; subs 6th graf pvs, At that, with name of space council.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen said today that he and running mate Michael Dukakis support
continued development of a permanent manned space station as part
of an ``all-out effort to restore American leadership in exploring
the universe.''
   Bentsen, speaking after a visit to NASA's Houston Spaceflight
Center, said he and Dukakis had discussed the space station in a
Sunday night telephone conversation and that Dukakis had promised
``an intensive review of the space station program in order to
ensure the success of this important effort.''
   ``We will stand behind an all-out effort to restore American
leadership in exploring the universe,'' Bentsen said in the midday
speech, which was made available to reporters beforehand.
   As part of that effort, Dukakis said in Worcester, Mass., that,
if elected, he would create a Cabinet-level position to direct the
nation's space program.
   Dukakis said in a statement that the space program ``suffers
from a lack of a clearly defined purpose and ineffective top
management ... our space policy is lost in a maze of bureaucratic
committees.''
   President Reagan came out for a permanent station in 1984. Under
current plans, the $16 billion station is to be assembled in orbit
beginning in 1995; more than $5 billion in contracts have been
awarded. The House in June approved and sent to the Senate
legislation authorizing spending of $902 million on the station in
the next fiscal year.
   Bentsen, campaigning through Texas while Dukakis is in his home
state of Massachusetts, recalled the early years of the space
effort and said, ``One reason we overcame the initial Soviet lead
in space was good organization and strong leadership.''
   At that time, he said, a Cabinet-level National Aeronautics and
Space Council was established, chaired by the vice president.
   ``Unfortunately, the council was abolished by President Nixon
and (the Reagan) administration vetoed an attempt by Congress to
put in back in business,'' he said, adding:
   ``One of the reasons I accepted Mike Dukakis' offer to be on the
ticket was the understanding he would give the vice president a
major policy role in his administration. We agreed that in a
Dukakis-Bentsen administration the space council would be
reinstated and I would serve as chairman.''
   The timing of the announcement in Houston gave Bentsen an
opportunity to promise more jobs and more federal spending for his
home state, which will be a major battleground in the fall campaign.
   ``My friends, that nails it down,'' Bentsen said. ``There should
be no doubt in Houston or anywhere else in the world where a
Dukakis-Bentsen administration will stand in space.''
   From Houston, Bentsen was scooting across the state line into
Arkansas for a rally in Little Rock and then returning to Beaumont,
Texas, for a rally.
   He spent Sunday resting with a visit to his father's home near
McAllen, Texas. Reporters were kept away, but Bentsen spokesman
Mike McCurry said the major event was a gin rummy game won, as
usual, by the 94-year-old Lloyd Bentsen Sr.
   Besides recharging the 67-year-old senator's batteries, the stop
underlined the campaign's effort to point out that Bentsen is a
native Texan. Vice President George Bush, who receives the
Republican nomination this week, claims Texas as his home but was
raised in New England.
   Dukakis plans to join Bentsen in the state later in the week,
and Bentsen points out that before he was on the ticket the
Republicans were cocky.
   ``They thought they had this state locked up,'' he told
reporters.
   Bentsen speaks confidently of winning Texas and Houston, the
city both he and Bush have called home.
   ``I think we'll carry Houston, sure do,'' he said.
   Bentsen beat Bush in Texas once before, in the 1970 election
that first put him in the Senate. He chuckled when reporters asked
if he was concerned now that Bush was moving part of his national
campaign organization to the state.
   ``No, it doesn't worry me,'' he said. ``He's had his operations
here before.''
   Bentsen is running parallel campaigns for the vice presidency
and for re-election to his Senate seat. The dual candidacies are
allowed under an unusual Texas law.
</TEXT>
