<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolPartnerships     08-15 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Partnerships,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foundation Announces $300,000 Grants to Foster School-College
Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Life Foundation announced
Monday it is distributing $300,000 in grants to foster partnerships
between five colleges and public schools and thereby enhance
teacher programs.
   The foundation was established in 1976 by the Metropolitan Life
Insurance Co. to distribute grants to education, health and civic
groups. Over the past three years, the foundation has distributed
more than $772,000 to foster partnerships between colleges and
public schools.
   ``We're convinced that programs to bring college and university
faculty into partnerships with teachers from local public schools
enhances collegiality and encourages creativity in solving
important educational problems,'' said Sibyl Jacobson, the
foundation's president.
   The new awards included:
   _ $71,000 to Florida Memorial College and Miami Northwestern
Senior High School to establish a new partnership between the
college's faculty and the public school's parents and teachers to
develop new teaching techniques to help curb the dropout rate.
   _ $71,000 to Fordham University Graduate School of Education and
District 10 Prep School in New York to help graduate student social
workers and classroom teachers to identify potential junior high
school dropouts.
   _ $69,000 to Lawrence Hall of Science-University of California
at Berkeley and Richmond Unified School District for a program to
recruit senior citizen volunteers to teach 720 students in small
groups.
   _ $39,000 to Montclair State College and the Newark, N.J.,
public school system to include college faculty, public school
teachers, parents and elementary school children in home and school
activities aimed at fostering reading and academic skills.
   _ $50,000 to SUNY College at Brockport, N.Y., and School No.
6-Rochester City School District, N.Y., to support the Genessee
River Valley project, a curriculum designed by teachers at the
public school which uses the nearby river as the starting point for
interdisciplinary study.
</TEXT>
