<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Robinson, star of Fox Television's ``21
Jump Street,'' is not coy in explaining how she got her break in
show business.
   ``Pure nepotism,'' she says in the Aug. 20 issue of TV Guide.
   Miss Robinson was referring to assistance from her mother,
Dolores, one of Hollywood's top personal managers, and her father,
Matt, who played Gordon on ``Sesame Street'' and is a head writer
for ``The Cosby Show.''
   The 23-year-old actress, who studied at the Sorbonne in Paris
and speaks four languages, has had only one previous role, as LeVar
Burton's sister in the movie ``Dummy.''
   She would like a singing career, but her only stints so far have
been singing ``The Star Spangled Banner'' at Los Angeles Dodgers
baseball games and Seattle Seahawks football games.
   ``They wanted Whitney Houston, but they couldn't afford her, so
I decided to take her leftovers,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackie Collins, the queen of romance fiction,
says her yen for steamy stories began at an early age when she
routinely ditched her schoolbooks for Harold Robbins and Mickey
Spillane novels.
   ``When I was about 8, I would copy dirty limericks into my diary
and charge all the girls in school a few pence to read them,'' says
the London-born author of ``Hollywood Wives'' and ``Rock Star.''
   Her ``bad girl'' reputation was well earned, the sister of
actress Joan Collins said in the September issue of Glamour
magazine. ``I'd play truant for literally months at a time,
sneaking off to coffee bars in Soho, and, of course, to the movies.
   ``At 15 I was expelled _ for truancy, for smoking and for waving
at the neighborhood flasher,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Charles R. Vaughan found out he
would be portrayed by Oscar-winning actor George C. Scott in a
television movie, his own stock shot up dramatically.
   ``I can't walk down the street, I can't eat at a restaurant,''
said Vaughn, a Lafayette attorney. ``The response is constant. It's
always, `Hey, George!'''
   The film on AIDS victim Ryan White will air on ABC later this
year. Vaughn represented the teen-ager in his successful battle to
attend a Kokomo-area school. White soon left Kokomo because of
lingering bitterness and moved to Cicero.
   Vaughn said he is gratified by the interest Scott has shown in
the case. ``The producers said he knew all about the Ryan White
story. He said this was a part he wanted,'' Vaughn said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip
met with some 40 survivors and relatives of the worst oil rig
disaster in history, but their visit Monday was marred by the
injuries of two seamen trying to guide the royal yacht into harbor.
   A deck hand was admitted to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary for chest
and abdominal bruising and a harbor pilot was treated and released,
police said. The two had gotten caught between the yacht and their
pilot vessel as the boats pitched in rough seas.
   The queen was asleep at the time and the yacht Britannia docked
safely. Later Elizabeth and her husband talked with those involved
in the July 6 tragedy in which 167 men lost their lives.
   The couple then headed for Balmoral Castle, the royal summer
retreat in the Scottish Highlands, where they will see their fifth
grandchild for the first time.
   The Princess of York, the first child of the queen's second son
Prince Andrew and his wife Sarah, was born Aug. 8 in London. The
baby's name is expected to be made public after receiving approval
from the queen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former police detective Eddie Egan,
who helped crack the French Connection heroin ring that was the
basis for an Academy-Award winning movie, said a sequel he's
planning will be even more intriguing.
   A movie company he's formed, he said, will tell how the 112
pounds of heroin seized in the 1962 bust was stolen from New York
police vaults.
   Egan's role in cracking the heroin trafficking scheme was
portrayed by Gene Hackman in ``The French Connection.''
   Egan retired from the police force in 1971 and became a
character actor in such TV and movie stories as ``Badge 373,''
``Police Story,'' and ``Joe Forrester.''
   Filming on the $8 million movie will start in Fort Lauderdale in
the fall, Egan told the Fort Lauderdale News and Sun-Sentinel.
</TEXT>
