<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre     08-15 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lefebvre Followers, Church Loyalists March in Dueling Processions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholics loyal to the Vatican and followers
of rebel archbishop Marcel Lefebvre organized competing processions
Monday, each attracting about 5,000 faithful to renew France's
350-year-old vow of consecration to the Virgin Mary.
   Carrying statues and banners of the Virgin, and chanting ``Hail
Marys'' _ the loyalist group in French, the traditionalists in
Latin _ the two sets of marchers added color to downtown streets on
the Assumption Day holiday, one of the quietest days of the year in
France.
   Parisians and tourists at sidewalk cafes turned to watch the
processions and puffs of incense.
   This was the third year of dueling processions on Aug. 15, but
the competition was sharpened this year by the recent schism and
excommunication of Lefebvre for consecrating bishops without
permission from Pope John Paul II.
   It also drew added attention because Monday was the 350th
anniversary of King Louis XIII's vow of France's loyalty to the
Virgin. It is celebrated on Assumption Day, which marks the day
Mary was received into heaven.
   Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, the archbishop of Paris, led the
official ceremony at Notre Dame Cathedral.
   Across the Seine River in the Latin Quarter, the traditionalist
procession was led by Monsignor Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, one
of the four bishops Lefebvre consecrated in a ceremony June 30 at
Econe, Switzerland.
   Lefrebvre was excommunicated for going through with the
consecrations without papal permission, creating the church's first
schism in more than a century.
   ``Those who remain faithful to Monsignor Lefebvre will stay in
the path of grace,'' Tissier de Mallerais said before the
procession left the church of St. Nicolas du Chardonnet. ``Those
who do nor remain faithful will lose this grace.''
   The 17th century church, in the ancient Latin Quarter a few
short blocks from Notre Dame, has been occupied since 1977 by
traditionalist worshipers and priests who follow Lefebvre in
rejecting such church reforms as Mass said in modern languages
instead of Latin.
   Lustiger has taken steps recently to try to appeal to the
traditionalists, including establishing the Assumption Day
procession three years ago, following their example. He also said
Mass in Latin at Notre Dame, and said the traditional Latin Mass
would be used in three Paris churches each Sunday.
   ``It's an effort to co-opt people,'' said Jean-Baptiste
Chaumeil, one of the marchers in the traditionalist procession.
``It shows a hypocrisy. The French bishops have always been against
Monsignor Lefebvre and tried to make sure the negotiations with
Rome would fail.''
   At the halfway point of their procession, at the ruins of the
Roman arena of Lutece, there was a caged lion, which organizers
said was intended to evoke the martyrdom of early Christians and
symbolize the plight of Lefebvre's followers.
   Police estimated the traditionalist procession at about 5,000
people.
   Roughly the same number were gathered at the same time in
late-afternoon sunshine in the square in front of Notre Dame
Cathedral.
   Huge banners decorated the famous facade, including one
multicolored representation of the Virgin holding the Christ child
that was hung between the Western towers.
   Church officials said it reproduced a tapestry said to have hung
in Notre Dame in 1638, when King Louis XIII dedicated the nation to
Mary.
   Another banner reproduced the king's words: ``We believed
ourselves obliged to consecrate our person and our state to the
grandeur of God.''
   The processions also were linked to ceremonies worldwide marking
the end of the Roman Catholic Church's Marian Year, a period
designated by the pope for special devotion to the mother of Jesus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
