<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeResigns     08-15 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Resigns,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Of Few Black Female Federal Judges Returns To Private Practice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge stepped down from the bench
Monday to return to private legal practice, leaving fewer than a
dozen black women among the nation's federal trial judges.
   U.S. District Judge Gabrielle McDonald said she considered that
statistic when deciding to leave the bench after nine years.
   ``One of the most pressing concerns I have is my race and my
sex, because I know I have brought to the bench a different
perspective,'' she said. ``The federal judiciary is an institution,
and an institution should reflect society.''
   However, she said: ``I think I've done all I can do here. For
me, it's time to move on.''
   A desire to return to private practice, rather than
philosophical considerations, prompted her to leave the bench.
   ``I'm not so much leaving, but resuming what I did the years
before I came here,'' Mrs. McDonald said. ``I want to practice
quality law.''
   But she also cited overloaded dockets and lack of support
services as reasons for returning to private practice. She said
budget cutbacks had left each federal judge in Houston struggling
to handle more than 1,000 cases without enough employeees or
adequate computer systems to handle the work.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, now the Democrats' vice presidential
nominee, recommended Mrs. McDonald for a federal judgeship when she
was a lawyer handling employment discrimination cases.
   ``I feel very, very loyal to Senator Bentsen,'' she said. ``For
him to appoint me when I had a reputation for suing on behalf of
minorities _ that took courage.''
   Mrs. McDonald was sworn in May 31, 1979, whens she was 37, and
became the first black and the third woman to assume a federal
judgeship in Texas.
   Her race came into play in several of her cases.
   The grand dragon of the Ku Klux Klan in 1981 asked her to step
aside in a lawsuit brought by Vietnamese shrimpers who claimed they
were being harassed by Klan members.
   Mrs. McDonald refused the request, pointing out that the grand
dragon had never heard her express a personal opinion about the
Klan.
   Her race became an issue again when she presided over a dispute
about attorneys' fees in a package of voting rights lawsuits
brought against the city of Houston. The suits eventually led to
changes in the way the City Council is elected.
   The city asked her to step down from the case in 1984, saying
that as a black she was a plaintiff in the class-action suits filed
on behalf of Hispanic and black voters.
   Mrs. McDonald refused to bow out and her decision was upheld by
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   ``If the 5th Circuit had not affirmed, I expect I would have
left the bench then; that's how important it was,'' she said. ``A
decision not to affirm would have rendered me a second-class
citizen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
