<1ST_LINE>u p PM-WyoBallots     08-15 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wyo Ballots,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wyoming Locked In Battle With Justice Department Over Absentee
Ballots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming officials today refused to
acknowledge the state violated federal election laws in its
handling of absentee ballots, setting up a showdown in court
against the U.S. government.
   At issue is when the state's county clerks mailed out absentee
ballots for Tuesday's primary elections.
   Some counties sent the ballots just 26 days before the election;
the U.S. Justice Department prefers that ballots be sent at least
30 days in advance.
   Wyoming officials today said they refused to sign a Justice
Department stipulation saying they violated the law and agreeing to
count any ballots received through Aug. 22, six days after the U.S.
Senate and House primaries.
   ``We are not going to enter into a consent order,'' said Wyoming
Secretary of State Kathy Karpan.
   She said she expected the Justice Department to go into federal
court later today to obtain a court order imposing the six-day
extension.
   State officials believe fewer than 1,000 absentee ballots are at
stake.
   Karpan and state Attorney General Joseph Meyer said they do not
believe the state violated any election laws.
   ``There is no set date in the statute that says (absentee
ballots must be mailed) so many days (before a primary),'' said Ms.
Karpan. ``There are no rules and regs ... so we're not so sure that
we're not in compliance.''
</TEXT>
