<HEAD>Divided in Primary, Husband-Wife Delegate Team Finds Common Ground</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United in marriage but divided by politics,
Illinois GOP delegates Carl and Karen Hawkinson say George Bush's
choice of a running mate could end their friendly disagreement.
   Hawkinson, 40, a state senator from Galesburg, was elected as a
delegate for Kansas Sen. Bob Dole. Mrs. Hawkinson, 35, the county
GOP chairwoman, got her ticket to New Orleans as a Bush delegate.
   Now, both agree Dole would make a top-flight running mate.
   ``I think we're close,'' Hawkinson said Monday.
   Their most memorable piece of political pillow talk was a
late-night phone call from Lee Daniels, Dole's Illinois campaign
chairman, a few days before the March 15 primary.
   ``We were talking about strategy for Dole coming to Galesburg,''
Hawkinson said. ``And after all of this, he said, `Don't tell
Karen.'
   ``And I said, `Well, Lee, she's been lying here listening to the
whole thing, but I'm sure she won't report it.''
   ``And I didn't,'' Mrs. Hawkinson added.
