<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Anti-SmokingAds     08-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Smoking Ads,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ad Agency Loses State's Anti-Smoking Account Over Tobacco Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State health officials have canceled a $1.7
million contract with an ad agency to produce youth-oriented,
no-smoking commercials because the agency merged with another which
has a tobacco company account.
   The incident ``shows how long the tentacles of the tobacco
industry are,'' said Kathy Harty, manager of the state Health
Department's section on nonsmoking and health.
   The Campbell-Mithun agency, based in Minneapolis, recently
merged with New York-based William Esty, which has a $35 million
account with Brown & Williamson Tobacco Co.
   Campbell-Mithun, which had a two-year contract with the state,
developed and produced television and radio spots that have been
broadcast regularly around the state since January. One shows
students falling over, domino-fashion, from the bad breath of a
teen-age girl smoker. Another highlights the smelly odor left in
smokers' clothes.
   The campaign, rather than focusing on long-term health risks of
smoking, emphasized the lowered personal attractiveness and social
isolation of the smoker.
   The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services recently began
airing animated public service ads with a similar tone,
characterizing smokers as ``buttheads'' and pariahs.
   Harty said Friday that Campbell-Mithun would be replaced by the
Martin-Williams agency of Minneapolis for at least two years.
   The contract with Campbell-Mithun had just been renewed when its
merger with Esty was announced last month, she added.
   The Campbell-Mithun advertisements have been ``very effective,''
Harty said, based on measurements of audience reach and recall.
   Campbell-Mithun made deft use of the state's limited
media-buying budget, obtaining a significant number of free spots
along with those it bought, she said.
   Paula Baldwin, a spokeswoman for what now is Campbell-Mithun
Esty, said the move ``was an extremely difficult decision to reach,
but it was an amicable one. We remain very, very proud of the work
we did.''
   Esty and the former Campbell-Mithun agencies are owned by the
New York-based Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Inc.
   Mary Gustafson, a Martin-Williams spokeswoman, said the agency's
projections indicate very little likelihood of landing a
tobacco-linked account.
   ``Even if it should happen, we've made a commitment to (the
Health Department's) section on nonsmoking,'' she said. ``We'd ask
(the prospective client) to understand, but it they didn't we'd
probably not pitch for their business.''
</TEXT>
