<DOCNO> AP880815-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1545EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--EndOfAnEra Bjt   08-15 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--End Of An Era, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan a Hard Act to Follow, Really Loves His Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one can say that we'll never see the likes
of him again, but Ronald Reagan will be a hard act for any
president to follow.
   The man actually enjoys the job.
   Other presidents pursued the office with equal ardor, but none
has savored it the way Reagan does.
   Harry Truman used to refer to the White House as ``that great
white prison,'' yet he had the luxury in those safer times of
taking a walk around the block. By contrast, Reagan is swaddled in
a germ-free cocoon and hasn't seemed to mind. If he were to write a
book, you can bet it won't be about the splendid misery of it all.
   That aura of comfort in the job invited a comment from delegate
James Proctor from Rocky Mount, N.C., that you hear often around
the Republican National Convention: ``I don't think there's anybody
here who wouldn't like to have Ronald Reagan on the ticket again.''
   George Bush _ and, for that matter, Michael Dukakis _ eat your
heart out.
   Everything about Reagan shows his pleasure with the best role of
his actor's life. It's in his body language. He bounds onstage for
speeches; he looks interested in the other guy's speech; he laughs
at every punch line. His wave to crowds is never forced. Amiability
is his strong suit.
   He has turned his age to advantage with endless variations of
the same one-liner. ``I always feel at home here in Louisiana
because, you know, I'm the fellow that talked Tom Jefferson into
buying it,'' he said at a rally welcoming him to New Orleans on
Sunday. It got a laugh; it always does.
   Where other presidents were renowned for their inability to make
small talk _ Richard Nixon comes to mind _ Reagan is the kind of
man you'd like at your dinner party. He is a natural quipster and
never more so than on the day he was shot.
   As he was wheeled into the operating room, he told Nancy,
``Honey, I forgot to duck.'' To his doctors: ``Please tell me
you're all Republicans.'' and, en route to the recovery room, ``All
in all, I'd rather be in Philadelphia.''
   Politics aside, Americans like a man like that. He is the movie
cowboy blowing the smoke away from his gun barrel, John Wayne
striding across the shot-up deck of his destroyer, Will Rogers
finding humor in the serious business of politics.
   George Bush was a real war hero, but he's derided as the wimp.
Reagan's the tough guy who spent his war years making movies for
the Army.
   Franklin D. Roosevelt developed a rapport with the American
people by extolling optimism in a dark time. Reagan has taken pages
out of FDR's book, ridiculing the malaise that Jimmy Carter talked
about. ``A New Beginning,'' was his campaign slogan in 1980. ``It's
Morning in America,'' was the refrain in 1984.
   Who else could get away with the things Reagan does? He and his
wife speak freely of family values when their own family is torn.
His reputation is that of a religious man, yet he seldom goes to
church. He is caught red-handed with faulty facts, misstatements,
admission of ignorance of his administration's doings and he walks
away with head held high.
   It is, as Rep. Pat Schroeder said, a Teflon presidency where
nothing sticks.
   Far from being a drawback, Reagan's actor background has helped
him mold public opinion. No matter what he says, it sounds good
when he says it. Television is his medium. He handles it better
than anyone since John F. Kennedy.
   Used to taking orders from directors in his earlier career,
Reagan has surrounded himself with aides to whom he delegates much
authority. That enables him to be what he said he would be, a
9-to-5 executive who does not take work home.
   He came in to the White House with solidly rooted ideas and it
has been both an attribute and a flaw that he sticks with them no
matter what. His off-the-cuff public statements often draw on the
3-by-5 cards he used during his political infancy in the 1960s and
even before when he honed his conservative views as a company
spokesman for General Electric.
   Reagan is the 40th American president, the first actor, the
first divorced man, and the oldest ever. His administration was
tainted by scandal, by the Iran-Contra affair, by budget deficits,
by curtailment of programs.
   None of that necessarily will be stressed by history. What will
be remembered is Ronald Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
