<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Bingham     08-15 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Bingham,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media Family Patriarch Dies at 82</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Bingham Sr., the patriarch of a
media empire that he sold in 1986 to end a family squabble over
control of the holdings, died Monday at age 82.
   The former owner and publisher of The Courier-Journal and The
Louisville Times had undergone treatment in Boston and Louisville
hospitals since learning he had a brain tumor late last year. His
doctor said Bingham had been in a coma for the past nine days.
   Bingham, whose newspapers won eight Pulitzer Prizes, sold the
two papers in 1986 to Gannett Co., which folded the Times into The
Courier-Journal.
   Many public figures praised Bingham's journalistic and financial
contributions to Kentucky.
   ``He was one of our commonwealth's treasures,'' said former Gov.
A.B. ``Happy'' Chandler, who had his share of feuds with The
Courier-Journal during his half-century in public life.
   ``He was respected for his character, integrity, fair-mindedness
and benevolence of spirit by those on every side of the
controverisal issues of the day,'' said Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky.
   ``The tradition he established serves as a continuing memorial
to his high sense of journalistic responsibility,'' said George N.
Gill, president and publisher of The Courier-Journal.
   Dr. William A. Blodgett, Bingham's personal physician, said he
was with Bingham when he died at home at 5:15 a.m. ``He had a
seizure last weekend, and we believed the tumor was growing
again,'' the doctor said.
   Bingham served as president and publisher of The Courier-Journal
and The Louisville Times from December 1937 until June 1971, when
his son Barry Jr. took over the reins and he became board chairman.
   Since the sale of the media properties _ including the two
papers, a TV station and a printing company, reportedly for $435.8
million _ Bingham had exercised his influence through the Mary and
Barry Bingham Sr. Fund.
   Bingham and his wife established the philanthropic organization
to support education, arts and health endeavors in Kentucky and
southern Indiana. It had distributed more than $8 million by late
last year.
   One of the fund's largest gifts was $2.6 million for the
construction of the 40-story Louisville Falls Fountain, the world's
largest floating fountain, which will be dedicated Friday.
   Bingham placed the media properties on the market in January
1986 after nearly two years of family infighting. He said he
couldn't find a solution that was fair to everyone.
   His illness came as he unsuccessfully fought the release of a
controversial book about his father, Judge Robert Worth Bingham,
who had acquired the newspapers in 1918 with a $5 million
inheritance from his second wife.
   The book alleged that the elder Bingham contributed to his
second wife's death by failing to secure proper medical attention
for her and by drugging her to try to persuade her to change her
will.
   Macmillan Publishing Co. dropped the book project after Bingham
supplied a 5-inch thick memorandum of what he contended were 160
misstatements of fact by author David Chandler. Crown Publishing
Co. issued the book in 1987 after making what it called
insignificant changes.
   The Louisville-born Bingham graduated from Harvard with honors
in 1928, eventually abandoning his dream of becoming a novelist and
joining the newspaper as a police reporter. He took control of the
media empire in 1933 when President Franklin Delano Roosevelt
appointed his father ambassador to Great Britain.
   Judge Bingham had launched WHAS-AM radio in 1922 and later
started Standard Gravure, which prints Sunday magazine and
advertising supplements. Barry Bingham Sr. set up WHAS-TV in 1950;
Barry Bingham Jr. was involved in opening WAMZ-FM.
   Dissension within the family surfaced in 1984 when Sallie
Bingham challenged the ability of her brother to serve as editor
and publisher.
   Sallie Bingham, her sister Eleanor Bingham Miller and their
mother were replaced on the board of directors by professional
managers. Sallie Bingham then announced she was disposing of her 15
percent interest. That eventually led to Bingham's surprise
announcement that he was dismantling the empire.
   In addition to his wife and three children, Bingham is survived
by nine grandchildren. Two other sons died in accidents, in 1964
and 1966.
   A funeral service is scheduled for Wednesday at Calvary
Episcopal Church in Louisville.
  
</TEXT>
