<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Australia     08-15 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Australia,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speaker To Return 45 Years After Combat Tour, This Time Leading
Delegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-five years after Jim Wright flew a
daring World War II bombing mission from a remote Australian
airfield, the speaker of the House is going back _ this time as the
leader of a congressional delegation celebrating the country's
bicentennial.
   ``For me it will be a sentimental journey,'' Wright said,
remembering the 17 hours spent flying over the South Pacific in a
stripped-down B-24 and the midnight bombing of refineries at
Balikpapan, Borneo, where much of Japan's aviation fuel was being
produced.
   The Texas Democrat was a 19-year-old second lieutenant in the
Army Air Corps when he and Capt. Gus Connery flew the lead plane in
the 2,700-mile mission and suprised the Japanese, who had left the
lights on in the harbor at Balikpapan because they thought the
refineries were beyond the range of American bombers.
   On this trip Down Under, he hopes to ``demonstrate to Australia
our appreciation for their steadfast friendship.''
   A meeting with Prime Minister Bob Hawke is on Wright's
itinerary, as the speaker, his wife, Betty, and about a dozen
members of Congress and their spouses attend ceremonies to
inaugurate the new Parliament House in the capital of Canberra.
   The delegation leaves Friday and returns to the United States on
Aug. 31, said Wright, who is organizing the bipartisan group at the
request of the State Department and William Lane, U.S. ambassador
to Australia.
   While in Canberra, Wright and the delegation will attend the
first session of Parliament in the new building and meet with
leaders of the ruling Labor Party and of the opposition party. The
U.S. lawmakers will visit the Australian War Memorial and the
Australian-American War Memorial, and Wright will lay a wreath on
each.
   The Australian air force will fly Wright to Fenton air strip in
the rugged Northern Territory, where he spent much of his combat
tour.
   ``I'll go back for this sentimental journey,'' he said,
reminiscing about the time as a young soldier he bought a wild
horse from a nearby rancher for $48 and fed the animal with oats
intended for his comrades' breakfast.
   He was awarded the Distinguished Flying Cross for his valor in
the bombing of the Balikpapan oil refineries, at the time the
longest bombing mission on record. His plane was the first to
arrive over the refineries and the lights immediately went out when
he dropped his bombs.
</TEXT>
