<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Zaccaro     08-15 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zaccaro,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Seeks Review of Program That Allows Zaccaro to Live in
Luxury Digs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MR1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin has asked for a
review of a state corrections program that has allowed John Zaccaro
Jr. to spend his four-month prison term for selling cocaine in a
$1,500-a-month apartment.
   Louis Berney, a spokesman for the governor, said Monday Kunin
believes the overall program is outstanding but that she is
concerned about inequities in living accommodations among
participants.
   Zaccaro, the son of former Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro, was convicted in April of selling a
quarter-gram of cocaine to an undercover officer while a student at
Middlebury College in 1986. He was sentenced to one to five years
in prison, with all but four months suspended.
   Zaccaro was deemed eligible for the state Corrections
Department's ``house arrest'' program, under which non-violent
convicts can find their own housing while they remain under close
supervision by corrections officials. The program is designed to
ease prison overcrowding.
   Zaccaro is staying in a luxury apartment with room service and
cable TV in a building designed for expense-account business people
on short assignments.
   ``This guy is a drug felon and he's living in conditions that
99.9 percent of the people of Vermont couldn't afford,'' said
Addison County State's Attorney John Quinn, who prosecuted the
24-year-old Zaccaro.
   State corrections officials say they have no control over the
quality of the living quarters. ``The department doesn't provide
the apartment,'' said John Perry, director of planning for
corrections. ``The prisoner does that. We are only concerned that
it meets minimum standards _ no drugs, no guns, no college kids
hanging around.
   ``Obviously, some people, Mr. Zaccaro among them, have more
money than others, and they can afford a better place. The Aga Khan
probably wouldn't think much of his apartment,'' he said.
   ``The governor believes poeple should be treated equally
regardless of personal circumstances,'' so has asked for the
review, said Berney. He said Kunin had no suggestions for solving
the inequities.
   There are a host of problems in trying to regulate the standard
of living quarters. For example, some of the participants live at
home, raising the question of whether the state would force people
from their homes if they seem too luxurious.
   Berney said it was important to remember Zaccaro ``does not have
freedom in any sense of the word. He works most of the time, and is
restricted to his apartment for the rest of the time, with the
exception of one hour a week in which he has to go grocery
shopping.''
   Zaccaro works at a community youth center in Burlington.
   ``He gets a personal visit a day and two phone calls a day from
an officer. He is very closely monitored,'' said Berney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay     08-15 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stroessner Takes Oath of Office for Eighth Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Stroessner took the
oath of office for an eighth time Monday in a subdued ceremony that
followed weeks of tension between the government and the Roman
Catholic Church.
   Stroessner, 75, was sworn in before the congress by the
president of the Supreme Court, Luis Maria Argana. He then quietly
walked off the podium without speaking to assembled representatives
and foreign dignitaries.
   The 25-minute ceremony was broadcast by state-run radio across
this landlocked and mostly rural country of 3.8 million.
   Although there were no protests, the Catholic Church canceled
the annual Te Deum mass of thanksgiving traditionally celebrated on
Aug. 15 to mark the anniversary of the founding of the capital,
Asuncion.
   The cancellation, ordered by Monsignor Ismael Rolon, archbishop
of Asuncion, was a response to the expulsion July 25 of a Spanish
Jesuit priest for allegedly publicly encouraging overthrow of the
government.
   The church denied the charge and said the priest, Juan Antonio
de la Vega, a 65-year-old professor, was explaining Liberation
Theology, a movement that advocates political change as a tool of
social reform.
   The church, the most influential institution in the country
after the government and the military, claimed in a message
delivered from pulpits two weeks ago that it was the victim of
persecution.
   Pope John Paul II urged Stroessner during a visit here last May
to relax restrictions on human rights and political freedom.
Stroessner, also commander of Paraguay's military, took power in a
1954 coup and has ruled with a heavy hand ever since.
   His tenure has brought order and modest economic growth to a
country that had seen turmoil and 11 different presidents in the 19
years following the end of the Chaco War with Bolivia in 1935. But
most civil liberties are curtailed and dissent is crushed.
   Stroessner won an eighth term in February in an election marked
by the absence of the major opposition groups, and by charges of
fraud. He was credited with obtaining 88.6 percent of all votes
cast.
   Monday's inauguration was witnessed by Brazilian Foreign
Minister Roberto de Abreu Sondre, Taiwan's Prime Minister Yu Kuo
and delegations from South Korea, South Africa and neighboring
Argentina.
   Afterward, Stroessner swore in his 11-member Cabinet. Rodney
Elpidio Acevedo replaced Carlos Saldivar as foreign minister.
</TEXT>
