<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Iran     08-15 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Iran,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Meets Iranian Foreign Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi met with Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and praised Iran and Iraq for
agreeing to end their war, the Libyan news agency JANA reported
Monday.
   Velayati left Libya Monday after a visit.
   The dispatch from Tripoli, the Libyan capital, did not specify
when or where the two met.
   Col. Gadhafi ``lauded the stances of both Iran and Iraq for
ending the war, calling for the necessity of directing all the guns
against the common Zionist enemy,'' JANA said in a report monitored
in Rome.
   Gadhafi said Libya ``is ready to respond to any sign from the
two sides to solve any complications that may arise in the future.''
   Velayati said Gadhafi had praised Iran's acceptance of U.N.
Resolution 598, which calls for a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war.
Velayati quoted Gadhafi as calling it a ``wise action for ending
the war,'' according to a report from Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency, monitored in Libya.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced the
cease-fire last week, and said it would take effect Aug. 20.
