<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0660 08-15 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0660,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Warn Pakistan; Rebels Take District Near Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inserts 1 graf after 10th `Soviet military' with casualty figures
form Tass and Najib</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin said Monday it will not tolerate more
Pakistani aid to Moslem guerrillas in Afghanistan, who increased
pressure on the Soviet-sponsored government by capturing a district
near Kabul, the capital.
   Insurgent leader Gulbaddin Hekmatyar said in Pakistan that
guerrilla successes in the field may cause the Soviets to complete
their troop withdrawal ahead of the Feb. 15 deadline. He said his
forces had captured Shigal, a strategic post in Kunar province near
the Pakistani border.
   A Soviet government statement issued through the official news
agency Tass contained some of the sharpest language the Kremlin has
aimed at Pakistan.
   ``The Soviet government most resolutely declares that the
continuation by Pakistan of its obstructionist policy vis-a-vis the
Geneva accords on Afghanistan cannot be further tolerated,'' it
said.
   ``The Soviet Union reserves for itself, in that case, the right
to take such measures that are necessitated by the situation.'' It
was not specific about the response.
   On May 15, the Soviet Union began withdrawing its estimated
115,000 soldiers from Afghanistan under an agreement signed April
14 in Geneva by Afghanistan and Pakistan, with the Soviet Union and
United States as guarantors.
   Half the soldiers were to be out by Aug. 15, which the Soviets
said Sunday had been achieved, and all are to be gone by Feb. 15.
   President Najib of Afghanistan marked the occasion with an
article in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda thanking the Soviet
Union for its help.
   With the article, Pravda printed a map showing the remaining
Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan along two evacuation routes, from
Kabul and from Shindand via Herat in the west.
   Soviet military officials said earlier the pullout had cleared
the Red Army from 25 of Afghanistan's 30 provinces. The map showed
soldiers in only a narrow ribbon through the remaining five
provinces.
   Tass said 31 civilians were killed and 113 wounded in 142
attacks on populated areas in the first 10 days of August. Najib
said at a news conference in Kabul there are more than 180
guerrilla training centers in Pakistan and 50 bases for rearming
rebels and storing weapons.
   The Geneva agreement calls for other countries not to interfere
in Afghanistan's internal affairs. Guerrilla groups were not
parties to the accord.
   Red Army soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced
one pro-Soviet government with another, and remained to fight the
insurgents. More than 13,000 Soviet soldiers have been killed.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and use Pakistani border camps and cities, where more than 3
million Afghan refugees live, as supply points and bases. The
United States and other countries have armed them through Pakistan.
   Tass said Monday fighters from insurgent groups had captured the
Shakardar district about 20 miles north of Kabul. It quoted reports
in Kabul as saying they were armed with 1,500 rockets they intended
to aim at the capital.
   Other guerrilla organizations planned to send large forces armed
with ``long-range weapons, rockets and Stinger missiles'' from
Pakistan to the Karabag, Pagman and Sorubi districts of Kabul
province, the agency said.
   Lt. Gen. Boris T. Gromov, Soviet commander in Afghanistan, said
Sunday that insurgents had captured Kunduz, a northern provincial
capital 40 miles from the Soviet border.
   Afghanistan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil, who arrived in Moscow
on Sunday, told a news conference that reports of the fall of
Kunduz were ``fabrication and misinformation.''
   When told Gromov announced it, Wakil said the general's
statement was not ``authentic.''
   ``What is authentic and reliable is the statements made by the
government of Afghanistan,'' he said.
   ``Several days ago Kunduz faced a barbarous and ferocious
attack,'' but insurgents could not be considered in control unless
they established institutions such as schools and hospitals.
   ``The fact is that they do not have any kind of administration
over there,'' he said.
   Najib said Monday soldiers had recaptured the city. Hekmatyar,
leader of the Hezb-i-Islami guerrillas, said his information
indicated fighting continued near Kunduz.
   Wakil did not respond directly when asked whether there were
circumstances under which the Soviets might stop withdrawing.
   He cited a joint statement issued Aug. 7 when Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze was in Kabul saying the two sides would
``draw the necessary conclusions and determine their actions'' if
Pakistan continued to aid the insurgents.
   Shevardnadze said in an interview the same day, however, that
the withdrawal would finish on schedule.
   Hekmatyar claimed Moscow had wanted to remove partial units from
eastern, southern and southwestern Afghanistan to make things
easier for Afghan government forces, but that proved too dangerous
so entire units have been withdrawn.
   ``The Soviets are not leaving because of a Geneva agreement but
because they see no gain,'' he said. ``They are forced to leave.''
</TEXT>
