<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Humphrey-Veep     08-15 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Humphrey-Veep,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humphrey Relishes `Lone Wolf' Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lone wolf, maverick, member of an extremely
small group of conservative U.S. senators _ Gordon Humphrey
identifies with all those characterizations and says he doesn't
care as long as George Bush is listening closely.
   ``I run with a pretty small pack,'' the self-proclaimed and sole
congressional spokesman for the Coalition for a Winning Ticket said
late Sunday night. ``I didn't come here to blend in with the
wallpaper. I'm going to compete within the bounds of civility up to
the end to put forth my agenda.''
   Thus far, Humphrey's effort to pressure Bush into naming a
conservative running mate has attracted tremendous media coverage.
   Humphrey planned it that way. ``If there weren't a news vacuum
at this convention, we wouldn't really get the attention, but I saw
the chance and, quite frankly, decided to exploit it,'' he said.
   Humphrey acknowledges that all the noise won't win victory on
the convention floor if he had to take it to a roll call vote.
   ``We'd be beaten,'' he said.
   So why fight Bush campaign attempts to create harmony?
   ``We're trying to sensitize him and particularly his advisers.''
Humphrey said. ``Bush people are tone deaf. They are so isolated
from the majority of the party.''
   Humphrey, 47, a former airline pilot, narrowly defeated 16-year
incumbent Sen. Thomas McIntyre, a Democrat, in what was viewed as a
major upset in 1978. It was Humphrey's first try for public office.
He promised to be the ``toughest skinflint in the U.S. Senate.''
   Humphrey has since carved a niche in the Senate as the leading
spokesman against abortion. He is a fiscal conservative, strongly
anti-communist and an advocate for the freedom fighters in
Afghanistan.
   ``I do not try to be all things to all people,'' he says of his
essentially unyielding positions. ``People either like the kind of
representation I give them or they don't.''
   When Bush named New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean as keynote speaker,
Humphrey threatened to stage a boycott unless Bush allowed an
abortion opponent to speak. Humphrey later announced he was
satisfied with the Bush campaign's promise to let Congressman Henry
Hyde of Illinois to speak on the issue.
   ``I've made that (abortion) a real point of leadership,'' he
said. ``That riles some people.''
   Humphrey also believes that many agree that the vice
presidential nominee should be anti-abortion, fiscally conservative
and strong on defense, but are afraid to speak out.
   ``If I wasn't raising hell, who would be?'' he asked.
   Humphrey says he doesn't really want to force the convention to
consider an alternative nominee, but he will try if Bush picks a
moderate. Even in losing, an alternative nominee would be able to
reassure conservatives ``the movement is still there and lives.''
   ``As long as I don't overplay my hand or become uncivil, I don't
see any downside for conservatives,'' he said. ``Right now, we're
shut out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
