<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: become rich.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   They talk about plant closings _ we want to continue plant
openings. They see America in terms of its limits _ we see America
in terms of its possibilities.
   If we do our job right, I predict that by 1992 _ the start of
George Bush's second term _ one-quarter of our party will consist
of black, Hispanic, and Asian-Americans, who will see in our party
the best hope of a better life for themselves and their families.
   What's the real purpose of the Reagan revolution? It wasn't to
defeat Democrats. It was to bring new ideas and superior
leadership, to restore confidence in America. Like the American
Revolution itself, the greatness of our revolution is measured, not
by who we're against, but by what we're for.
   Last month in Atlanta, the leaders of the Democratic Party
failed to say what they're for. All they said was who they're
against. They all said, ``We can't stand another eight years of
Republican policies.'' Of course they can't. It's clear that Ted
Kennedy, Jim Wright, and Michael Dukakis can't stand another eight
years of Republican policies: because that means another 5 million
new employers _ and another 17 million new jobs. At that rate, all
their constituents will become Republicans.
   This is no time to stop. This is no time to go back. We have a
lot of work to do. We dn't just want low inflation _ we want no
inflation. We don't just want low unemployment _ we want no
unemployment. We need a safety net to keep people from falling _
but we also need a ladder of opportunity upon which all can climb.
   We don't just want to oppose communism _ we want to support men
and women who are fighting for freedom and democracy, whether in
Afghanistan, Angola or Central America. We want to free people, not
only from too much dependence on government _ we want to free them
from dependence on drugs, and the disrespect for human life.
   Mr. President, you've brought us to the threshold of a new era.
In fact, you've taken us over the threshold. You've shown us that
we can do more than contain our adversaries _ we can transcend
them. You've shown us how we can make even the threat of nuclear
war obsolete, through the now-proven technology of strategic
defense. You've reminded us that the first and best Department of
Health, Education and Welfare is a strong family. And you've shown
us that the power of a right idea is the greatest force on Earth.
   Mr. President, this is a powerful legacy that you are handing us
here in New Orleans. I just want you and Nancy to know that, under
the able leadership of George Bush, this party is going to take it
and run with it.
   We're going to win in November. We're going to finish what we
began in 1980: To help all Americans _ to help people everywhere _
to share in the success of freedom, democracy, and peace.
   Thank you, and God bless you.
</TEXT>
