<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--GOP-Rules     08-15 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--GOP-Rules,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Rules Committee Rejects Veep Roll Call</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative group pushing for a roll call
vote for the Republican vice presidential nomination lost one round
Monday when a convention committee voted to scrap the
time-consuming ritual to conserve television time.
   However, Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., chairman of the group
calling itself the ``Coalition for a Winning Ticket,'' said that he
was prepared to carry the fight to the convention floor, possibly
putting up a rival candidate for vice president to keep the process
open.
   ``Every dictator in history has wanted to make the trains run on
time,'' Humphrey said at a news conference after his proposal died
before the Republican National Convention's Rules Committee.
``There is no more foolish thing in politics than seeking to stifle
dissent.''
   Humphrey has been outspoken in recent weeks in urging George
Bush to choose a conservative as his vice presidential running
mate. Bush has not said who he will ask to join him on the ticket.
   Now Humphrey and his group object to a rules change that would
dispense with a state-by-state roll call vote on the GOP vice
presidential nomination if only one candidate's name is placed in
nomination. In effect, the rules change, if adopted by the entire
convention, would allow delegates to vote only on whether the
nomination should be made unanimous.
   Haley Barbour of Mississippi, who proposed the change in the
rules, said it is to let the party use prime-time television more
productively.
   ``Are we going to take 45 minutes of George Bush and the
Republican Party's valuable time and waste it on an uncontested
nomination?'' Barbour asked during the rules committee meeting.
   Humphrey, who is not a member of the committee, was allowed to
speak to the panel. But when delegate Duane Mutch of North Dakota
tried to bring Humphrey's proposal up for a vote, he was ruled out
of order.
   When the entire set of GOP rules came up for a vote, only one
dissenting voice was heard.
   Humphrey said later that he would try to line up the five state
delegations necessary under the rules to put another vice
presidential candidate's name in nomination. He said he had nobody
in particular in mind and refused to name which states he was
targeting.
</TEXT>
