<HEAD>Rabin Tours Gaza Strip, Troops Kill Arab In West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 2 grafs SUB for 6th graf pvs, In Arab ... with hospital
officials identifying Americans. PICKS up 7th graf pvs, Scattered
protests ... with minor editing to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUREIJ, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin said Monday his order confining 650,000 Palestinians to their
homes under a military curfew was a clear message that Israel was
cracking down on protesters.
   In the occupied West Bank, Israeli troops shot and killed a
Palestinian, bringing the Arab death toll in more than eight months
of anti-Israeli violence to 245, according to United Nations
figures.
   The around-the-clock curfew was imposed indefinitely on this
seaside strip Sunday evening following a violent weekend in the
occupied lands in which three Arabs died. Troops shot and wounded
25 people in Gaza on Sunday, according to Arab reports.
   It was only the third time the army had sealed off the Gaza
Strip since the uprising began Dec. 8. Rabin said the curfew, which
kept about 50,000 Gazans away from jobs in Israel, would be in
effect ``as long as it is needed.''
   Some Israeli sources speculated the move was related not to
resurgent violence but to an effort to put economic pressure on the
650,000 residents of Gaza.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, Palestinian protesters threw rocks at
police and at an Israeli bus near the walled Old City, slightly
injuring three American tourists, police said.
   An official at Hadassa Hospital identified the Americans as
brother and sisters Abraham, Dina and Shoshana Kai. The official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the three teen-agers were
released after treatment. He did not have their hometown.
   Scattered protests broke out Monday despite the curfew, and
Palestinian reports said two residents of the Jabaliya refugee camp
on the outskirts of Gaza City were wounded in the legs by army
gunfire.
   Reporters were allowed into the strip only with Israeli army
escorts to tour with Rabin.
   ``We have delivered a clear-cut message ... that violence will
be met by force,'' Rabin said, standing in the road near the site
where a firebomb hurled at a van Sunday burned six Israelis, one of
them an 8-month-old infant.
   ``The population ... must realize that if they take the law into
their own hands, throwing firebombs, stones and putting up
roadblocks, this will lead nowhere and they will be the ones to
suffer.''
   Rabin said earlier that soldiers had been ordered to ``shoot to
hit'' anyone caught throwing a firebomb and that the homes of
suspects would be torn down without right of appeal.
   Yigal Kaminetzky, the chief rabbi of Jewish settlers in Gaza,
called for tough measures to prevent further firebomb attacks,
including clearing both sides of the road for 50 yards in both
rural and built-up residential areas.
   During Rabin's tour Monday, Arab youths darted out from behind
garbage dumpsters and brick walls to hurl rocks at a 12-car
military convoy carrying reporters and military offixcials.
   The convoy stopped several times to chase away protesters, but
no shots were fired.
   In Gaza City, Palestinians violating the curfew dropped a large
rock on top of a van carrying an Israeli television crew, but no
one was hurt.
   Protesters also set tires on fire in the middle of roads and
scrawled slogans on walls.
   Most streets were deserted, but an Arab witness who spoke on
condition of anonymity said soldiers forced some residents to
whitewash graffiti or clear away debris.
   Rabin said the army would concentrate on breaking the power of
autonomous Palestinian ``popular committees,'' which have been
orchestrating protests at the neighborhood and village level.
   He attributed the unrest to a show of force by Moslem
fundamentalists, who called for demonstrations to mark the start of
the Islamic new year 1409.
   Palestinians traced the weekend protests to the arson deaths of
two Gaza workers who were trapped in a shed that was set on fire
near Tel Aviv. Police said Jewish extremists may have been involved.
   In the occupied West Bank, hospital officials said 21-year-old
Jamal Odeh of Tulkarm refugee camp was dead on arrival after being
shot in the heart during overnight clashes.
   Troops shot an 18-year-old Palestinian in the right leg after
youths threw rocks on soldiers in the old city marketplace, and a
second 18-year-old was hit in the eye with a rubber bullet, Nablus
hospital officials said.
   Israeli officials expressed mixed reactions to suggestions from
senior PLO official Salah Khalaf that a ``completely new'' PLO
charter might include recognition of Israel.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, the dovish Labor Party leader,
called for clarifications.
   ``Whoever wants negotiations should say so clearly. What has
been said until now is a jigsaw puzzle,'' Peres told reporters.
   But a spokesman for right-wing Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
described Khalaf's statements as ``verbal trickery.''
   ``We have to watch what they do, not what they say,'' said
spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
</TEXT>
