<HEAD>Bush Vows to Be Own Man, Says Comparisons With Reagan Inevitable</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES with new grafs 3-6 on Bush still uncertain, bgng, As
of xxx; picks up 4th graf pvs, Making the xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush conceded Monday he has a hard act
to follow but hopes to leave his personal stamp on the Republican
National Convention and ``not try to be a Ronald Reagan. There is
only one.''
   The vice president spent his last day here putting finishing
touches on his acceptance speech and maintaining his silence on his
choice of a running mate. He planned to watch Reagan's evening
speech to the convention on television before flying to New Orleans
on Tuesday morning.
   As of late Monday, Bush still had not made up his mind on a
running mate, although was likely to do so Tuesday before his
arrival in New Orleans, said spokeswoman Sheila Tate.
   ``He's going to call the schedule the way he sees fit,'' she
said. ``He knows that if he tells one person, it will leak.''
   Ms. Tate said Bush still plans to announce his choice Thursday
morning, although she would not rule out the possiblity that the
announcement might be moved up to Wednesday night.
   Bush spent two sessions on Monday working on a final draft of
his acceptance speech with speechwriter Peggy Noonan and was
``pretty well finished'' with it, Ms. Tate said.
   Making the rounds of morning television interview shows, Bush
said that while he had narrowed his choice of a running mate he
still had not made the final decision, even in his own mind.
   Asked whether he expected to be compared with Reagan, Bush told
NBC's ``Today'' show he felt such comparisons were inevitable
``because he's been a great president. He deserves tribute, not
only of the Republican party but of a grateful nation. And so there
will be some comparison of that nature.''
   ``I'm not going to try to be a Ronald Reagan,'' he continued.
``There is only one. I want to be George Bush.''
   Bush also told NBC the ``pressure is mounting'' as he nears the
time of nomination.
   But he also said that as ``an athlete,'' he'd been ``in pressure
situations before, maybe none this intense. But, look, all I'll do
is just stand up there and say what I believe about peace and what
I believe in about prosperity.''
   In an interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' Bush said,
``I want to stand up there on Thursday, pay tribute to what we have
done, and give the president plenty of credit for bringing this
country to new heights, and then say what I, George Bush, will do
on peace and on keeping this recovery going until everybody
benefits.
   ``So it's a big moment for me, the culmination of a lot of years
in politics. But I don't feel concerned about it. I've got to be
what I am and I'm not going to be like someone else.''
   On the subject of a vice presidential choice, Bush told ABC, ``I
have not decided. And I probably will say when I have decided. But
I'm going to continue with this appropriate plan, making a decision
in private and then presenting it at the appropriate time.''
   Bush also said he hoped to make maximum use of his family at the
convention, including his five children, their spouses and his 10
grandchildren.
   ``I've always protected the privacy and the wonder of our
family,'' he told CBS' ``Morning News.'' But he added, ``I've had
to lighten up and say to the world, I guess, through this
convention, this is what makes me tick.
   ``I thought Governor Dukakis did a good job on that (showing off
his family) at the Democratic convention. But we've got him
outnumbered, we've got a stronger bench, and we've got a great
family.''
</TEXT>
