<HEAD>Congressman Facing Ethics Probe Named Georgia Delegation Head</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Republicans, gambling that Rep. Pat
Swindall will be vindicated by a House ethics committee
investigation, voted Monday to elect him chairman of the state
delegation to the Republican National Convention.
   Swindall's election in a unanimous vote came at a rowdy caucus
at which delegates were poised to elect Brant Frost IV of Macon,
Ga., a leader of a faction dominated by supporters of former
presidential candidate Pat Robertson, the television evangelist.
   Then, Oscar Persons, an Atlanta lawyer nominated Swindall, a
born-again Christian with wide support among the Robertson faction.
Frost withdrew and endorsed Swindall.
   The Robertson faction, which won control of the delegation in
the credentials fight, demonstrated its clout by beating back the
faction led by party regulars in a series of procedural roll call
votes.
   The selection of Swindall by party leaders came less than two
months after the same GOP officials met privately to decide whether
to launch their own investigation of Swindall.
   Those meetings were prompted by revelations about an on-going
federal undercover investigation of Swindall. Tape recordings from
the investigation, obtained by Atlanta newspapers, showed that
Swindall had continued to pursue an $850,000 home construction loan
after he was told it likely would be financed with drug money he
would be helping to launder.
   The Georgia GOP decided not to conduct its own investigation,
but the House ethics committee, formally known as the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, launched a probe of Swindall in June
to determine if he had violated the law or House rules.
   Swindall, who requested the ethics committee probe, apologized
for his role in the loan negotiations at a news conference in June.
He said he was wrong and ashamed but would continue to seek
re-election.
</TEXT>
