<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDS-Ranking 1stLd-Writethru a0599 08-15 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Ranking, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Deaths From AIDS Outnumber Those From Birth Defects</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, ``For statistical,'' to add figures for
overall category in which AIDS included</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS claimed about 13,000 American lives last
year, a toll that would have ranked it 15th among all causes of
death, according to the first annual government statistical summary
to include the disease.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome was added to the annual
summary of disease starting in 1987, the National Center for Health
Statistics reported Monday.
   The agency estimated that between 12,450 and 13,820 Americans
died of AIDS last year. While AIDS was not officially added to the
overall rankings of causes of death, that total would have put in
15th place, ahead of birth defects, which claimed 12,130 lives.
   For statistical purposes, AIDS has been listed in the category
of ``other infectious and parasitic diseases,'' which accounted for
19,160 deaths in 1987, compared with 9,030 the year before.
   The report said 65 percent of AIDS victims were white males and
25 percent black males. White and black females each made up
between 4 percent and 5 percent of the total.
   The age groups most heaving affected were 25 to 34 and 35 to 44,
the study added.
   AIDS is a contagious, fatal disease that attacks the body's
immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases
and infections.
   The disease is spread most often through sexual contact, needles
or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring.
   The chief victims of AIDS have been homosexual men and
intravenous drug abusers. Health officials estimate that
heterosexual contact is responsible for 4 percent of cases and that
between 1 million and 1.5 million Americans have been exposed to
the virus.
   A person who tests positive for antibodies to the AIDS virus, an
indication of exposure, has a 20 percent to 30 percent chance of
developing AIDS over a five-year period, according to the federal
Centers for Disease Control.
   As of Aug. 8, AIDS had been diagnosed in 70,208 Americans, of
whom more than half, or 39,620, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the federal Centers for Disease Control. No one is
known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--`Generic'Speeches     08-15 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--`Generic' Speeches,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Speechwriters Reduced to `Generic' Veep Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican convention organizers say time
pressures brought on by the mystery over George Bush's running mate
are forcing them to begin writing ``generic'' speeches for
last-minute use by the person picked for the ticket.
   They conceded, however, that they'd leave some room for
modification to fit whoever delivers the speech.
   ``By Wednesday morning...we will have one or two writers working
on a generic kind of acceptance speech which the nominee would then
have to take and modify and put into his or her own style of
words,'' said Fred Malek, George Bush's convention manager.
   By keeping the vice presidential selection the best-kept secret
in the convention city, Bush adds pressure to organizers of the
convention who are working hard to orchestrate even the tiniest
detail for a good television showing.
   That includes editing and painstaking revision of every word in
every speech delivered from the podium. Malek said those
speechwriters want an early start on the vice presidential
nominee's speech, because it will be a major focus of the
convention's final night.
   ``It's a generic kind of a speech, it's a draft,'' Malek said.
``The nominee will not learn of his or her selection until Thursday
morning.''
   Even with the head-start on the nominating speech, Malek said
convention organizers will face a last-minute scramble to line up
nominating speakers _ and write their speeches.
   ``We've got two other, three other addresses, really, to go
along with it,'' Malek said. ``They will be also in the same
sequence. We'll have one or two writers working on an acceptance
speech and another working on a nominating speech.
   ``We won't start this until Wednesday,'' he said. ``They will
have no clues, nor will I, on who it's going to be.
   ``A good writer, with some general directions and general clues,
can get a running start,'' Malek said.
   ``We haven't selected yet who is going to give the nominating
speeches, for the same reason,'' he said. ``We are developing some
ideas of who are good speakers and could do it.''
   Part of the problem, Malek said, is whoever nominates the vice
presidential candidate must have some logical ties to the person
selected and fit within the campaign theme selected by Bush.
   ``There's got to be some kind of a linkage,'' he said.
   This week's Republican National Convention is a carefully
scripted affair, and Malek clearly wasn't comfortable with leaving
major gaps in a schedule that's been developed over months of
planning.
   ``We don't have any choice,'' Malek said.
   ``I think it's going to be all right, I think we have the
caliber of people to do the nomination. I don't have any great
trepidations about that. Obviously they could do a better job with
more time.''
</TEXT>
