<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-15 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms In East, More Record Heat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms broke out Monday over parts of the
Northeast and the Ohio Valley, with widespread rain over the
Southeast, and temperatures reached record highs from Iowa to the
East Coast.
   Intense thunderstorms moved over sections of Ohio during the
morning with high wind and heavy rainfall. Wind downed trees and
power lines in Defiance County, and nearly an inch of rain fell in
less than an hour in northern Ashland County. One person survived a
lightning strike near Albion, the National Weather Service said.
   Severe thunderstorms also developed in warm, moist air ahead of
a cold front over sections of the Northeast. Wind uprooted trees at
Johnsonville, N.Y., and downed numerous trees at Keene and Jaffrey,
N.H.
   ``We had alarms going off, flooding in the streets, power lines
going down, trees going down. What else can I tell you,'' said
officer Terry Talomadge in Jaffrey. ``The rain was so thick you
couldn't see your hand in front of your face.''
   Power was out in some parts of New Hampshire and some streets
were flooded.
   A strong thunderstorm spawned a tornado near Greensburg, Pa.,
during the afternoon.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were along the Gulf Coast, over
New Mexico and the Texas Panhandle, Florida, the southern Atlantic
Coast states and the Tennessee Valley. Homestead Air Force Base,
Fla., got 3.04 inches of rain in the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Philadelphia again broke a record for greatest number of
90-degree or higher days in a year, reaching its 48th day at that
heat. It was also the 18th consecutive day of temperatures 90 or
above.
   Williamsport, Pa., hit a record 40 days of 90 degrees or higher.
   Record highs Monday included 97 at Allentown, Pa.; 99 at
Atlantic City, N.J.; 101 in downtown Baltimore and 98 at the
airport; 99 at Charleston, W.Va.; 102 at Des Moines, Iowa; 97 at
Hartford, Conn.; 96 at Indianapolis; 97 at Louisville, Ky.; 97 at
New York City; 102 at Peoria, Ill.; 98 at Philadelphia; 97 at
Rockford, Ill.; 99 at Washington's National Airport; and 97 at
Wilmington, Del.
   Records were tied at Cape Hatteras, N.C., at 89; at Evansville,
Ind., at 98; and at Williamsport, Pa., at 97.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 112 at Pierre, S.D. The nation's low
Monday morning was 30 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over the Gulf Coast and Florida, the coast of North Carolina,
northern Maine, northwestern Montana, central Arizona and along the
front range of the Rockies. Scattered showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast ahead of a cold front over eastern sections of
the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted in the Pacific Northwest
and the California coast; in the 70s in northern New England;
between 100 and 105 in northern Texas, the middle and northern
Plains, and the middle Mississippi Valley; between 100 and 110 in
the desert Southwest and the Rio Grande valley; and in the 80s and
90s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
