<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India     08-15 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Warns Pakistan Against Helping Sikhs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi warned
Pakistan on Monday against aiding Sikh insurgents in Punjab state,
saying he did not want to take further action Pakistan ``might
later regret.''
   He spoke at celebrations of the 41st anniversary of India's
independence from Britain. Clashes in Kashmir state related to the
celebrations injured at least 75 people, including 25 police
officers, the Press Trust of India said.
   In Gujarat state, Popatlal Sarothia, a legislator of Gandhi's
governing Congress Party, was shot and killed Monday by a
disgruntled party worker attending independence festivites, the
news agency said.
   Gandhi said at a ceremony in New Delhi, ``We have taken firm
action against (Sikh) terrorism.'' He did not elaborate.
   He has often accused Pakistan of arming and training Sikh rebels
who are fighting for a separate homeland in northern Punjab state,
which borders Pakistan. India has offered no proof and Pakistan has
denied the charge.
   ``We do not wish to take action (Pakistan) might later regret,''
the prime minister said. He did not refer to Pakistan by name, but
said Sikh insurgents were getting help from across the border.
   On Sunday, Indian border guards shot and killed 11 Pakistanis as
they tried to slip across the border into Kashmir, authorities said.
   Sikh radicals have waged a bloody six-year struggle in Punjab,
which has claimed about 1,700 lives this year.
   In Srinagar, capital of Kashmir state adjoining Pakistan, police
fired in the air to disperse pro-Pakistani demonstrators objecting
to independence celebrations, PTI reported. It said demonstrators
burned a police jeep, threw stones at police and forced shops to
close, with at least 75 people hurt.
   Pakistan was part of India until 1947. Since their joint
independence from Britain, the two nations have fought each other
in three wars.
   Pakistan controls 30 percent of Kashmir, but claims the entire
state as its own. India rejects the claim.
   At least 2,500 security officers were on duty as Gandhi
delivered his Independence Day address at the 16th-century Red Fort
in New Delhi, according to a police official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Guests, including Cabinet ministers and foreign diplomats, were
frisked before the 40-minute ceremony and sharpshooters were posted
on tall buildings around the sandstone fort.
   Gandhi, wearing white trousers and a tunic, unfurled the Indian
flag on the ramparts of the fort to begin the festivities.
   He referred in his speech to the nearby island nation of Sri
Lanka, where about 47,000 Indian soldiers are deployed to enforce a
July 29, 1987, peace accord aimed at ending a five-year rebellion
by Tamil insurgents.
   Tamil rebels returned to combat after a brief truce and are
fighting Indian troops.
   ``We hope that the accord will be speedily implemented,'' Gandhi
said.
   A major reason for India's brokering the accord was that India
has 60 million Tamils of its own, who are sympathetic to the Sri
Lankan rebel cause. Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people and claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese
population.
   India's diplomatic mission in Colombo, Sri Lanka, is under heavy
security after intelligence reports that a Tamil assassination
squad entered the capital.
</TEXT>
