<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--DuPont-Jackson     08-15 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Du Pont-Jackson,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Du Pont Says Jesse Jackson's Future is in the GOP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Onetime presidential candidate Pete du Pont
called on Jesse Jackson to become a Republican, saying Monday that
he has no political future as a Democrat.
   ``May I suggest with all sincerity that the ground you seek is
here, in New Orleans, in the party of Lincoln and Reagan and Bush
and Kemp and Bork,'' du Pont said in an address to the Republican
National Convention.
   Delegates applauded as du Pont listed reasons he believed the
Republican Party was superior to the Democratic Party.
   But when he said of Jackson, ``We ask you to join us because we
need you and you need us,'' the Superdome was silent.
   Jackson wasn't talking about it either; Pam Smith, a spokeswoman
for him in Chicago, said he would have no comment.
   ``Rev. Jackson, you seek common ground, higher ground,'' du Pont
said to the convention.
   Du Pont praised Jackson for expressing the ``most interesting
thoughts'' at the Democratic National Convention last month in
Atlanta. However, du Pont did not mention any specifics.
   ``As long as your lungs have breath, yours will be a prominent
voice,'' du Pont said. ``But as long as you speak as a Democrat,
you will never be a successful leader.''
   The GOP has formed committees to recruit blacks and other
minorities to become Republicans, but the party remains
predominantly white. An Associated Press survey found that 92
percent of the delegates to the national convention are white.
   Du Pont mentioned the name of George Bush just twice.
   Using Jackson's keep-hope-alive slogan, he said Bush ``will not
only keep hope alive, but he will make the dream of millions of
Americans come true.''
   Du Pont, a former governor of Delaware and an heir to the
family's chemical empire, entered the GOP presidential race on
Sept. 16, 1986, and dropped out last Feb. 18, two days after the
New Hampshire primary.
</TEXT>
