<HEAD>Iraq Complains Of Iraqi Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq accused Iran on Monday of bombarding
its troops with artillery and mortar fire, the second time in a
week it said Tehran had broken a promise not to attack in the days
leading to a formal cease-fire.
   Iraq made its accusations in a letter from the Iraqi mission to
the United Nations. It did not mention casualties or damage.
   Iran denied a similar accusation last week. Iraqi Ambassador
Ismat T. Kittani did not lodge a protest, but filed a brief
``factual report'' with the United Nations.
   In the latest letter, Iraq said Iranian gunners fired from
Saturday through Monday in army sectors that include the Iraqi
southern port city of Basra and the southern Faw Peninsula.
   On Aug. 8, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced
that Iran and Iraq had agreed to a truce in their nearly 8-year-old
war beginning Saturday, and to start peace talks five days later in
Geneva.
   Iran gave Perez de Cuellar a letter pledging not to engage in
military action except in self-defense. Iraq did not offer such a
letter, but the secretary-general said both countries told him they
would restrain their armed forces.
   Last week, Tehran lodged a protest with the U.N. chief, claiming
Iraqi warplanes violated Iran's air space and created sonic booms
over five cities.
