<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Cardinal     08-15 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Cardinal,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Warns Sandinistas and Contras Preparing For Renewed War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo said
Monday the Sandinista government and U.S.-supported rebels are
preparing for more war after several failed attempts at talking
peace.
   During the news program El Pensamiento on privately owned Radio
Noticias, the Roman Catholic prelate referred to a broadcast in
which a leader of the rebels, known as Contras, said they never
will abandon their fight against the leftist Sandinistas.
   ``I heard a few moments ago something resembling the Roman
saying that `if you want peace, prepare for war,' and it seems both
sides are preparing for war,'' Obando y Bravo, archbishop of
Managua, said. ``That would be deplorable because those who pay the
price for it are the youths who are dying.
   ``I have always said dialogue should be the solution, but it
seems clear a propitious climate for dialogue doesn't exist at this
moment.
   ``God willing the government and the (Contra) resistance will
adopt flexible positions. These inflexible positions only produce
death, destruction and the country's ruin,'' he said.
   Contras and their civilian supporters have been fleeing to
neighboring Honduras as supplies dwindle for lack of U.S. funds,
but rebel leader Enrique Bermudez said on clandestine Liberation
Radio the fight will continue.
   ``If we want peace, we should prepare ourselves for war,''
Bermudez said at a ceremony inducting 600 new guerrillas into
Contra ranks at a camp in southern Honduras. Liberation Radio
carried parts of the ceremony.
   ``We will not abandon the struggle until we achieve democracy in
Nicaragua,'' Bermudez said. ``We will lay down our weapons only in
exchange for democracy ... (otherwise) the Nicaraguan people will
declare us guilty of writing one of the blackest chapters in our
country's history.''
   ``We will not return to the negotiating table until the
Sandinistas are ready to talk seriously,'' he said, referring to
President Daniel Ortega's call last week for resumption of the
stalled peace talks.
   Bermudez, a hard liner, was elected last month to the
seven-member directorate of the Contra umbrella organization
Nicaraguan Resistance.
   Contra and Sandinista representatives signed a cease-fire
agreement March 23 that has been extended but often violated.
Ortega last extended it unilaterally for 30 days until Aug. 31.
   Efforts to negotiate a permanent truce have been deadlocked. The
Contras insist the Sandinistas introduce democratic reforms before
they lay down their arms, but the Sandinistas demand the rebels
stop fighting and join the legal opposition.
   Contra negotiators broke off the last meeting in Managua, saying
the government confined them to their hotel and did not allow them
to meet with opposition leaders.
   Ortega proposed another meeting Aug. 27-29 in Managua or
Washington.
   The Contras demanded a site elsewhere in Central America,
preferably San Jose, Costa Rica, and that Ortega lead the
government delegation. The Sandinistas have not responded.
   Last week, Honduras revived the issue of an international
verification commission provided for in a Central American peace
plan of Aug. 7, 1987, and said it should operate on the
Nicaragua-Honduras border to keep Contras and Sandinista troops
apart.
   Ortega agreed, but on Monday the rebels objected.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero said in Miami: ``The Nicaraguan
Resistance is present throughout Nicaragua ... so if you are going
to get an international force to guarantee a security zone, it will
be necessary to have an international force that will guarantee all
of Nicaragua as a security zone.''
</TEXT>
