<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Czechoslovakia     08-15 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Czechoslovakia,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historian Gives Sympathetic Picture of `Prague Spring'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet historian says the goals of the
Czechoslovak reforms Soviet tanks crushed 20 years ago were similar
to those now pursued by Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   L.S. Yagodovsky's article in the latest issue of the weekly
journal Arguments and Facts contrasted dramatically with previous
characterizations of the the ``Prague spring'' led by Alexander
Dubcek, which ended with a Soviet-led invasion Aug. 21, 1968.
   As recently as January, the Soviet news agency Tass said
comparisons with current Soviet reforms were the work of Western
propaganda.
   Yagodovsky, assistant director of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences' Institute of the Economy of the World Socialist System,
used such Gorbachev words as ``restructuring,'' ``glasnost,''
``self-management,'' and ``self-financing'' to describe the
Czechoslovak reforms.
   Reforms adopted by the Czechoslovak Communist Party in 1965
``coincide with the basic principles of today's transformation in
this area in Czechoslovakia, as with the conception of economic
reform existing at this time in the Soviet Union and other
socialist countries,'' he said in the Aug. 13-19 edition of the
journal.
   He said Leonid I. Brezhnev, then the Soviet leader, was more
sympathethic to conservative opponents, and in the end reformers
let the situation get out of control.
   Yagodovsky quoted party documents that said no way existed to
restore order in the country except to invite the invasion.
   He said conservatives backed by party chief Antonin Novotny
blocked the reforms and they could not succeed without
``perestroika of the form and methods of party work, without
democratization of society, affirmation of glasnost (openness),
without giving socialism genuine human lines.''
   Dubcek replaced Novotny as party leader in January 1968, and in
March Ludvik Svoboda replaced Novotny as president.
   Further reforms put in place in January and April 1968 ``opened
the way for normalization of the situation, uniting the leading
forces in a platform of renewal,'' Yagodovsky said, but Dubcek and
other party leaders did not take advantage of it.
   ``One of the main reasons, in my view, is that despite the
rearrangement in the government, unity in the Presidium of the
Czechoslovak Communist Party, and in the party as a whole, was not
guaranteed,'' he said.
   All top officials wanted reforms but did not agree on what the
reforms meant, he said.
   ``Anti-socialist forces'' inside and outside Czechoslovakia
became more active and the situation in the country deteriorated
sharply, he said. Yagodovsky quoted Czechoslovak party documents as
saying the party was paralyzed, the government on the brink of
decay and there was no choice but to bring in the Warsaw Pact force
to restore order.
   Dubcek was replaced as Czechoslovak party leader in April 1969
by Gustav Husak, who retired last year after running one of the
Soviet bloc's more conservative organizations for nearly a
generation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
