<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Stassen     08-15 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Stassen,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stassen Says He Always Had Something to Say in His Campaigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Stassen wound down his eighth
fruitless presidential campaign Monday with the claim that ``I've
always had something to say'' during his 40-year quest for the
White House.
   ``The fascinating thing about this year,'' the 81-year-old
Stassen said in an interview as the Republican National Convention
began here, ``is I came in very late saying (that) none of the
other 14 candidates were saying anything about children.
   ``I said we needed a new American children's program, we needed
it urgently. So, I'm quite fascinated that they're all talking
about a new children's program now, the candidates of both
parties.''
   Stassen, the one-time ``Boy Wonder'' of Minnesota politics, was
elected governor at age 31, and re-elected in 1940 and '42. He
resigned in 1943 to serve in the Navy during World War II, and
never won another election.
   Stassen was a major contender for the GOP presidential
nomination in 1948, when the party's nod went to Thomas Dewey.
   He also unsuccessfully opposed Barry Goldwater for the party's
nomination in 1964, Richard Nixon in 1968, Gerald Ford in 1976 and
Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   Stassen entered primaries this year in New Hampshire, West
Virginia and a few other states.
   He insisted that campaigning, even when there is no chance of
victory, is the best way to get a hearing for his views.
   ``You don't get attention to your views'' by writing letters or
talking to politicians, said Stassen, who practices law and lives
with his wife, Esther, in the St. Paul suburb of Sunfish Lake.
   Stassen said he's attended about a dozen Republican National
Conventions, the first in 1936 as president of a young Republicans
organization.
   Asked whether he will run for president again, Stassen said, ``I
don't know how long I'm going to live.''
</TEXT>
