<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GenesisParish     08-15 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Genesis Parish,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parish That Experimented With Lay Participation Loses Official
Sanction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental Roman Catholic parish
that offered extensive lay participation such as planning the
liturgy went out of official existence Monday, but its members
vowed to carry on.
   Daniel Corley, a lay trustee of the Genesis Community, said the
13-year-old group would continue in some form despite Bishop Louis
E. Gelineau's decision to disband it as a formal church-sanctioned
group.
   ``After today, the bishop has told us that we cannot have a
priest and a Eucharist celebrated on Sunday morning,'' Corley said.
``We will be following the bishop's directive over the next 40
days. We will not get together as a community for Eucharist
celebration on Sunday morning.''
   The group will meet on Sunday nights for ``prayer, reflection
and discussion'' and will decide at the end of the 40 days where to
proceed, Corley said.
   Last month, Gelineau, who created the Genesis Community 13 years
ago, announced it would be dissolved after a task force he
commissioned found it beset with ``erroneous attitudes'' concerning
church teaching.
   Corley said the group was consulting canon lawyers to see
whether Gelineau's decision could be appealed. William G. Halpin,
spokesman for the Roman Catholic Diocese of Providence, said he did
not think an appeal was possible.
   ``They're an experimental open worship community that was a
creation of the diocese, so it's strictly a diocesan internal
matter,'' Halpin said.
   ``My understanding is that their only appeal would be to the
bishop,'' he said. ``I don't think there's any provision where they
could go over his head _ to Rome, for example.''
   The Genesis Community, unlike most Catholic parishes, was open
to Rhode Islanders regardless of where in the state they lived.
Corley said it was distinguished by the role lay people played in
``sitting down with the priest, planning liturgy, social justice
concerns.''
   Conflicts between the group and its most recent priest, the Rev.
Peter Scagnelli, led Gelineau to commission the task force that
recommended ending the experiment.
   Corley said the conflicts included whether leavened or
unleavened bread would be used during the Eucharist ceremony and
whether lay people as well as priests could read from the Gospel or
deliver homilies.
   He said the community gave in to Scagnelli on each of those
issues, but with each concession, some members became more and more
disturbed.
   Some members said the degree of lay participation was what drew
them to Genesis and warned that the church's resistance to the idea
would be self-defeating.
   ``The Catholic Church is not the cathedral. It's not the clergy.
It's us. It's the people,'' said member Jack Cotter. ``I can't see
myself going back to the parish I left 13 years ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
