<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RapeRecant     08-15 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Recant,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dotson Attorney Asks Executive Clemency; Says New Test Clears His
Client</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 15th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second request for clemency for convicted
rapist Gary Dotson was made Monday to Gov. James Thompson, citing
new high-tech tests Dotson's attorney says support Cathy Webb's
recantation and prove his client's innocence ``beyond a doubt.''
   ``This is a case where a person was arrested, convicted and
sentenced for a crime that never occurred,'' said Dotson's
attorney, Tom Breen.
   Dotson had served six years of a 25- to 50-year sentence
following his 1979 rape conviction when Mrs. Webb stepped forward
to say she had lied when she said he raped her, in order to cover
up a teen-age sexual liaison.
   Thompson, who received results of the test last week, is in New
Orleans for the Republican National Convention.
   Terry Barnich, the governor's legal counsel, said before
Thompson makes a decision on the clemency ``he wants to talk to
some scientific types, to feel comfortable in his own mind whether
this test is scientifically reliable beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   Dotson, meanwhile, remained behind bars Monday at the Joliet
Correctional Center, serving the last day of a six-month prison
term for failing to call his parole officer immediately after
Thompson granted him a ``last chance'' release from prison Dec. 24.
   Testimony before the Illinois Prisoner Review Board showed
Dotson waited until Dec. 26 to call his parole officer. Later that
day, he was arrested in a bar for allegedly starting a fight over a
sandwich.
   That was only one of a number of scrapes with the law Dotson has
had since May 1985, when Thompson commuted his sentence on the
original rape conviction to the six years Dotson had already served.
   In commuting his sentence, Thompson bypassed Dotson's request
for clemency, saying he did not believe Mrs. Webb's recantation nor
Dotson's denials.
   Since that 1985 release, Dotson, 30, has been in jail several
times, convicted of drunken-driving charges and arrested for
allegedly punching his wife and threatening the couple's infant
daughter.
   Under the good-behavior terms of Thompson's ``last-chance''
order, Dotson will remain under parole supervision for three years
and will undergo treatment for an admitted drinking problem.
   Dotson will be released Tuesday into an intensive residential
treatment program for ``an unspecified period of time'' and will
continue to receive out-patient counseling for his alcohol problem,
said Nic Howell, spokesman for the Illinois Department of
Corrections.
   Breen suggested Monday that Dotson's run-ins with the law may
have stemmed from his original imprisonment, and that recent tests
performed by a California forensic serologist prove ``conclusively,
absolutely and definitively that Gary Dotson did not have sex with
Cathy Webb.''
   Results of the test, which involve DNA analysis of blood and
semen samples from Dotson, Webb and her former boyfriend, were
turned over to Breen by Thompson's staff.
   Dr. Edward Blake, who performed the tests, said in a telephone
interview Monday from the San Francisco area that the test
``demonstrates that the semen in Webb's panties did not come from
Dotson, but was compatible with that of her boyfriend.''
   He said results of the test, called Polymerase Chain Reaction,
were submitted in one criminal case in which he testified in
California state courts and were not legally challenged by either
prosecutors or the defense.
   He said he was uncertain whether Illinois courts would allow
test results to be submitted as evidence.
   The actual clemency request Breen made Monday is submitted to
the prison review board, which makes a recommendation and passes
the request on to the governor.
</TEXT>
