<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Norway-BusCrash     08-15 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Bus Crash,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Carrying Children Hits Mountain; At Least 12 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish tour bus carrying mostly
youngsters slammed into the wall of a tunnel in a mountainous area
of western Norway on Monday, killing at least 12 people, police
said.
   The Swedish Foreign Ministry earlier said 13 people were killed
in the crash outside of Eidsfjord, 120 miles west of Oslo, but
Norwegian police put the death toll at 12.
   Bernt F. Moe, chief constable in the Hardanger district where
the crash occurred, said 34 people were in the tourist bus when the
vehicle hit a tunnel wall about 6:30 p.m. (12:30 p.m. EDT).
   Moe said the bus had Swedish license plates.
   Norway's news agency NTB said 23 of the passengers were
schoolchildren from Stockholm, but it was not reported how many of
those killed were children.
   ``We do not yet know why the accident happened, but it is a
mountainous area with steep hills and the road curves in several of
the tunnels in the area,'' Moe said.
   ``Practically all survivors were injured in one way or the other
... and all of them now have been taken to hospitals by helicopters
and ambulances that were directed to the site,'' Moe said.
   It was not immediately known where the bus originated or its
destination. Moe said the the bus was traveling in the direction of
Bergen, on Norway's western coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
