<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--SovietJournalists     08-15 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Soviet Journalists,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Journalists Housed 60 Miles from Superdome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds; Retransmitting a0772 to fix slug</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet journalists didn't expect to be
treated like honored guests at the Republican National Convention,
but they at least thought they would get housing somewhere in the
city of New Orleans.
   Instead, they are staying at a Holiday Inn some 60 miles from
the Superdome, where the convention is being held, in the outlying
town of Hammond.
   Three Washington-based Soviets from the news service Tass and
newspaper Pravda said their drive to the convention site is even
longer because they must travel by a route approved by the State
Department.
   They also had to book their rooms through the department, which
is routine, said Vitaly Gan of Pravda.
   He said they asked for their rooms in April and were told
everything in New Orleans was booked up.
   State Department officials told them, ``There are no rooms. No
chance. Sorry guys, no deliberate attempt to impede your work.''
   ``They said you're lucky not to be in Baton Rouge,'' added Oleg
Polyakovsky of Tass.
   At the State Department in Washington, spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley, gave a different version of what happened.
   She said one Soviet request was received in May and another in
July, and that the New Orleans hotels were in fact booked up.
   Some other New York-based Soviets applied in April and were
housed in downtown New Orleans, she said.
   However, one American journalist reported booking a room only
last week downtown, and another said a French Quarter hotel that is
housing many journalists told him space was available on Monday.
</TEXT>
