<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0725 08-15 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,330</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: New Throughout with Arrests, Other Protests</NOTE>
<HEAD>Protesters Show Up At Start Of GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators sought to disrupt a rally for
evangelist Pat Robertson and focus attention on the homeless and
AIDS as the Republican National Convention got under way Monday.
   Police said six demonstrators were arrested outside the hotel
where the Robertson rally was underway.
   While most rallies were peaceful, a shoving match broke out near
a fence outside the Superdome, the convention site, when some of
about 50 people protesting federal policy on acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, or AIDS, tried to push their way past. No one
was arrested.
   Before they arrived at the Superdome, protesters gave brief
speeches calling for more government support for social and medical
programs for AIDS victims. Then they lay down on the steps of city
hall for what they called a ``die-in.''
   At Lafayette Park, about six blocks from city hall and the
Superdome, officials had set up a small stage and sound system for
demonstrators to reserve 90-minute slots. The stage was empty much
of the day.
   One of the speakers, Na'im Dai-Y, head of the New Orleans
Coalition for the Homeless, said more attention should be paid to
the issues which prompted the demonstrations.
   Protest organizers have lamented about light turnouts at several
events. Dana Beal, 41, a demonstrator from New York, said many
groups are complacent about the fall elections.
   ``There's no turnout because everybody thinks George Bush is a
goner. He's behind in the polls,'' Beal said.
   The climate is another factor with both parties' conventions
held in the South this summer.
   It's difficult to ``persuade people to go from one hot place to
another hot place,'' Beal said.
   Daytime temperature in New Orleans have been in the 90s. Similar
conditions prevailed at the Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta last month.
</TEXT>
