<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS 10th graf to make minority sted majority leader.</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Other Races: GOP Senate Candidates Make Their Pitch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Senate candidates paraded their
wares at the GOP national convention Monday as the coordinator of
their drive to regain control of the Senate said none of them will
ever be ``outhustled'' by their Democratic opponents.
   Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., chairman of the Republican
Senatorial Campaign Committee, predicted the GOP will regain
control of the Senate in November because of good organization,
good candidates, good financing and a series of ``surprises,''
although he acknowleged that at the moment ``12 to 15 seats can
still go either way.''
   Thirty-two Senate seats are at risk this fall. The Republicans
hold 17 of those seats, the Democrats have 15.
   Boschwitz was optimistic.
   ``We think the GOP can regain control of the United States
Senate in 1988,'' he said. ``We think it's in the realm of reason
no matter how you look at it. These are good candidates. None of
them is going to be outhustled.''
   He predicted that the Republicans will take five of the six
states left open by retirements.
   He acknowleged that Republican candidates are behind in some
states. But he added: ``We think a number of these guys are going
to pull through.''
   Democrats won conntrol of the Senate in 1986 and now hold it
with a majority of 54-46.
   Boschwitz introduced the candidates at a news conference and
allotted 60 seconds of exposure to each of 16 candidates. Many took
longer than that.
   Susan Engeleiter, minority leader of the Wisconsin State Senate,
reported that her name identification is up from 15 percent to 65
percent.
   Pete Dawkins of New Jersey said that he has raised $5 million in
his race against Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and is looking to
raise another $2 million.
   Alan Keyes of Maryland, a black former ambassador, said he will
defeat veteran Democrat Paul Sarbanes and demonstrate that ``we can
split any bloc and take any vote.''
   Sen. David Karnes, R-Neb., who said his first poll showed a name
recognition factor of 1 percent, said he has pulled to a 44-44
deadheat with his opponent.
   Rep. Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he has achieved ``momentum'' in
his drive to replace Sen. John Stennis, D-Miss., who is retiring.
   Robert McMillan, a New York lawyer, said that he is introducing
``one new positive issue a week'' in his drive to defeat Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., whom he accused of absenting
himself from the Senate to write books.
   Rep. Beau Boulter, R-Texas., claimed he has a good chance to
unseat Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who is simultaneously running
for vice president.
   ``Our prediction is that Lloyd Bentsen will fall off both horses
he's trying to ride at the same time,'' Boulter said.
   Jay Wolfe, a Wwest Virginia businessman, claimed he has a chance
to unhorse Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W. Va., the Senate majority
leader. Byrd was first electyed to the Sernate in 1958.
   Equally optimistic was Joe Malone, a Massachusetts businessman,
who denied he is in the race against Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., as ``a sacrificial lamb.''
   ``I'm hearing people saying that 25 years of Ted Kennedy is
enough,'' he said. ``You're going to have the upset of the century.
</TEXT>
