<HEAD>Conservatives Celebrate Phyllis Schlafly Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Republicans, two of them vice
presidential hopefuls, paid tribute Monday to Phyllis Schlafly,
blasted Michael Dukakis and hailed what they hoped will be a GOP
triumph in November.
   Rep. Jack Kemp of New York called Mrs. Schlafly's Eagle Forum
``the most effective lobbying organization on behalf of a good
cause in the United States today.''
   Mrs. Schlafly, the conservative anti-feminist activist, returned
the compliment, calling Kemp the most exciting champion of SDI'' _
President Reagan's Star Wars missile defense system _ and ``the man
I think is the quarterback of the Reagan economic recovery.''
   About 40 people chanting ``Bigots for Bush'' demonstrated
outside the party at the New Orleans Museum of Art as various
luminaries arrived in their limousines. The protest was staged by
Act Up, a coalition which opposes what they view as inaction by the
government on the AIDS crisis.
   ``We're here to protest the cream of the right wing, who have
led the fight against people with AIDS, against lesbians and
gays,'' said Maxine Wolfe, of Brooklyn, N.Y.
   The forum presented brass clocks to Kemp and Jeane Kirkpatrick,
both vice presidential hopefuls; and to Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas,
Education Secretary William Bennett and Robert Bork, the former
federal appeals judge whose nomination to the Supreme Court was
rejected by the Senate.
   ``I certainly wish this had been the audience I was talking to
in the Senate Judiciary Committee,'' said Bork, whose appearance
drew the loudest applause.
   Bennett said Mrs. Schlafly's group had ``done more for the cause
of freedom in the world and moral decency in the country.'' He said
the two issues in the campaign were ``defense and freedom in the
world'' and ``nurture of children.''
   ``On both of them the Democrats are wrong and the Republican
Party is right,'' he said.
   Bork said that if the Dukakis is elected to the White House,
``the judges will effectively be chosen by Edward Kennedy,'' the
liberal Massachusetts senator who is a ranking Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee.
</TEXT>
