<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet-US     08-15 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet-US,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Asks Tibet To Remove Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's ambassador to China said Monday that
during a visit to Tibet he expressed concern about human rights
violations and asked the region's government to lift restrictions
on foreign journalists and other travelers.
   Ambassador Winston Lord Lord said he told Doje Cering, chairman
of the Tibet Autonomous Region, that ``if they want to have
informed reporting they ought to let in journalists as well as
anyone else.''
   Lord visited the Tibetan capital of Lhasa and the city of Xigaze
Aug. 4-10. He was the first U.S. ambassador to visit the remote
western region.
   Tibet, ruled by China, has been closed to all but a few selected
foreign reporters since pro-independence riots in Lhasa last fall
and again in March. Tibet had been trying to build a tourist
industry, but it also banned individual travelers, permitting only
organized group tours, after the violence.
   Fourteen foreign reporters who went to Lhasa to cover the
October riots were expelled from Tibet.
   Lord said Doje Cering ``seemed responsive.'' He did not
elaborate.
   The ambassador said that in his two-hour meeting with Doje
Cering he also brought up the issues of human rights and the status
of prisoners detained after the disturbances.
   China accused the U.S. Congress of interfering in its internal
affairs after the passage of several congressional resolutions last
year calling for an end to human rights violations in Tibet.
   Lord said Doje Cering told him that the human rights situation
has improved in Tibet since the Chinese Communists ended the
theocracy headed by the Dalai Lama, the spiritual head of Tibetan
Buddhism.
   Tibet came under Chinese military and political control in
1950-51. The Dalai Lama fled to India after a failed nationalist
revolt in 1959 and Tibet was made an autonomous region of China in
1965. Lord noted the United States recognizes China's sovereignty
over the region.
   The anti-Chinese demonstrations in October 1987 and last March
were led by Tibetan monks loyal to the Dalai Lama. They accuse the
Chinese government of undermining Tibetan social and religious
customs.
   Lord said Doje Cering told him that only 25 or 26 of the more
than 200 people detained after the March rioting remained in
prison, and eight of those still jailed were Buddhist monks or
nuns. It is beleved several dozen people were killed during the
violence in March.
   Lord said he asked permission for a U.S. official to visit a
jail but there was no immediate response.
</TEXT>
