<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--ConventionRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0689 08-15 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0689,750-1370</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top material throughout; Breaks into two takes. Evening
session skedded to begin 8 p.m. EDT; Reagan speech skedded at 10:35
p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans ridiculed Michael Dukakis from
the opening bell of their 34th national convention Monday as they
rallied behind George Bush's come-from-behind quest for the White
House. Delegates reached out for a final, emotional embrace with
President Reagan.
   Bush viewed the proceedings from afar, saying he hadn't settled
on a vice presidential partner for the fall campaign. But that
didn't stop the rumor mill _ or the jockeying by Rep. Jack Kemp,
Sen. Dan Quayle and the others interested in the post.
   Party chairman Frank Fahrenkopf had hardly pounded the opening
gavel at the Superdome podium when a parade of speakers began
thumping the Democrats. ``Americans know that Michael Dukakis will
trash them,'' said Alexander M. Haig Jr., Bush's one-time rival in
the primary campaign. He dismissed the Democratic candidate as a
``diminutive clerk from Massachusetts'' in a speech that drew a
disclaimer from the Bush campaign.
   ``Your party has lost its way, our party has found the way,''
former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont said in an appeal aimed at
Democrats.
   Bush's convention city arrival was set for Tuesday. But he had
no trouble making his presence felt, from his round of morning
television interviews to the notice to the news media that eight of
his 10 grandchildren would be visiting the city zoo.
   Outside the vast Superdome, six demonstrators were arrested at a
rally for evangelist Pat Robertson, one of several of Bush's
vanquished primary campaign rivals.
   
   FOLLOWING EMBARGOED FOR 9:30 p.m. EDT
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Inside the convention hall, the Republicans were praising the
man who twice led them to victory and declaring that Bush would
pilot the party to greater heights.
   In remarks prepared for delivery, Rep. Jack Kemp likened Reagan
to Abraham Lincoln for giving the ``whole world a birth of
freedom.'' He said, ``Mr. President, this is a powerful legacy that
you are handing us...I just want you and Nancy to know that under
the able leadership of George Bush, this party is going to take it
and run with it.''
   
   END EMBARGOED MATERIAL
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   It was Reagan's last full day in the spotlight at Bush's
convention, complete with an affectionate birthday party tribute to
his wife. ``In front of all our friends here today, let me say
thank you for all you do, thank you for your love and thank you for
just being you,'' he said.
   Said the first lady: ``We have had a wonderful run, but today it
is time for the Bushes to step into the political leading roles and
for the Reagans to step into the wings.''
   Republicans hoped that Bush's turn at center stage would
dramatically improve his standing against Dukakis. Most polls
indicate the vice president trailing, and a new ABC News poll gave
the Massachusetts governor a double-digit advantage.
   The vice president told interviewers that he hadn't settled on a
partner for the fall campaign, and hinted that some surprise names
were still on his private list. ``Nice try,'' was his
non-informative reply when one interviewer tried to penetrate the
secrecy.
   If there was no news about his pick, there was no shortage of
interest.
   ``We're trying to get Barbara Bush to put a recorder under the
vice president's pillow,'' said Barbara Campbell, GOP chairwoman in
Montana.
   Many of the contenders were in town for the convention and
related caucuses and receptions, some of them practically
auditioning for the job and others professing bewilderment that
they even figured in the speculation.
   ``If I were to be asked, I would be a terrific campaigner, and a
terrific candidate and a terrific vice president,'' said Kemp.
   ``We're not running,'' Sen. Bob Dole insisted as his wife and
co-contender Elizabeth sat at his side. But ``when the phone rings
she says, `Well, let me get it,''' he teased.
   But former Senate Majority Leader and White House chief of staff
Howard Baker said, ``I've no desire to be vice president.'' Quipped
Sen. William Armstrong, ``They can't possibly call me now, I have
an unlisted number.''
   Convention organizers passed the word that they would soon
assign aides to draft ``generic speeches'' for use by the person
Bush ultimately selects.
   Bush said he felt the ``pressure mounting'' as his big moment
approached. ``But I don't feel concerned about it. I have to be
what I am'' he said on ABC.
</TEXT>
