<HEAD>Quayle Says He Worries About Candidacy's Effect on His Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said Monday he would be
George Bush's running mate if asked, but that ``from a personal
standpoint'' he wouldn't choose to run for national office this
year.
   The Indiana senator, said to be on Bush's short list of
prospective vice presidential nominees, said he has reservations
about his candidacy's effect on his family. Quayle, 41, is married
and has three children.
   ``From a personal standpoint, if I had a time in my life to be
vice president, I wouldn't choose this time,'' he said.
   But, he added: ``If George Bush thinks I can offer the most to
the ticket ... Dan Quayle will sign up immediately.''
   His wife, Marilyn, also said she has reservations about ``the
total lack of privacy.'' Whether her husband gets the nomination or
not ``it's fine,'' she said. ``I'm not panting after it.''
   Quayle said his 14-year-old son, Tucker, is fascinated by the
prospect of his father running for vice president. Benjamin, the
Quayle's 11-year-old son, is ambiguous, his father said, and
9-year-old Corinne doesn't like the idea of her father spending
more time away from home.
   ``She told me, `Daddy, I really hope George Bush picks Bob
Dole,''' Quayle said. ``I said, `It may happen.'''
   In case he is selected, Quayle has begun to think about an
acceptance speech to the Republican National Convention.
   ``I haven't sat down to write. I think that would be bad luck,''
he said. ``But I do have some ideas.''
</TEXT>
