<HEAD>How Foreign Newspapers See Republican Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of foreign opinion on the Republic National
Convention which opened Monday in New Orleans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Frankfurter Rundschau, a left-leaning daily:
   ``In the coming four days, (George) Bush must show the U.S.A.
that he is the worthy heir to ... Ronald Reagan.
   ``He must prove that he is really as good as his supporters say
and not so indecisive and wishy-washy as the Democrats and a large
part of the media portray him.''
   _Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, a conservative newspaper:
   ``George Bush, in the role of crown prince, will have to fight
against numerous image problems.
   ``Trailing in the opinion polls, ... (he) will try to present a
picture of himself during the Louisiana gathering that is hoped to
shorten the distance between him and his (Democratic) rival,
Michael Dukakis.''
   _Die Welt, a conservative, Bonn-based daily:
   ``It is the most critical nominating convention for the
Republicans in the last 12 years. They have not had to operate so
much on the defense since Jimmy Carter challenged incumbent Gerald
Ford.
   ``The Republicans now realize that for them Reagan is an
indispensable factor in their presidential election campaign.''
   A West German television ARD report showed segments Monday of
President and Mrs. Reagan's arrival at the convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Le Figaro, a conservative newspaper in a report from its
correspondent in New Orleans:
   ``The Republicans asked themselves for a long time: should
Reagan and Bush appear together in New Orleans? The GOP delegates
do not hide their preference for the incumbent president and a
certain lukewarm feeling about the candidate Bush. It was therefore
judged more reasonable that the two men simply shake hands Tuesday
morning as they pass at the military airport at New Orleans.
   ``So tomorrow George Bush takes charge of the party.''
   _Le Monde, an afternoon daily, published a front-page cartoon
showing Reagan gesturing toward Bush, and saying, ``Believe me,
Dukakis is worse.''
   Le Monde correspondent Jan Krauze wrote:
   ``Mr. George Bush remains, after 7{ years as vice president and
more than a year of campaigning, a man about whom there are
questions ... A man who, despite eminent strengths and a long
experience in public life, has never succeeded in showing a quality
that is elementary but essential at this stage: that he really has
the stuff of a candidate, let alone that of a president.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEDEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Expressen, a liberal Stockholm newspaper:
   ``Is George Bush the right man as the next president in the
White House? ... Alas, there is the chance the image of Bush will
still be slightly blurred when ... (the convention) is over ...
Something appears to be stagnant, too stagnant around the
politician George Bush.''
   _Dagens Nyheter, independent:
   ``The Republican party convention in New Orleans will hardly be
exciting. ...
   ``An undeniable fact is that the Republicans' slogan `Peace and
Prosperity' is their best weapon against the Democrats. ... If Bush
simply manages to articulate this message of Republican triumph at
the convention ... he has won half the battle for the presidency.''
</TEXT>
