<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines-Politics     08-15 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Politics,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Meets to Form New Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel began
meeting opposition leaders Monday to form a new political party
opposed to President Corazon Aquino, whom he accused of
incompetence.
   Laurel met with Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, members of ousted
President Ferdinand Marcos' New Society Movement and other
opposition groups at the Club Pilipino, where Mrs. Aquino took her
oath as president on Feb. 25, 1986.
   Enrile and Laurel said at a news conference later that more
meetings would be held to unite the opposition and seek Mrs.
Aquino's ouster.
   ``We are just starting the evolution to unify the political
parties,'' said Enrile, the only opposition member in the 23-seat
Senate.
   ``Maybe then the administration will know there is a quiet
opposition strong enough to make a challenge.''
   Laurel said Saturday that Mrs. Aquino had failed to provide
strong leadership in the face of the country's communist rebellion
and in other economic and social crises.
   He urged her to step down and call new elections, and promised
to resign himself if she did. If she refused, he would stay in
office and join the opposition, Laurel said.
   Laurel told reporters Monday he had not received a reply from
Mrs. Aquino and could not say when he would formally announce an
alliance with the opposition.
   ``I do not want to pressure Mrs. Aquino,'' he added. ``The
moment it becomes obvious that she will not be stepping down, I
will be a free agent.''
   Mrs. Aquino has not commented directly on Laurel's call. But she
accused the vice president Saturday of withholding public support
during coup attempts in 1986 and in August 1987.
   Asked the president's reaction to Laurel's meeting Monday with
the opposition, spokesman Teodoro Benigno quoted Mrs. Aquino as
saying: ``I was under the impression they were together all along.''
   Sen. Sotero Laurel, the vice president's brother, told the upper
house he would remain with the administration, saying ``there is no
reason for me to dissociate myself from the coalition.''
   Previous opposition attempts to form a united political alliance
have faltered, mainly due to personal rivalries. Mrs. Aquino's
supporters rolled up landslides in congressional elections in May
1987.
   Mrs. Aquino ran under the banner of Salvador Laurel's United
Nationalist Democratic Organization in February 1986 elections that
led to Marcos' ouster after 20 years in power.
   Manila newspapers reported recently that 21 of 22 members of
that party were defecting to pro-Aquino parties. Many members left
the party last year.
   Enrile, fired as defense minister in November 1986 after a coup
attempt by his followers, said the opposition would stick to
constitutional methods and not attempt a coup.
   Share prices on the Manila Stock Exchange declined 5.92 points
Monday. Some traders said Laurel's announcement may have raised
fears among foreign investors about political stability here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
