<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Convention-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0726 08-15 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First 3 grafs Embargoed for Release at 10:40 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES With Reagan quotes in first 3 grafs, picking up Nancy
Reagan material below the dash</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some of Monday's
developments at the Republican National Convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Reagan Prepares `Very Personal' Address</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in a valedictory address to the Republican
National Convention, challenged the GOP delegates to ``never let
the fire go out or quit the fight.''
   ``I'm grateful to God for blessing me with a good life and a
long one,'' Reagan said in an address that mixed reminiscence of
his nearly eight years in the White House with praise for George
Bush, the GOP presidential nominee-in-waiting.
   The Monday night timing of the speech was picked by Reagan to
avoid stealing the spotlight from Bush, who officially becomes the
Republican presidential nominee Wednesday night.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Honored at GOP Luncheon</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan surprised his wife, Nancy, with an unscheduled appearance
Monday at a luncheon in her honor.
   ``I really can't imagine these last eight years without Nancy,''
he said. ``She once said the president has all kinds of advisers
and experts ... when it comes to foreign policy, the economy or
whatever, but no one to look after his needs as a human being.
Well, Nancy has done that.''
   Mrs. Reagan, moist-eyed at the tribute, said, ``The Republican
Party has given Ronnie and me eight of the most wonderful years we
have ever had.''
   But she added, ``Today the curtain begins to close on the Reagan
era of the Republican Party. We have had a wonderful run, but today
it is time for the Bushes to step into the political leading roles
and for the Reagans to step into the wings.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Bush Readies Acceptance Speech</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush, putting the finishing touches on his speech accepting the
GOP presidential nomination, conceded that Reagan will be a tough
act to follow.
   But he said he hoped to put his own stamp on the convention and
``not try to be a Ronald Reagan. There is only one.''
   Bush planned to watch Reagan's speech to the convention on
television at the vice presidential residence in Washington before
flying to New Orleans on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Potential Running Mates Make the Rounds</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Potential Republican vice presidents made a whirlwind round of
appearances Monday, some openly touting their qualifications,
others playing coy. In Washington, Bush said he still hadn't made
up his mind.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said he and his
wife, former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, left a
message on their telephone answering machine back in Washington:
``Just in case they got the wrong number. It just says, `I
accept.'''
   Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana told the Ohio delegation, ``I'm here
because George Bush knows who I am. He decided to put me on a
list.'' And Rep. Jack Kemp told reporters, ``I would be a terrific
campaigner and a terrific candidate and a terrific vice president.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Party's Also-Rans Step Into Spotlight _ Briefly</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Once bickering rivals taking aim on Bush's shortcomings, the
five men he bested in the Republican primaries assembled here this
week to sing his praises, attack Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis
and _ in at least one case _ pull a surprise.
   Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont improbably beckoned the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, the Democratic runner-up, to switch to the GOP. ``We need
you and you need us,'' du Pont said. ``As long as you have breath
yours will be a prominent voice, but as long as you speak as a
Democrat, you will never be a successful leader.'' The proposal was
greeted with silence by delegates.
   Alexander M. Haig Jr. contrasted Bush's ``safe and progressive''
policies with those of Dukakis, whom he called the ``diminutive
clerk from Massachusetts.''
   Du Pont and Haig spoke at Monday's opening morning session.
Dole, Kemp and Pat Robertson will speak in evening sessions on
prime-time TV.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Party Time Rolls On</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Lindy Boggs, a Louisiana Democrat, put aside political
differences to repay a political favor and on Monday hosted
visiting Republicans to celebrate at her house on bustling Bourbon
Street.
   Other festivities included welcomes for Robertson's die-hard
delegates, evening cruises on the Mississippi River and the start
of a three-night outdoor engagement by jazz trumpeter Al Hirt.
   In 1976, Boggs helped plan the Democratic National Convention in
New York City, and she recalled the warm welcome from the
Republicans among her hosts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
