<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IsraeliCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0728 08-15 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israeli Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0728,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two High-Flying Jets Collide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 1 graf after 3rd pvs, The announcement ... to identify
victims. PICKS up 4th graf pvs, Informed sources ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Israeli F-15 jet fighters on a training
flight collided over the Dead Sea area Monday and both pilots were
killed, the military command reported.
   It said Maj. Gen. Avihu Bin-Nun, the air force commander,
appointed a commission to investigate.
   The announcement was held up about 12 hours and gave no further
details. Strict censorship delays release of information on events
considered to involve national security.
   The army identified the pilots as Maj. Ehud Falk of the northern
Israeli kibbutz, or communal settlement, of Merhavya, and Lt. Col.
Ram Kuller of the northern kibbutz of Kfar Giladi.
   Informed sources in Washington said it was the first known
accident Israel's air force has had with the high-flying
American-built Eagle.
   Israel has about 50 of the planes, manufactured by the McDonnell
Douglas Corp., and ordered five more earlier in the summer.
   They were used with deadly force in an air war with Syria a
decade ago. More than 80 Syrian jets were shot down. None of the
Israeli F-15s were lost.
   The lopsided Israeli victory, and triumphs in other wars with
Arab enemies, has created an aura of pride and proficiency envied
by other air forces around the world.
   Two other F-15s, owned by Japan, crashed last June. The planes
cost about $30 million apiece.
   Normally, Israeli training exercises with the high-flying jets
are conducted over the Negev desert in the southern area of the
country, but speculation about Monday's accident centered on the
Israeli-held West bank.
   The F-15, nicknamed the Eagle by the U.S. Air Force, is the most
advanced, land-based jet fighter in the American inventory. The
twin-engine jet is designed to fly and fight in all weather
conditions and can soar at more than 2{ times the speed of sound.
   Israel is one of few foreign countries that has been allowed to
acquire the plane. Even so, the Eagles in its possession are not
the most advanced version of the F-15 produced by McDonnell Douglas.
   In recent years, the F-15's safety record has helped the U.S.
Air Force reduce its overall accident rate to some of the lowest
marks ever.
   The U.S. Air Force has had three mid-air mishaps involving F-15s
this year, but in each case the plane was only damaged, managed to
land without further incident and there were no fatalities.
   Overall, the Air Force said, there have been 15 mid-air
accidents.
   The F-15 was first flown in the United States in 1972 and was
delivered to U.S. Air Force combat squadrons beginning in 1976.
Since then, the Eagle has chalked up an overall accident rate of
3.0 mishaps per 100,000 flight hours, which for a jet fighter is
very low.
   The F-15 is normally armed with one internal 20mm cannon and two
types of air-to-air ``dogfighting'' missiles, the Sparrow and
Sidewinder. The single-seat fighter has a combat altitude ceiling
of 65,000 feet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
