<1ST_LINE>u p AM-WyomingPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0693 08-15 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyoming Primary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Probe Could Slow Decision In Senate Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with one graf to UPDATE with Justice Department
seeking injunction, judge scheduling hearing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming's primary election Tuesday
features a hotly contested Democratic U.S. Senate primary that
could take a week to untangle because of Justice Department
concerns over the handling of absentee ballots.
   State and federal officials tried Monday to avoid a lawsuit that
could leave the Democratic race undecided until next week, but
Secretary of State Kathy Karpan and Attorney General Joseph Meyer
refused to acknowledge that the state had violated federal election
laws.
   Unable to reach an agreement, the Justice Department asked U.S.
District Judge Clarence Brimmer on Monday to order state elections
officials to count any absentee ballots received through Aug. 22.
Brimmer scheduled a hearing on the matter for Tuesday.
   Several weeks ago, the Justice Department told Karpan it would
file a lawsuit over the mailing of absentee ballots since some
county clerks sent the ballots out just 26 days before the primary
instead of at least 30 days.
   Karpan, however, maintains that there are no specific guidelines
governing the mailing of absentee ballots.
   A wide margin of victory in the Senate primary among state Sen.
John Vinich, state schools Superintendent Lynn Simons and
University of Wyoming law professor Pete Maxfield would make the
Justice Department's concerns moot.
   State officials believe that less than 1,000 absentee ballots
are involved in the controversy, and with GOP registration in
Wyoming approaching 60 percent it's possible that just 400 of those
ballots were sent to Democrats and so only an extremely tight race
would be affected by those ballots.
   Meyer and Karpan pointed that out Monday to Justice Department
officials, who refused to wait until after the primary to decide
whether to take the state to court, said Karpan.
   The secretary of state, as a precaution against a court order,
did advise all 23 county clerks to hold any absentee ballots
received after the polls close Tuesday for at least one week.
   The Justice Department flap capped a primary election campaign
dominated by the Democratic Senate race, which easily overshadowed
uncompetitive U.S. House contests and state legislative races.
   Vinich, the first to seek the Democratic Senate nomination,
became labor's favorite and later attracted support from
environmentalists. Simons counted on the success of her three
previous campaigns for superintendent of public instruction.
Maxfield is a political neophyte.
   Incumbent U.S. Sen. Malcolm Wallop faced little opposition in
the Republican primary and spent much of the months leading up to
the election reconstructing a campaign machine that twice before
had led him to victory in November.
   When he did campaign, Wallop stressed the record he has built
over the past 12 years, pointing to his support of Western water
rights, a strong defense, and efforts to reduce the tax burdens on
the oil and gas industries.
   In the races for Wyoming's only House seat, Bryan Sharratt was
unopposed for the Democratic nomination while five-term incumbent
Republican Dick Cheney faced Bob Morris, who two years ago lost by
63,520 votes.
   If Cheny wins, his campaign would get off to a slow start. He's
scheduled to undergo heart bypass surgery Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
