<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0727 08-15 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest As Congress Meets To Certify Election Results</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE size of crowd in front of
Congress building as estimated by reporters at scene, and include
Cardenas' comments. PICKS up 3rd graf pvs: The 64-member...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 5,000 people claiming the July
elections were fraudulent clogged the steps of the Congress
building Monday as legislators began the process of certifying
election results.
   The crowd parted as Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, presidential candidate
of the leftist National Democratic Front, arrived to address
Congress. People showered Cardenas with confetti and shouted
insults at the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known
as the PRI.
   Cardenas told the legislators: ``What we are asking the members
of the Electoral College is one thing _ responsibility.
   ``We are asking that the elections be cleaned up ... of the
innumerable irregularities committed in the electoral process
principally by representatives of the official party, by municipal,
state and federal authorities.''
   The 64-member Senate and 500 members of the Chamber of Deputies
serve as the Electoral College, and the session is scheduled to run
through Aug. 31. Senators will certify election results for Senate
seats and the deputies will certify the results for seats in the
lower house. The Chamber of Deputies then will certify the count in
the presidential balloting.
   According to the Federal Election Commission, PRI candidate
Carlos Salinas de Gortari won the presidential contest with 50.36
percent of the vote. It said Cardenas, a former PRI governor and
senator who broke with the party last year over democratic reform,
received 31.12 percent, and Manuel J. Clouthier, candidate of the
conservative National Action Party, obtained 17.07 percent.
   The PRI has governed Mexico since 1929, dominating both national
and state politics, and it is virtually certain that the
legislators will name Salinas president-elect in the final stage of
this year's election process.
   The new president will be inaugurated Dec. 1, replacing
President Miguel de La Madrid who is completing his six-year term
and could not run for re-election under Mexican law.
   For the first two weeks of the Electoral College session the
legislators will review the results of the congressional races. The
results for 26 seats in the Chamber of Deputies and at least one
Senate seat are being challenged.
   Both right-wing and left-wing parties have accused the PRI of
fraud in the July 6 elections and have held protest rallies almost
daily.
   Opposition leaders claim the PRI cheated at the polling places
and doctored the voter registration rolls and totals released by
the Federal Election Commission.
   Despite the allegations, the election may have been the most
open since the PRI was founded in 1929.
   For the first time, the opposition won seats in the Senate,
gaining four although one is being challenged. And the PRI will
have have to contend with at least 227 opposition deputies in the
lower house, which has been expanded from 400 to 500 seats. The PRI
had 289 seats in the old, 400-seat chamber.
   The final count depends on the certification of the Electoral
College.
   In all previous presidential races the PRI presidential
candidate received at least 70 percent of the vote.
   The opposition is awaiting with particular interest the separate
returns on the presidential race from about 25,000 of the nation's
nearly 55,000 polling places, which the election commission did not
make public.
   The commission, after a week-long delay, announced overall
totals, saying Salinas, a 40-year-old former budget director, had
won, but it made public the tallies from only about 30,000 polling
places.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
