<DOCNO> AP880815-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 2152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-PuertoRico     08-15 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Puerto Rico,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Committee Hears Debate On Puerto Rico's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Puerto Rican speakers showed their deep
divisions at the United Nations Monday over whether statehood,
independence or keeping the island's status as a U.S. commonwealth
was the answer to its economic woes.
   The United Nations Decolonization Committee is holding hearings
this week on Puerto Rico's status, athough the United States
already has rejected the committee as anti-American.
   A diplomat on the committee, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the committee probably will issue a resolution Wednesday
calling for self-determination for Puerto Rico.
   William Felice, from an organization called the International
League for the Rights and Liberation of Peoples, said Puerto Rico
has become poorer than any U.S. state and should be granted
independence.
   But Manuel Medina, a member of a group called Puerto Ricans for
Statehood Inc., told the committee Puerto Rico would benefit more
by achieving statehood. Medina said the island still could preserve
its Spanish culture.
   Other speakers said the United States was actively trying to
block the pro-independence movement.
   Cuban Ambassador Oscar Oramas-Oliva introduced a resolution
which noted allegations that the Federal Bureau of Investigation
was using surveillance to keep track of Puerto Rican independence
activists.
   The United States seized Puerto Rico in 1898 during the
Spanish-American War. Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens.
   In 1952, Puerto Rican voters overwhelmingly passed a referendum
favoring commonwealth status, and the following year the General
Assembly removed Puerto Rico from its list of colonies.
   Since 1973, the U.N. Decolonization Committee has adopted
numerous resolutions calling Puerto Rico an illegal colony and
demanding self-determination for its people.
   The United States rejected those resolutions as interference in
U.S. internal affairs, and in 1971 walked off the committee, saying
it had an anti-American bias.
   Pro-statehood speakers told the committee Monday that 95 percent
of the island's voters rejected independence in a 1984 election and
that the solution to poverty is to make Puerto Rico the 51st U.S.
state.
   Jan Susler of the National Lawyers Guild described the U.S.
attitude toward the commonwealth as colonial, saying
pro-independence advocates are added to blacklists compiled by the
FBI and shared with the Puerto Rican police.
   She said Washington used the grand jury system to compel friends
and family members of pro-independence advocates to testify about
their activities or face jail, ``a method to politically intern
Puerto Rican independence activists.''
   A pro-statehood advocate, Elsie Valdes Ramos of the Movimiento
Unidos ante la Incertidumbre (the United Movement against
Uncertainty), said Spanish would not atrophy in Puerto Rico.
Rather, she said, mainland America will become bilingual in English
and Spanish, with Puerto Rico leading the way.
   Carlos Vizcarrondo Irizarry spoke for keeping the commonwealth.
He said the present U.S.-Puerto Rico relationship should be
maintained and developed, but he questioned whether the United
States desired to really improve the economy of the island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
