<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiberaceTrial     08-15 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberace Trial,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Liberace's `Penniless' Sister Has Been Paid $132,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accountant testified Monday that the
sister of the late Liberace has been paid nearly $132,000 since his
death 18 months ago and has $511,000 remaining in her trust account.
   The testimony conflicted with that given last week by Angie
Liberace, 74, who described herself as ``penniless.''
   Certified Public Accountant Gary Mohler revealed the figures in
state District Court, in the ongoing legal battle involving efforts
to remove the executor of Liberace's estate.
   Both sides rested Monday after weeks of testimony and closing
arguments were scheduled for Tuesday afternoon. Then it will be up
to Judge Michael Wendell to decide whether to remove Beverly Hills
attorney Joel Strote as executor of the Liberace estate and head of
the Liberace foundation.
   A sister and four former associates have filed suit seeking to
have Strote removed, saying he drew up the will and had Liberace
sign it when the famed pianist was too ill to comprehend what he
was doing.
   Those testifying on the attorney's behalf say Liberace was well
enough to know what he was doing when he signed the will Jan. 22,
1987, and that Strote had done a good job of increasing the value
of the estate.
   Strote testified he did not know what was taking the life of his
famous client until after the will was signed 13 days before
Liberace died Feb. 4, 1987, from AIDS complications.
   Angie Liberace testified last week she was ``penniless'' and had
to live off charity. But Mohler testified Monday that the sister
had been paid an average of $7,755 a month the first 17 months
following her brother's death.
   Mohler discounted the contention that Strote had kept money from
the sister.
   ``Mr. Strote was concerned that Angie be able to get the money
as needed,'' Mohler testified. ``Up until four or five months ago
we had been told to give her almost anything she wanted.''
   Mohler, who oversees the Angie Liberace Irrevocable Trust and
disburses its funds, said in recent months he has been asked to
obtain authority for any expenditures from the trust, which
Liberace set up for his sister.
   Strote testified earlier that he put restrictions on the account
because he was concerned over the rate which the money was being
spent.
   Mohler said he had been a member of the Liberace Foundation for
the Performing Arts since the entertainer formed the foundation in
1979 to provide scholarships at 30 colleges and universities.
Mohler said Strote had conducted foundation meetings since the
organization was formed.
</TEXT>
