<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Buckleys-Weicker,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buckley Clan Endorses Weicker's Democratic Opponent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of America's most prominent conservative
families used the start of the Republican National Convention
Monday to announce endorsement of Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr.'s
Democratic opponent in the November election.
   James F.W. Buckley of Tewksbury, Mass., speaking for the Buckley
family of Sharon, Conn., said that although the endorsement came in
a satiric National Review magazine article released Monday, its
intent was serious.
   Buckley, 32-year-old son of former New York Sen. James Buckley
and nephew of conservative columnist and editor William F. Buckley
Jr., announced the formation of ``Buckleys for Lieberman'' to
support Connecticut Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman.
   The younger Buckley told a news conference attended by three
reporters that the liberal Weicker is an embarrassment to the party
and ``an erratic man. He prides himself on being a pain to the
mainstream of the Republican Party.''
   Weicker, who draws much of his support from Democrats, is rated
20 points more liberal than Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., by
Americans for Democratic Action. Lieberman is a liberal Democrat.
   Weicker laughed off the endorsement and said it would be a boost
to his campaign.
   A spokeswoman for Lieberman, Marla Romash, welcomed the
endorsement, saying, ``We have finally found something where Bill
Buckley and Joe Lieberman agree.''
   Buckley, a computer programmer, hasn't lived in Connecticut
since 1980 and can't vote in the state. His father is now a federal
appeals court judge in Washington and his uncle lives in Stamford,
Conn.
   ``I really don't know that much about Lieberman,'' Buckley
conceded, but added that his family felt that even an unknown
quantity was preferable to Weicker.

</TEXT>
