<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Slayings     08-15 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Slayings,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Reportedly Kill 10 People During Meeting</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Troops fired without warning into a
group of youths holding a meeting in a remote town north of the
capital, killing 10 people, a Roman Catholic radio station reported
Monday.
   The victims were members of a youth club in Labadie, a small
town about 80 miles north of Port-Au-Prince, according to Radio
Soleil.
   The station attributed the report to a witness who identified
himself as a member of the youth group. Rev. Hugo Trieste, director
of Radio Soleil, said four other members of the group corroborated
the story.
   Monday was a national religious holiday commemorating the Feast
of Assumption and attempts to contact police, government officials
and civic organizations were unsuccessful.
   The station said the soldiers opened fire on the youths without
warning. Radio Soleil said four the 10 victims were identified, but
said the military did not permit the bodies of the others to be
examined.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy seized power in Haiti on June 19 after a
coup that ousted civilian President Leslie Manigat, who was in
office for four months. Namphy suspended Haiti's constitution on
July 8.
</TEXT>
