<HEAD>Fire Trucks Sent to Dome Before President Reagans Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrical short in an ABC-TV unit brought
fire trucks racing to the Louisiana Superdome three hours before
President Ronald Reagan was scheduled to speak Monday night to the
Republican National Convention on Monday.
   Fire officials said they sent extra trucks to the ABC-TV shed in
a parking lot outside the Superdome because of the magnitude of the
night's events.
   ``There was absolutely no fire,'' said Capt. Terry Tullier of
the New Orleans Fire Department.
   Tullier said normally two units would have responded to the
call, but because the president was involved, three pumpers, two
ladder units, and two district chiefs were sent to the Superdome.
   Bruce Fischhertz, an electrician working at the Superdome, said
the short caused no problems at ABC.
