<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Convicted Spy's Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday rejected an
appeal for a retrial by convicted spy Arne Treholt, ending the
former Foreign Ministry official's hopes for a reversal of his
20-year prison sentence.
   Treholt, 45, was sentenced by a district court in June 1985 to
Norway's maximum prison term. Prosecutors charged he had been
handing over Norway's secrets to Soviet and Iraqi agents since 1974.
   Treholt was arrested Jan. 20, 1984 when he was about to leave
Oslo's airport with classified documents, which the court said were
intended for his Soviet contacts.
   Police claimed last year they had uncovered a plan by Treholt to
escape to Africa with a girlfriend.
   Treholt's appeal was based on arguments that evidence was
misinterpreted, a police witness withheld important information and
there were technical mistakes during his trial.
   An appeal last year to the district court that sentenced him was
turned down and the one to the Supreme Court was his last legal
option.
</TEXT>
