<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Kemp 1stLd-Writethru a0722 08-15 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Kemp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout to show remarks delivered and add color.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kemp Says Bush Would Fulfill Reagan's `Powerful Legacy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kemp, addressing the convention he had
hoped would be nominating him, compared Ronald Reagan to Abraham
Lincoln on Monday and said George Bush would fulfill the
president's ``powerful legacy.''
   With his hopes still alive for becoming Bush's running mate,
Kemp praised the Reagan record and urged the Republican Party to
reach out to blacks, Hispanics and other minorities.
   ``As the party of Lincoln _ and Reagan _ we believe that freedom
and hope and opportunity can't be for just some of us,'' Kemp said.
   ``They've got to be for all of us. America has got to keep
moving ahead, and we can't leave anyone behind,'' the New York
congressman said.
   Kemp, whose bid for the Republican presidential nomination
fizzled in the early primaries, took the platform at the Republican
National Convention shortly before Reagan was delivering his
farewell to his party.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, watched from their seats in the
Superdome convention hall as Kemp spoke for 18 minutes.
   Kemp, a favorite of many in the party's right wing, was greeted
by red signs bearing his name and the words ``I Back Jack.''
   Kemp was the object of an intense campaign by conservatives, who
consider him Reagan's ideological heir, pressing for Bush to select
Kemp as his vice presidential nominee.
   Kemp and two other prominent Republicans, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, took the
podium on the opening night of the convention to describe for
delegates the Reagan successes.
   ``Abraham Lincoln, the founder of our Republican Party, gave
this nation a new birth of freedom. Ronald Reagan has helped give
the whole world a new birth of freedom,'' Kemp said.
   ``Nations around the world are following our example, choosing
lower tax rates, less government and more freedom,'' said Kemp, a
leading advocate of the income tax cut Reagan pushed through
Congress in his first term.
   Speaking to the president, Kemp said Reagan had ``brought us to
the threshold of a new era _ in fact, you've brought us over the
threshold.''
   ``You've shown us that we can do more than contain our
adversaries _ we can transcend them,'' Kemp said.
   He said Reagan's support for the Strategic Defense Initiative,
the ``Star Wars'' nuclear defense system, has ``shown us how we can
make even the threat of nuclear war obsolete.'' And he credited
Reagan with leading ``an entrepreneurial renaissance'' that has
``electrified the world and raised our standard of living'' while
creating 17 million jobs in five years.
   ``Mr. President, it's a powerful legacy that you are handing us
here in New Orleans,'' Kemp said. ``I just want you and Nancy to
know that, under the able leadership of George Bush, this party is
going to take it and run with it. And we're going to win in
November.''
</TEXT>
