<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 2241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-West-EastEurope     08-15 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-West-East Europe,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Market Has Diplomatic Relations with Some Soviet Bloc
Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community has
established diplomatic relations with some nations in its Soviet
bloc counterpart, COMECON, the West German government announced
Monday.
   Communist East Germany's state-run ADN news agency also reported
the development.
   Both the EEC, also known as the European Common Market, and
COMECOM are basically economic and trading blocs.
   ADN quoted East German Foreign Ministry spokesman Wolfgang Meyer
as saying the development contributes to the creation of a ``common
European house.''
   That phrase has been used in recent weeks by communist leaders
calling for closer links between Eastern and Western Europe.
   West German government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling released a
statement in Bonn saying, ``The European Economic Community (EEC)
has established official relations with East Germany as well as
with other member states of COMECON.''
   A West German government official said Monday night that at
least four of the 11 COMECON countries had established formal ties
with the EEC and others were expected to follow.
   The official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
identified the four as the Soviet Union, East Germany,
Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria.
   The other COMECON members are Hungary, Poland, Romania, Albania,
Mongolia, Cuba and Vietnam.
   Schmuelling's statement said the ``establishing of missions in
Brussels (the headquarters of the EEC) by COMECON member nations
can ease economic cooperation'' between the two blocs.
   Two months ago, COMECON, which stands for the Council for Mutual
Economic Assistance, and the EEC paved the way to establish formal
ties by signing documents of mutual recognition.
   Talks between the EEC and COMECON on establishing links began in
September 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0216 </DOCNO>
