<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MspiLegislature 1stLd-Writethru a0687 08-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mspi Legislature, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0687,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Near Reforms Inspired By FBI Corruption Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with conference committee agreement, details; picks up
next-to-last graf pvs `The House...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State House and Senate negotiators
reported reaching a compromise Monday on a county government
reorganization bill inspired in part by an FBI corruption
investigation in which 56 county supervisors were charged.
   After doubts earlier in the day on whether differences could be
settled between versions the two chambers approved in a special
legislative session, chief Senate negotiator Ollie Mohamed said an
agreement was reached. He said it would be brought before the full
House and Senate for approval Tuesday.
   ``I did not want to be held responsible, as I was held
responsible last May, that the Senate killed the bill,'' he said.
   The plan to restructure county government stemmed from an FBI
investigation of corrupt county purchasing practices that led to
federal charges ranging from mail fraud to extortion against 56
supervisors in 25 counties.
   Gov. Ray Mabus called the special session to consider
instituting countywide administration in place of Mississippi's
unique system in which most counties are split into districts in
which locally elected supervisors govern decisions such as
purchasing and road maintenance.
   Mohamed said his conferees had backed off a Senate provision
that would have required counties to purchase at least 10 percent
of equipment, supplies and services from businesses owned by
minorities and women.
   He said House conferees had accepted a provision granting ``home
rule'' to counties, but senators had allowed to be stricken
language prohibiting them from entering collective bargaining
agreements.
   Under home rule, counties would be allowed to take actions not
specifically prohibited by law. Under current statutes, they may
take only those actions expressly permitted. Cities were granted
home rule in 1985.
   Mohamed said negotiators had accepted the House language on the
wording of a referendum for voters to decide if their counties
would maintain roads on a countywide or district basis. He said
they had ``split'' on Senate language that would have exempted from
the referendum requirement those counties that were in
``substantial compliance'' with provisions of the bill on Oct. 1.
   The House and Senate agreed that a county supervisor could not
serve as county administrator, road manager, purchasing clerk,
receiving clerk or inventory clerk.
   Of the 56 supervisors charged, 42 have pleaded guilty, six have
been convicted, one has been acquitted, one died before going to
trial, one died after sentencing, and another was declared mentally
incompetent to stand trial. The remaining ones still have charges
pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
