<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeSillers Fails to Turn Over Property</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who allegedly bought a car, jewelry and
clothes with nearly $500,000 donated for her late son's three liver
transplants failed to turn the items over Monday and faces contempt
charges.
   Maria DeSillers also failed to post a $100,000 bond as an
alternative, said Karen Gievers, the court-appointed curator of
Ronnie DeSillers' estate who was supposed to receive the property.
   ``The order clearly has been violated,'' Ms. Gievers said. Ms.
DiSillers' attorney ``has indicated no bond has been posted, and I
have personal knowledge that the property has not been turned over
to me.''
   Ms. Gievers said she would file a contempt order Tuesday with
Dade Circuit Judge Francis Christie, who will then schedule a
hearing.
   Ronnie, 7, died at Pittsburgh Children's Hospital in April 1987
while awaiting his fourth transplant. Contributions, including
$1,000 from President Reagan, had poured in after a small fund
collected by Ronnie's school was reported stolen.
   Ms. DeSillers refuses to pay the hospital about $262,000 in
medical bills because she says her son received improper care, a
charge hospital administrators deny.
   She also has refused to cooperate with authorities and account
for the rest of the money.
   Ms. Gievers believes about $242,000 remains of the nearly
$690,000 donated for the boy's liver transplants.
   At a last-minute hearing before Christie earlier Monday, Ms.
DeSillers sought to put off complying with an order issued last
week that she turn the disputed items over to the court.
   Her attorney told the judge that items in Ms. DeSillers' home
were valued at $4,500, and that bonding companies refused to issue
a $100,000 bond for them.
   But Christie brushed aside the objection and ordered Ms.
DeSillers to turn the items, including a BMW luxury car, over to
Ms. Gievers by 4 p.m., or post the bond.
   Ms. Gievers said Ms. DeSillers never showed up.
</TEXT>
