<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Iranians     08-15 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Iranians,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Rescued Iranian Fishermen Going Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Iranian fishermen, rescued by the
U.S. Navy eight days ago from their drifting dinghy in the Gulf of
Oman, were headed home Monday after hopscotch visits to four
American warships.
   U.S. military sources said the five were to be turned over to
Omani authorities at Goat Island in the Strait of Hormuz and then
delivered to Iranian diplomatic officials. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The five were picked up Aug. 8 by the U.S. missile cruiser
Vincennes and said they had spent eight days adrift after their
fishing boat sank.
   They were without food and their water supply had run out. U.S.
military doctors said they were suffering from exposure,
deyhdration, hypothermia and rashes and probably could not have
survived another 24 hours.
   The Vincennes mistakenly shot down an Iranian civilian jetliner
on July 3 and all 290 persons aboard perished.
   The cruiser rescued the fishermen after lookouts saw the flash
of cigarette lighters and heard voices shouting in the pre-dawn
darkness.
   The Vincennes was ordered on another mission, according to the
U.S. sources, and the five were transferred to the missile cruiser
Texas that subsequently sent them to the frigate Fanning.
   After a week of Navy chow they were shifted to the destroyer
Robison that took them to the Omani base in the Hormuz Strait at
the southern end of the Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
