<HEAD>Sam Donaldson Stopped From Eavesdropping in Prime-Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC White House correspondent Sam Donaldson
didn't get far Monday night when he tried to listen in on a
telephone call from George Bush to the Texas delegation.
   ``We're going to eavesdrop on this,'' Donaldson said as he held
his microphone to the phone cradled by Sen. Phil Gramm.
   The Texas senator said in a loud voice, ``Listen, whoever you
choose, George, we're behind you.''
   ``Senator, could you ask the vice president a question?''
Donaldson said. But Gramm passed the phone like a hotcake to Lee
Atwater, Bush's campaign manager.
   ``We're going to sign off, but I'll see you tomorrow when you
get here,'' Atwater said. ``Sam Donaldson's yelling in my ear so
loud I can't even hear.''
   ``Let me talk to the vice president,'' Donaldon said.
   ``Hey, Sam, for once in your life, cool it for a minute,'' said
Atwater, who thrust the phone at Donaldson's ear _ covered by the
reporter's headset _ and then pulled it back.
   ``Well, they pay me to try to do my job,'' said Donaldson.
   As things calmed down, Atwater recounted the conversation,
saying Bush ``still plans to make the announcement on Thursday, but
he wants to reserve a little flexibility.''
   ``You're teasing us ... trying to keep the nation watching,''
said Donaldson.
   ``I'm not teasing you. I'm telling you what he said,'' said
Atwater.
   ``Gentlemen, back to you,'' Donaldson said to the network
anchors watching from ABC's convention booth overhead.
   ``There is the modern, electronic version of the smoke-filled
room,'' commented David Brinkley.
