<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChavezFast     08-15 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez Fast,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Urge Chavez to Consider Ending Fast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors said Monday farm labor leader
Cesar Chavez was weak and dizzy and should consider ending his
monthlong fast in protest of pesticide use on California table
grapes.
   ``We are extremely concerned about the possibility of
irreversible damage to his health,'' the physicians said in a
prepared statement. ``The longer he continues his water-only fast,
the closer he comes to reaching the point where his life will be in
danger.''
   Chavez said he would consider it, said Dr. Marion Moses.
   Chavez, whose fast was in its 30th day Monday, had not suffered
irreversible damage even though he had lost 30 pounds, 17 percent
of his original 174-pound weight, Moses said.
   But the joint statement signed by Moses, Dr. Fidel Huerta and
Dr. Augusto Ortiz said Chavez was weak and dizzy, has a high uric
acid level, which is dangerous to his internal organs, and is
having increased difficulty maintaining proper fluids.
   Chavez began a water-only fast on July 17 to call attention to
the United Farm Workers' boycott of California table grapes and
claims that workers and consumers are endangered by five pesticides.
   Chavez raised the pesticide issue in 1986 and demanded that
California growers stop using Captan, Dinoseb, methyl bromide,
Parathion and Phosdrin. The union contends tolerance levels of
those chemicals ``were set without toxicity data or any information
concerning their long-term effects on people's health and the
environment.''
   Jim Wells, a pesticide expert with the state Department of Food
and Agriculture, countered that all five chemicals are tightly
controlled.
   Chavez conducted a 25-day fast during the 1968 grape boycott. He
conducted a 24-day fast in 1972 to protest adoption of a
right-to-work law in Arizona.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
