<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0831 08-15 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0831,500</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with Reagan quote.</NOTE>
<HEAD>The One Man Who Needed No Introduction Got Several</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``There was the good news and bad news from
Atlanta. The good news was that Dukakis laid all those cards on the
table. The bad news is they were all face down.''
   Laughter. Applause.
   ``The Democrats asked the wrong question. The question was not
`where's George?' The question is, `who's Mike?'''
   Laughter. Applause.
   This was the introduction to the introduction, or to be more
exact, Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming introducing former Sen. Paul
Laxalt of Nevada, whose job it was to introduce Ronald Reagan.
   And Reagan, of course, was the only person at the Republican
National Convention who needed introduction to no one.
   But political conventions being what they are, Laxalt spent five
minutes welcoming Reagan, who was about to enter the hall.
   ``I don't have to give a ringing political speech,'' said
Laxalt, who was described by Simpson as the president's ``first
friend.''
   ``Nor do I have to speak of his many political accomplishments
and the legacy he leaves,'' said Laxalt. Instead, he spoke of
Reagan the person.
   ``To Ronald Reagan, the Golden Rule is very much alive. ... He
has faithfully stuck to his conservative guns. ... His eternal
optimism is infectious _ if there's a pony in the pile, give him
time and he'll find it every time.''
   Then Reagan entered with his wife and the applause and cheering
from the delegates and visitors lasted exactly the five minutes it
had been scheduled.
   
   Many in the huge Superdome couldn't see the first couple in
person so they watched the entrance via huge screens on three sides
of the hall. It presented a peculiar picture of heads turned in all
directions.
   This was the night for lauding the president who's about to
leave. The praise for the man Republicans hope will be the
president-to-be comes later.
   Jack Kemp, the congressman from New York and former football
star, likened Reagan to the Gipper _ a character that actor Reagan
played in the movie ``Knute Rockne.''
   ``We all remember the famous line about winning one for the
Gipper,'' Kemp said. But, he said he preferred another scene, the
one in which Rockne tells the Gipper he would be given the ball and
he should just run with it.
   ``Ronald Reagan, the Gipper, just looks at him with that smile
of his,'' Kemp recalled, ``and says, `how far, Coach?'''
   Kemp turned toward Reagan, sitting across the hall in a box
decorated with the presidential scene.
   ``Well, Mr. President,'' Kemp said, ``when America gave you the
ball eight years ago, no one could have imagined how far you would
carry it.''
   Later, Reagan also evoked the old movie, with a request for
George Bush.
   ``George,'' said the president, ``go out there and make it one
more for the Gipper.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0535EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     08-15 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0573</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A calculating error by Reagan administration
budget experts cannot be rectified by law and is preventing
Congress from enacting $1.2 billion in additional spending programs
for 1989.
   The over-calculation of the size of next year's deficit was
pointed out to congressional aides in the last few days by the
agency that committed it _ the White House's Office of Management
and Budget.
   OMB officials confirmed this past week that the mistake had been
made, and said they had told congressional staff members about it.
   As the $1.1 trillion federal budget goes, $1.2 billion normally
would barely register a tick.
   But the amount is significant because it means that Congress
will have to squeeze spending for anti-drug programs, the homeless,
the hungry and other popular causes under a $1.8 billion ceiling,
rather than what should be a $3 billion limit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet scientists, ignoring a
diplomatic gaffe half a world away, are conducting rehearsals for
this week's historic nuclear experiment that will mark a milestone
in the atomic age.
   Wednesday's test blast comes nearly four years after President
Reagan first proposed such a project during a speech to the United
Nations.
   The joint verification experiment is designed to measure each
country's ability to monitor the size of the other's test.
Verification could lead to ratification of treaties limiting the
size of nuclear tests, which were signed in the 1974 and 1976 but
never ratified.
   Scientists from the United States and the Soviet Union will be
measuring the explosive punch of a thermonuclear device encased in
a steel canister buried 2,050 feet beneath a picturesque mesa, 130
miles northwest of Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing the potential of terrorist attack,
members of Congress are putting the Reagan administration on notice
that they will strongly oppose any move to permit sea shipment of
plutonium from Europe to Japan.
   ``Here you have an administration that is supposedly waging a
war on terrorism, but promoting a policy that could make terrorism
easy,'' said Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., a member of the House
Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The issue stems from a recently signed U.S.-Japan nuclear
cooperation treaty that authorizes shipments by air of plutonium
from reprocessing plants in Europe back to Japan, where it will be
used to fuel nuclear power plants.
   The plutonium, which also could be utilized for nuclear weapons,
is controlled by the U.S. government because the nuclear fuel
originated in the United States.
   Proceeding with the air shipments was made contingent upon
development of crash-proof shipping casks, which so far has proven
unachievable.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College students reduced their drinking more if
their assumptions about alcohol's benefits were challenged than if
they were warned about its dangers, psychologists say.
   ``We're looking at this as an approach to prevention'' of
problem drinking, said researcher Renelle Massey of the University
of South Florida at Tampa.
   Study results support a theory that one reason people drink is
because they think it will make them funny, brave, more sociable,
sexier, more assertive or better in some other way, she said.
   Levels of such ``expectancies'' have been linked to alcohol
consumption in previous studies, she said in an interview Sunday at
the American Psychological Association's annual meeting.
</TEXT>
