<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Jordan'sPrince Adv22   08-15 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan's Prince, Adv 22,0797</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Aug. 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan Urges Economic Reform and Openness</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heir to Jordan's throne is a prince who
fosters economic reform and political openness for his nation in
the midst of Middle East turmoil.
   ``There has been a continous cry on my part ... for a need to
think seriously of Jordanian perestroika,'' said Prince Hassan,
referring to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's plans to
revitalize Soviet society.
   The 41-year-old younger brother of King Hussein is regarded as
one of the Arab world's most visible intellectuals.
   For two decades, the Oxford-educated prince has guided
development planning in this country of 2.8 million people. He has
overseen remarkable economic growth in a land blessed by education
but nearly barren of natural resources.
   With an economic slump squeezing the region, Hassan has urged
bureaucratic reforms and calls for economic policies aimed at
making the Hashemite desert kingdom a center for services and
technology.
   Hassan sees economic success as a major element of identity for
his 40-year-old country, along with his family's 1,000-year history
as rulers of Mecca.
   He said in an interview with The Associated Press the task of
rebuilding Jordan following the disastrous 1967 war with Israel,
which flooded the country with refugees, was one of ``restating
Jordan's credibility on the basis of merit; that Jordan is a
country that works.''
   He also describes the war as his greatest trauma. Most of his
published works have been devoted to the Palestine problem, urging
a moderate road to Arab-Israeli peace. About half or more of
Jordan's population are Palestinians; most of the remainder are
Bedouin Arabs, like King Hussein and Prince Hassan.
   Jordan's failure in its efforts for Arab-Israeli peace led King
Hussein in early August to renounce responsibility for the
Palestinians on the Israeli-occupied West Bank.
   Hussein's decision is expected to force Jordan to forge a new
identity for itself, one in which Hassan likely would play a role
because of his leadership of the kingdom's economic and research
institutions.
   The prince himself is key to the survival of the last Hashemite
monarchy. His family, descended from Islam's Prophet Mohammed, once
ruled Arabia, Syria and Iraq as well as Jordan. It led the Arabs to
independence from Ottoman Turkey in a World War I alliance with
Britain.
   His patronage of Jordan's intellectual and business communities,
as well as his periodic tours of army installations, are partly
designed to help broaden his base in a country so closely
identified with its ruler that a common cliche says: ``King Hussein
is Jordan and Jordan is King Hussein.''
   Hassan was an Oxford undergraduate in Oriental studies when
Hussein named him crown prince in 1965. He said his Oxford years
were ``definitely the happiest years of my life,'' and an academic
aura still clings to him.
   He described himself as ``a magpie reader,'' sampling a wide
range of subjects.
   But he said Gorbachev's book, ``Perestroika,'' was the most
fascinating thing he had read lately _ along with British
philosopher Bertrand Russell's ``In Praise of Idleness.''
   Short, stocky and athletic, the prince seldom seems idle.
   He spends his spare time practicing Chinese martial arts,
playing squash or polo, and with his family.
   The prince has four children by his Pakistani-born wife,
Princess Tharwat, but none have a direct line to the throne. King
Hussein has decreed that his own third son, Prince Aly, is in line
after Hassan.
   Jordanian television often shows Hassan addressing two or three
seminars or conferences a day in Jordan, or attending international
conferences on development or humanitarian affairs.
   He helped found most of the country's chief think tanks, and
said he enjoys seminars where he can step out of his palace role.
   ``Nobody's going to stand up to a person of authority and
express their views as clearly as they should,'' he said.
   Hassan has repeatedly urged freer debate on domestic policy
issues, occasionally bumping heads with government officials
concerned about criticism.
   The prince said Jordan should ``emphasize our basic renewable
resource, which is creative thought and political will based on an
openness which I think has characterized King Hussein's style.''
   He has also prodded Arabs to develop their own ``centers of
excellence'' and said he was ``somewhat resentful'' of the Western
dominance of Middle Eastern studies.
   ``I think that regional self-reliance in the intellectual field
is the only way of tempering that (Western) naivite, which is
welcome in terms of its innocence but tiresome in terms of its
clumsiness,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Aug. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
