<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv23,0480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Aug. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Aug. 23, the 236th day of 1988. There are 130
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In the early morning hours of Aug. 23, 1927, Italian-born
anarchists Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were executed in
Boston for the murders of two men during a 1920 payroll robbery.
The case had drawn widespread controversy, with many convinced that
Sacco and Vanzetti had been convicted for their political beliefs.
   On this date:
   In 1754, France's King Louis XVI was born at Versailles.
   In 1785, U.S. naval hero Oliver Hazard Perry was born in South
Kingstown, R.I.
   In 1838, one of the first colleges for women, Mount Holyoke
Female Seminary in South Hadley, Mass., graduated its first
students.
   In 1914, Japan declared war on Germany in World War I.
   In 1926, silent film star Rudolph Valentino died in New York at
age 31.
   In 1944, Romanian prime minister Ion Antonescu was overthrown,
paving the way for his country to abandon the Axis in favor of the
Allies.
   In 1947, an audience at the Hollywood Bowl heard President Harry
S. Truman's daughter, Margaret, give her first public concert as a
singer.
   In 1960, Broadway librettist Oscar Hammerstein II died in
Doylestown, Pa.
   In 1972, the Republican national convention, meeting in Miami
Beach, Fla., nominated Vice President Spiro T. Agnew for a second
term. (The vote was overwhelming, but not unanimous _ one vote went
to NBC newsman David Brinkley.)
   In 1979, Soviet dancer Alexander Godunov defected while the
Bolshoi Ballet was on tour in New York.
   Ten years ago: Leftist guerrillas who had seized the National
Palace in Managua, Nicaragua, the day before threatened to execute
their hostages unless their demands, which included the release of
political prisoners, were met.
   Five years ago: In an address to the American Legion in Seattle,
President Reagan charged that the anti-nuclear movement ``would
wage peace by weakening the free. That just doesn't make sense.''
   One year ago: Seven Democratic presidential hopefuls traded
gentle barbs at a debate in Des Moines, Iowa, with Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis repeatedly called upon to defend his claims of
economic revival in his home state.
   Today's birthdays: Actor-dancer Gene Kelly is 76. Orchestra
leader Bob Crosby is 75. Actress Vera Miles is 58. Political
satirist Mark Russell is 56. Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., is 55.
Actress Barbara Eden is 54. Ballet dancer Patricia McBride is 46.
Actress Shelley Long is 39. Actor-singer Rick Springfield is 39.
Queen Noor of Jordan is 37.
   Thought for today: ``If you board the wrong train, it is no use
running along the corridor in the other direction.'' _ Dietrich
Bonhoeffer, German theologian (1906-1945).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
