<DOCNO> AP880815-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--CuttingEdge Adv28-2Takes   08-15 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Cutting Edge, Adv 28-2 Takes,0713</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ When the skiing is done with and Aspen, Colo.,
settles down to a more placid way, it's an enviable setting for
thinkers of cosmic thoughts. That's what a large group of notables,
who have much to do with America's designs for living, does for one
very cerebral week each year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly 40 years, when other people's
thoughts turn to vacations and light summer reading, a select
contingent of conventioneers has descended on this pastoral Alpine
playground to contemplate the state of civilization.
   This year again, some 1,500 creative people who influence the
way much of the world buys products, wears clothes, reads books,
drives cars, eats, sleeps and works came to ponder and discuss.
Their theme was ``The Cutting Edge.''
   Or, put another way, where are we as a global society, as the
human race? That was the question co-chairmen Jay Chiat, a Los
Angeles-based advertising man, and Henry Wolf, a New York-based
photographer and graphic designer, bit off and left for the 38th
International Design Conference to chew.
   ``...it seems that many of us have serious doubts that
significant progress has taken place in literature, advertising,
architecture, and product and graphic design since the '60s,''
Chiat said in the conference program. ``Is this true? If so, why?
If not, why don't we believe it? Is there a cutting edge? Or is it
as dull out there as some of us think?''
   The IDCA was started in 1951 by the late Walter Paepke, chairman
of the Container Corporation of America. Paepke was a millionaire
businessman who, along with his wife, Elizabeth, who still lives in
Aspen, set out to make this mostly dilapidated Victorian-era
Colorado mining town a mecca for intellectuals and artists. The
entertainers and jet set followed.
   The first conference, ``Design as a Function of Management,''
explored the relationship of design to business.
   In 1951, TV was a fledgling medium that would change the world.
The first commercial color telecast was aired and dacron suits,
sugarless chewing gum, orlon and a commercial electronic computer
made their debut.
   In the intervening years, the folks who've designed everything
from cars to computers to commercials, the graphic artists,
painters, writers, social scientists, museum directors, film-makers
_ the men and women who decorate and stimulate our physical and
mental lives _ have made the pilgrimage to Aspen to learn how
design is integrated into politics, art, business, science,
education, and philosophy.
   Ted Goudvis, a retired mining engineer and Aspen resident who's
been attending the conference for eight years, found that the
speakers last June had a more ``idealistic slant.''
   Some ominous notes intruded. Dr. Howard H. Hiatt, former dean of
the Harvard School of Public Health and currently senior physician
at the Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, told the audience
that the AIDS toll in the United States ``is already catastrophic
but we have only seen the beginning.''
   He urged more government funding to combat acquired immune
deficiency syndrome and a national system of health care. ``I hope
the cutting edge, the state of things to be, will be a more humane
society,'' he said.
   A group of museum directors, including Kinshasha Conwill,
executive director of the Studio Museum in Harlem, and Richard
Koshalek, director of the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los
Angeles, noted that 80 percent of Americans live in cities and said
art has to go to the people.
   ``We defined space in Los Angeles that is outlined by four
freeways and we consider that our turf,'' said Koshalek, who's held
art exhibits in parking lots and now has a revolving collection in
a hardware store named The Temporary Contemporary.
   Ms. Conwill said she believed ``the current American art scene
is lacking in originality and vigor, and black artists are absent
from that arena,'' but added that her museum was spotlighting Negro
artists in ``probably the most important black community in the
world, Harlem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--CuttingEdge Adv28-1stAdd   08-15 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Cutting Edge, Adv 28-1st Add,0680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>ASPEN, Colo.: world, Harlem.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The conference was held among the manicured meadows of the Aspen
Institute for Humanistic Studies, also founded by the Paepkes.
Right away, the snack bar menu revealed it wasn't an ordinary
convention. Forget greasy burgers and fries, this was Aspen, home
of the too-thin, the too-rich. Here you have toubouleh sandwiches,
yogurt and cucumber soup, and brie with grapes.
   The participants were overwhelmingly Big City Dwellers From the
Coasts. Because most were designers, wardrobes ran the gamut from
silks to sleaze, black to brazen, polished to punk. The crowd's
differentness became a sameness.
   Set amid wildflowers and fresh air, spectacular sunsets and
snowcapped mountains, the gathering had its share of famous names.
   Former television talk show host Dick Cavett acted as a floating
moderator.
   David Puttnam, producer of 29 films, including ``Chariots of
Fire'' and ``The Killing Fields,'' talked about his disagreements
with the chiefs at Coca Cola, Inc., parent company of Columbia
Studios which Puttnam recently headed, and the state of movies
today.
   ``A movie should start out attempting to be everything _ good,
exciting, commercial in the best sense _ and leave an aftertaste,''
Puttnam said. ``Where we are at now is a lack of ambition in what
films can do. The dream in cinema is gone. I think money corrupts
the creative process. The sheer cost of making a film today takes
away (creative) risk.''
   Puttnam, a Briton who lives in London and now produces films for
Warner Brothers Studios, said unwillingness to take creative
chances pervades American corporate life today.
   ``There is this extraordinary pressure to perform, to
out-perform last year, to out-perform this year,'' said Puttnam, a
fan of smaller-budget movies with unknown actors and directors.
``The reason we are chasing the Japanese is that the Japanese have
this extraordinary ability to make a decision and then take a long
view.''
   Paul Goldberger, architecture critic of The New York Times since
1973, said that in the past few years ``there has been a tendency
to believe that the most profound effect of architecture has been
deciding what kind of molding to put on the $3 million beach house
of an investment banker.''
   ``Architects have become so obsessed with size, corporate power
and the lushness of detail that the idea that architecture serves a
social purpose has been forgotten,'' Goldberger said.
   Feminist Betty Friedan, founder of the National Organization for
Women and author of ``The Feminine Mystique'' and ``The Second
Stage'' and now at work on ``The Fountain of Age,'' said a new
feminine mystique is telling American women to give up the social,
economic and legal gains of the past two decades and ``put on the
girdle again, put on the miniskirt'' and go home again.
   ``The answer is `repent of your ways, of your feminist dreams,
of your ideas and your aspirations...,''' Friedan said facetiously,
nearly drowned out by laughter and applause. ``This economy would
really collapse if the women went home again, to say nothing of the
family's economy.''
   Friedan thought the nation was coming to the end of an era of
devotion to greed and gave it a verbal shove:
   ``The nation's resources are great enough to accept public
responsibility. ...If we let go unchallenged this culture of greed,
of privatism, not only are the poor, the homeless, the underclass
going to create (a possible) depression, the middle class, the
professional class and our children, earning more than we did when
we were their age, are going to have a mean life.''
   So what is The Cutting Edge, and where is it?
   ``The cutting edge is not always where we assume it to be,''
said IDCA co-chairman Wolf. ``It crops up in unpredictable places
and the prognosticators have a very hard time finding it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
