<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brazil's Japanese Rediscovering their Heritage</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: An accompanying story is BC-Brazil's Japanese-Successes,
b0661.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On an April day in 1908, the steamship
Kasato Maru set sail from Kobe, Japan, with 781 Japanese peasants
contracted to work on the coffee plantations of Brazil. Their plan
was to come home in two to five years and start new lives with
their earnings.
   But most stayed in Brazil to become the founders of what today
is the world's largest Japanese community outside Japan _ 1,168,000
strong.
   They are Brazilians first, they tell you, but as Japan has risen
in economic power and influence across the world, they are feeling
the pull of the land of their ancestors:
   _Andre Hori, 20, wearing faded blue jeans and a white sweat
shirt, kneels silently on a straw mat, his eyes riveted on the
kimono-clad instructor who patiently goes through the precise
movements of the ``chado,'' centuries-old Japanese tea ceremony.
   _A few blocks away in downtown Sao Paulo, Hifumi Konno, 55, in a
blue and white cotton kimono, rehearses the delicate and intricate
steps of the ``Kyo Fujima Ryo,'' one of Japan's traditional
classical dance forms.
   The renewed interest in homeland traditions is a relatively
recent phenomenon among Brazil's Japanese, according to Luis
Masahiro Hanada, executive secretary of the Brazil-Japan Cultural
Alliance.
   ``For many years, especially after Japan's defeat in World War
II, the main concern in the community was to integrate, to be as
Brazilian as possible. This led to an almost total rejection of
anything identified with Japan,'' he said in an interview.
   ``But in the 1970s, as Japan prospered, many in the community
started feeling a strong sense of curiosity and a need to
understand and recover a cultural past which for years had been
ignored.''
   He added that over the past 10 years the number of people
learning Japanese at the Cultural Alliance ``has been increasing by
15 percent annually.'' The alliance houses Brazil's largest
Japanese-language school, with more than 2,000 students.
   Similar increases have been registered in courses of traditional
Japanese art forms such as flower arrangements, origami (paper
folding) and caligraphy, he said.
   Andre Hori explained why he decided to learn the tea ceremony
and take Japanese language classes.
   ``I always felt that Japan's recovery after the war and its
current economic strength could best be understood by studying its
culture, something I knew nothing about,'' he said.
   Kaesundri Wakisaka, one the directors of the Japanese-Brazilian
Research Center, said another important reason for the community's
renewed interest in its cultural background is ``a kind of
instinctive concern that one day these traditions may disappear.''
   During a break in her dance rehearsals, Mrs. Konno said, ``If we
don't learn and transmit our cultural heritage to the younger
generations, it will all fade away.''
   She said that despite her efforts, her two daughters have shown
little interest ``in following my example. They have become too
Brazilian.''
   Wakisaka said the Japanese community's assimilation into
Brazilian culture and society was ``progressing so smoothly and
steadily that in 50 years it will be almost impossible to
distinguish it as an ethnically different group.''
   He said the main reason was growing number of interracial
marriages. Wakisaka estimated there were about 115,00 marriages in
Brazil between the descendants of Japanese and non-Japanese.
   Most Japanese-Brazilians interviewed insisted that their life
styles and way of thinking are Brazilian, but they make clear their
heritage is not far behind.
   Kenichi Yamai, a 58-year-old attorney said, ``I am so Brazilian
that I only remember my Japanese background when I look at myself
in the mirror.''
   But, sitting on a beige sofa in his three bedroom apartment, he
said he never misses a chapter of ``Takeda Shigen'' (The Great
Samurai), a soap opera produced in Japan and aired every Sunday in
Japanese by a local TV station.
   He also starts his day reading Sao Paulo Shimbun, one of three
Japanese-language newspapers published in Sao Paulo.
   With his wife Emi sitting at his side, Yamai also said he
insisted that his daughter Regina, a 28-year-old dentist, ``marry a
Japanese because mixed marriages never work out. And when my two
sons are ready to marry, I will make the same demand.''
   Carlos Nakayashi, a 43-year-old economist, said, ``No matter how
Brazilian we feel or act or are seen by others, there is no denying
our heritage. It's in our blood and will never go away.''
   For Harumi Kawasaki, a 50-year-old teacher in a Japanese
language school, ``being Japanese in Brazil is like having a split
personality, for we are constantly straddling two entirely
different cultures.''
</TEXT>
