<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil's Japanese, Adv 21-1st add,0673</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>SAO PAULO: different cultures.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After pouring a cup of Japanese tea and turning down the music
of Brazilian pop singer Milton Nascimento on the stereo, Tania
Yamura Delmanto said re are brief sketches of some of the
Japanese who made a success in Brazil:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MANABUA MABE, artist _ Born in Japan in 1924, Mabe immigrated to
Brazil with his parents in 1935. After 10 years of picking coffee
beans, he started painting figurative art but soon moved to
abstractionist paintings. His first public recognition as an artist
came in 1957 when he won the Best National Painter Award at the Sao
Paulo Bienal International Art Exhibition. Two years later he was
awarded the Best Foreign Painter Award at the Paris Bienal Art
Show. Mabe has a studio in New York but continues to paint at his
home in Sao Paulo, exhibiting his work in Brazil and abroad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TOMIE OHTAKE, artist _ Born in Japan in 1914, she came to Brazil
in 1936 to visit relatives but decided to stay after the
Sino-Japanese War broke out in 1937 and falling in love with
agronomist Ruy Ohtake, whom she married. She started painting as a
hobby, but friends and relatives insisted she go public and in 1957
she exhibited her work at Sao Paulo's Museum of Modern Art. In
September she will have a one-woman show in Japan _ one of many
countries where her paintings can be found.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FUJIO TACHIBANA, banker _ He came to Brazil as a 20-year-old in
1932 to work on a coffee plantation. Because of his training as an
accountant, he landed a job in 1938 with the Bratac Banking House
that two years later became the America do Sul Bank, one of
Brazil's largest. He became president in 1978 and still holds that
prestigious position.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HIRO HI URUSHIMA, entrepreneur _ He was 11 years old when he
arrived in Brazil with his parents and seven brothers in 1936. Like
most other Japanese immigrants, he worked on a coffee plantation.
But in 1938 his family left the plantation and Urushima went to
work in a radio repair shop in the city of Sao Paulo. In the 1940s
he started his own business building transformers and radio
receivers. In 1954 he began building car radios and selling them to
stores and individuals. Nine years later he founded Motoradio,
which today employs more than 2,000 workers at three different
factories making table and car radios as well as a wide variety of
electronic components.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ANTONIO UENO, congressman _ The 65-year-old Ueno is one of three
congressmen of Japanese descent re-writing Brazil's constitution in
Brasilia, the national capital. Born in 1923 in the southern state
of Parana, he spent his childhood helping his parents pick coffee
and cotton on local plantations. But they insisted he go to school
and in 1953 he graduated college with a degree in economics. He
entered politics as a councilman in the small town of Assai in
Parana. In 1965 he got a law degree and two years later was elected
to the Chamber of Deputies of Brasil's Congress. He has been a
congressman ever since. He presented 134 bills for the new
constitution and 34 of which have been approved, most favoring
foreign capital investments in Brazil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 21</NOTE>
