<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv18   08-15 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 18,0874</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 18, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for Aug. 18 in summary form.</NOTE>
<HEAD>In Complex Medical Cases, Ethics Comes To Forefront</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK RIDGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questions surrounding withholding and
cost of treatment, and even confidentiality, have hospitals turning
more frequently to special consultants and committees to help
search for the answers.
   The American Hospital Association estimates that at least 60
percent of U.S. hospitals with 200 or more beds have such
committees, made up of doctors, philosophers, theologians and
social workers. A report in last week's Journal of the American
Medical Association said 30 percent of 280 patients in a Virginia
study presented ethical problems.
   Some hospitals, like Lutheran General Hospital, have doctors
like John La Puma as consultants. La Puma does at least two
consultations a week.
   An ethics consultant helps clarify issues and ``provides a lot
of comfort for myself as a primary care physician,'' said Dr.
Stuart Goldman, director of research and family practice at
Lutheran General.
   In addition to medicine's capacity to prolong life, ``in a
society where lawsuits are common, lawsuits are less likely when an
ethics committee has been consulted,'' said Dr. David Larson,
director of Loma Linda University's Center for Christian Bioethics
in California. ``It's harder to demonstrate that a doctor has acted
unprofessionally.''
   The fact that not all ethics consultants are doctors raises
other issues.
   Among them, said Arthur L. Caplan, director of the Center for
Biomedical Ethics at the University of Minnesota, are ``Who should
be entitled to do this and what qualifications and training should
they have? What are the proper duties to give to someone who is an
ethics consultant _ teaching, troubleshooting, or policy-making?
What is the job?''
   Another unresolved issue is consultants' legal responsibility,
said Caplan. ``I think, down the road, the courts are going to have
to clarify their role.''
   Medical guidelines will ease debate over withholding treatment,
said La Puma. ``The big ethical issue of the 1990s is going to be
medical indigents, and what kind of care we provide for patients
who cannot provide for themselves.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Cornell Ornithology Center Is Nest Of Information For Birders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some professional birdwatchers look down
on amateurs, but the legacy of America's first ornithology
professor unites their work.
   Cornell University's Laboratory of Ornithology, which owes its
creation to Arthur A. Allen, contains millions of pages of behavior
studies and photographs and the world's largest collection of
birdsongs _ more than 5,000 species.
   Equally important, it links ornithologists and amateur
birdwatchers. ``The game is to position the laboratory between the
professional community and the birding community, the amateur and
the professional,'' said executive director Charles Walcott. ``We
are an information broker between the two.''
   Allen, an expert on red-winged blackbirds and pioneer in
recording and filming wild birds, headed North America's only
doctoral program in ornithology from the 1920s to the '40s. Lyman
K. Stuart, a business graduate and student of Allen's, financed
much of the lab and 180-acre sanctuary near Ithaca.
   The laboratory generates money through dues and project fees,
sale of publications and bird recordings, and home-study courses in
ornithology and bird photography.
   Its 1-year-old Project FeederWatch last year paid 4,000
birdwatchers to fill out a computerized form twice weekly recording
the species that appear at their backyard feeders. The goal this
year is 10,000.
   ``We can only begin to guess at what we might have been able to
accomplish if we had had this kind of information years ago,''
Walcott said, ``how many extinct species we could have saved.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Medical Sculptors Use Artistry To Heal Patients' Psyches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silicone, plaster and glue can go a long
way toward helping to heal wounded self-images.
   Hundreds of people each year who have lost an eye, ear, nose,
finger, toe, breast or other feature to birth defects, cancer,
accidents and fire _ and who can't be helped by plastic surgery _
seek assistance from prosthetic artists.
   Of some 200 patients treated at the University of Michigan
Medical Center's Medical Sculpture Unit a year, says director Denis
Lee, the breakdown is about 50 ears, 30 breasts, 20 noses, 20 eyes
and 50 ``miscellaneous.'' Most health insurance covers the cost,
$1,400 for an ear or nose and $2,000 for an eye.
   There are about 200 U.S. prosthetic sculptors, most of them
affiliated with the Michigan, a Veterans Administration clinic in
New York and a medical center at Baylor University, says Lee, who
also runs a program to train artists.
   The University of Illinois, Ohio State University, Johns Hopkins
University, the Medical College of Georgia and the University of
Texas also offer such courses. The course of study includes
anatomy, pathology, anatomical sketching, medical and scientific
drawing, and medical graphics. Graduates can set up their own
business, freelance, or work for a medical center.
   Sculptors take a plaster mold of the patient's undamaged
feature, then make a silicone rubber copy and carefully match skin
tone. The replacement is applied daily with a medical adhesive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
