<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose at a brisk annual rate
of 5.7 percent in July despite smaller increases for food, the
government said in a report that intensified already deepening
concerns about inflation.
   The Labor Department said Friday that its Producer Price Index,
which tracks prices for finished products one step before the
retail level, rose 0.5 percent last month, compared with a 0.4
percent increase in June.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories climbed for the 18th
consecutive month in June, the government said, prompting some
economists to warn that companies may be stockpiling goods in
anticipation of higher prices.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that inventories jumped 0.7
percent to a seasonally adjusted $733.9 billion in June, following
an identical 0.7 percent rise in May. Inventory levels have not
fallen since December 1986.
   Business sales surged 1.5 percent in June to $490.6 billion
following a 0.8 percent gain in May. It was the fifth month without
a decline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment firm owned by a Disney
family scion sweetened its takeover bid for Polaroid Corp., and the
camera company's board of directors met for six hours before
postponing action on the offer.
   Analysts interpreted Friday's new offer by Shamrock Holdings
Inc. as an effort to gradually raise the stakes for the instant
camera pioneer.
   Shamrock's new offer was $40 a share plus giving stockholders
the right to 40 percent of any settlement in Polaroid's $5.7
billion patent infringement case against Eastman Kodak Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell said he will
launch a $2.1 billion cash tender offer for Macmillan Inc. next
week, but made clear his main interest is acquiring its information
services business.
   Maxwell said Friday that his Maxwell Communications Corp. PLC
would be willing to pay ``not less than $1.1 billion'' in cash for
the information business.
   Macmillan already is the subject of a $1.9 billion bid from
Robert M. Bass Group Inc., a Texas-based investment group.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on new one-year,
adjustable-rate mortgages surged to the highest level in nine
months this week while fixed-rate mortgages jumped almost to the
high point for the year, according to a nationwide survey.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said Friday that the
one-year, adjustable-rate mortgages this week averaged 8.00
percent, up from 7.90 percent the week before.
   It was the highest since rates averaged 8.11 percent the week
ending Nov. 6.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The burgeoning insider-trading scandal
surrounding Business Week came home to haunt the magazine's own
editorial offices, after repeated assertions that its employees
were not involved.
   Business Week announced Friday that it fired its broadcast
editor for violating the magazine's written code of ethics and
possibly trading on advance knowledge of stocks mentioned in issues
before they were released to the public.
   S.G. ``Rudy'' Ruderman failed to disclose ``all the (stock)
trades he made and the full extent of his holdings'' in accordance
with the ethics code, a company spokeswoman said, reading from a
statement.
</TEXT>
