<HEAD>Dollar Moves Up, Gold Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in quiet European trading
this morning as the market waited for the release of the latest
U.S. trade figures to provide a fresh indication of the strength of
the U.S. economy.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was slightly below last
week's closing levels against the French franc and West German
mark, but was rising in general.
   They said the market was likely to trade in a narrow range until
the release of June U.S. trade figures on Tuesday.
   ``We are in a breather phase right now, which will last until
the markets have the force to start up again,'' said one dealer at
a U.S. bank in Frankfurt. ``But for that, we need the (trade)
data.''
   Italian financial markets were closed today for a holiday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8785 West German marks, down from 1.8805; 1.5758
Swiss francs, up from 1.5750; 6.3775 French francs, down from
6.3810; 2.1194 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1146; 1.2195 Canadian
dollars, unchanged.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 132.95 yen, down 0.10 yen from Friday's close.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 132.98 yen.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7135, weaker than
$1.7155 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at $431.40 a troy ounce and the city's
five major bullion dealers later fixed a recommended price of
$431.15. Both were down slightly from late Friday's bid of $431.50.
   In Zurich, gold was selling at a bid $430.125, down from
Friday's $432.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $433.80, up from
Saturday's finish of 430.68.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.71 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's 6.73.
</TEXT>
