<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ConsumerElectronics     08-15 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Electronics,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>65 Percent of American Households Now Have VCRs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Video cassette recorders, compact disc
players, camcorders and other consumer electronics products are
becoming standard fare in the American home, according to a Gallup
survey.
   These products are no longer just symbols of an affluent singles
lifestyle but are finding their way into the homes of families with
children, says the Electronic Industries Association's Consumer
Electronics Group, which commissioned the study.
   ``People always think of these as yuppie products, and they're
not,'' said Cynthia Saraniti, a spokeswoman for the electronics
group.
   The VCR is the fastest growing product in the $41-billion-a-year
consumer electronics industry, she said. The number of households
with a VCR has been climbing at 10 percent to 12 percent a year and
sales are expected to top 13 million this year, she said.
   The survey of 1,008 adults found that 65 percent of the
households polled had a VCR. By household composition, VCR
ownership was 40 percent among single adults, 63 percent among
households of two or more adults, and 78 percent among couples with
children.
   The survey was conducted by telephone last spring by the Gallup
Organization. The results have a sampling error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
   The next most popular product was a pair of speakers for audio
playback, an item claimed by 40 percent of the households overall.
Some 26 percent said they had an electronic typewriter, 24 percent
said they had a telephone answering machine, 18 percent had a
personal computer, 14 percent had a compact disc player and 8
percent had a camcorder, according to the survey.
   In all of the product categories, the ownership percentages for
couples with children were higher than for single adults: 47
percent compared with 25 percent for audio speakers; 32 percent
compared with 14 percent for electronic typewriters, 24 percent
compared with 18 percent for telephone answering machines, 24
percent compared with 8 percent for personal computers, 15 percent
compared with 10 percent for compact disc players, and 13 percent
compared with 3 percent for camcorders.
   Though the prices of most consumer electronics products have
dropped since they were first introduced, income is still a
determining factor in purchases _ the higher a household's income,
the more likely it is to have one of these products.
   In households with income over $60,000 a year, 88 percent said
they had a VCR, compared with 49 percent of households earning
under $20,000, the survey found. The disparity was more apparent
with personal computers, which were in 46 percent of the
higher-income households compared with 10 percent of the
lower-income homes, and camcorders, 25 percent compared with 3
percent.
   Portable stereo units known as ``boom boxes'' were the most
popular audio equipment, owned by 48 percent of those surveyed.
Smaller radio-tape players with headphones were owned by 40 percent.
   Nearly every household _ 99 percent _ had a television set,
according to the survey, and predictably the more people in the
household, the more TV sets there are likely to be.
   About half of the single adults said they had one set, about a
third had two sets and 14 percent reported three or more. In
households with children, 43 percent had three or more TV sets, 31
percent had two and 26 percent had just one.
</TEXT>
