<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Australia-NewZealand     08-15 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-New Zealand,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia and New Zealand Moving Closer To Full Economic Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia and New Zealand will move
closer to full economic union Friday with the signing of an
agreement designed to end all trade barriers within five years.
   Prime Minister David Lange of New Zealand, who arrived in
Australia for a weeklong visit today, also has suggested the
integration of the two nations' naval forces. ``Strategic logic
points us in the direction of a combined ... fleet,'' he was quoted
as saying Sunday in New Zealand.
   But he was quoted as saying political union between the two
Pacific neighbors was unlikely.
   Lange and Prime Minister Bob Hawke of Australia will sign the
Closer Economic Relations agreement in Canberra on Friday.
   The new agreement will end all trade barriers and unify business
law and customs procedures by 1993. It also calls for greater
controls on illegal immigration and drug trafficking.
   Since the first Closer Economic Relations agreement in 1983
relaxed tariff barriers, trade between the two countries has
doubled.
   New Zealand is Australia's third largest market with exports
valued at $1.68 billion. Australia is New Zealand's second largest
market with exports of $1.2 billion.
   Lange has said the new Australian-New Zealand market would not
be as restrictive a trading bloc as the European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
