<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Obit-Ferrari 1stLd-Writethru   08-15 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Ferrari, 1st Ld-Writethru,0582</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT price of cars, CLARIFY family
relations, report burial, tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MODENA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enzo Ferrari, Italy's greatest sports car
builder and racing pioneer, died at his home in Modena, his auto
company announced today. He was 90.
   In a statement, the company said, ``Enzo Ferrari serenely ended
his earthly life Sunday, Aug. 14.'' No cause of death was given,
but Ferrari was known to suffer from a kidney disease.
   At Ferrari's side when he died were his son Piero and Piero's
wife, Floriana, the statement said. Piero's mother, Lina, who was
not Ferrari's wife, was also at the deathbed. His wife had died in
1978.
   At Ferrari's request, the announcement of his death was made
after the private funeral rites and burial today in San Cataldo,
near this northern city, according to the ANSA news agency.
   The founder and chairman of the company that bears his name and
makes luxury sports cars and Formula One racers once dreamed of
becoming an opera star or a sportswriter.
   But his first love was automobiles, and his drivers whipped the
prancing black horse that decorates his bright red racing cars to
victory on every major track in the world.
   ``It's true that I have never met any man whom I thought
altogether resembled me _ but only because my faults are so
enormous,'' he wrote in his autobiography.
   ``I have yet to meet anyone quite so stubborn as myself and
animated by this overpowering passion that leaves me no time for
thought or anything else. I have in fact no interest in life
outside racing cars,'' he wrote. ``I have never gone on a real
trip, never taken a holiday. The best holiday for me is spent in my
workshops when nearly everybody else is on vacation.''
   His factory, in the town of Maranello, near Modena, turns out
about 1,300 cars a year. Hundreds of customers, book the Ferrari
models years in advance and pay as much as $150,000, and more, for
the cars.
   Born in February 1898, Ferrari entered motor racing in 1919 and
drove with the Alfa Romeo team for 11 years. But he never became a
great driver because of a fatal flaw _ he could not bear to ruin an
engine to win a race.
   Ferrari founded his Maranello auto works in 1946, letting other
men win races in cars he produced.
   At the time, about 400 workers toiled painstakingly on the
silvery engines. Some crankshafts were sculpted by hand out of
steel, each requiring more than 80 hours of work.
   His drivers drove the racers to more than 4,000 victories and
the Ferrari team picked up 13 world titles, including nine in the
Formula One category since 1952.
   Ferrari was forced to reduce his business activities in February
when he developed influenza.
   Last month, a company spokesman confirmed that Ferrari was being
treated at home for kidney troubles and ``for ailments typical of
his age.''
   Ferrari was an avowed agnostic who made no secret of his
aversion for the Vatican, which had criticized him for his stoic
attitude toward the deaths of his drivers in fiery accidents on the
track.
   However, in June, Pope John Paul II toured the company's plant,
took a spin in one of the sports cars and spoke by phone for five
minutes with the bed-ridden Ferrari.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
