<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-HarvardUnion     08-15 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Union,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearings Open on Harvard-Union Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Proceedings expected to begin by noon EDT; lead prospects
unlikely; also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Months after white collar workers at Harvard
University voted to unionize, a tense labor battle continues, with
the Ivy League school being accused of union-busting as its seeks
to throw out the vote.
   A National Labor Relations Board administrative law judge was
scheduled to open hearings today on Harvard's challenge of the May
17 vote that created a 3,300-member union. The hearings are
expected to take two weeks.
   Harvard alleges that organizers used illegal tactics, including
intimidation of opponents and electioneering at the polls, to win
the election by 44 votes, 1,530 to 1,486.
   The university wants the agency to invalidate the election.
   Officials at the Harvard Union of Clerical and Technical Workers
deny the charges. ``What's really going on here is we beat them,
and they know it, and everybody knows it,'' said Kristine A.
Rondeau, an organizer.
   ``Our union is now a permanent part of Harvard University, and
the only remaining question is, what's the future relationship
going to be _ peace or war? Harvard's got to decide,'' she said.
   Harvard administrator Anne Taylor, who coordinated the
university's response to the union, conceded that the school ``is
in a difficult position'' because ``it's a liberal institution''
and ``the administration of the university is not reflexively
anti-union and would not like to be thought of as reflexively
anti-union.''
   Joel Harmetz, an administrative law judge from Washington, D.C.,
who is conducting the hearings, is not likely to reach a decision
until mid-autumn, said Joseph L. Kane, supervisory examiner in the
NLRB's Boston office.
   The union drive, which began in 1975, was closely watched by
national labor leaders as a bellwether for organizing white-collar
workers.
   Taylor said administrators believe there is ``strong evidence''
that union organizers acted improperly during the election.
   She said the violations include ``the union's maintenance of
lists on which they checked off voters, their interrogation of
voters as to how they voted, the escorting of voters to the polls,
electioneering on the way to the polls and at the polls, and the
providing of things of value _ such as medical care and plane fares
_ to get union supporters to vote.''
   Rondeau said the union conducted a legitimate get-out-the-vote
operation, and nothing more.
   ``They're saying we were at the polls keeping lists, and we were
not,'' she said. ``They're saying we were intimidating people.
That's incredible, no matter how much you stretch it.''
</TEXT>
