<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-StolenTrees     08-15 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Stolen Trees,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peasants Raid Forest, Cut Down Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peasants in southern China have cut down and
stolen more than 10,000 trees from a state-run forest since the
beginning of the year, an official newspaper said.
   The Legal Daily said Monday that illegal logging has been
increasing at the Wugong Mountain forest in Jiangxi province
because forestry officials refuse to punish the peasants.
   The report said in the past peasants used to sneak up the
mountain and cut one or two trees down. Now, it said, ``they steal
dozens of trees and even hundreds of trees at a time.''
   The peasants use the wood to build houses and for fuel.
   On April 19, the paper said, 2,000 peasants from a nearby
village looted more than 200 cubic yards of trees. Five days later,
peasants again entered the forest and cut down trees. This time
forestry guards were injured, the paper said.
   The report said the Wugong Mountain forest has 49,444 acres of
trees and is one of the country's main producers of wood products.
   The Chinese press has said that illegal logging poses serious
problems for the environment and the development of agriculture.
Illegal logging quickens soil erosion and creates conditions where
small amounts of rain can cause major floods.
   Last year, 247,100 acres of forests in China were destroyed by
illegal logging and 91 million yuan, or about $24.5 million, in
trees were stolen, the China Daily reported in March.
   Monday's report said the problem could not be solved in Jiangxi
province because officials there are too lenient.
</TEXT>
