<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Peabody-Layoffs     08-15 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peabody-Layoffs,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peabody Coal lays off 128 workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRVIEW HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peabody Coal Co. has laid off
128 more employees from one of its operations in this St. Clair
County community, reducing the company's work force to only 32.
   Of the 128 workers laid off Friday, 50 were laid off
indefinitely, while the 78 others were offered new jobs or
transfers to other Peabody operations.
   The layoffs bring to 540 the number of local workers eliminated
in the past three years.
   Peabody Coal, a wholly owned subsidiary of Peabody Holding Co.,
operates 40 surface and underground mines in nine states.
   Another 85 administrative and clerical workers throughout the
company were also laid off.
   The latest layoffs occurred because of a reduced demand for
high-sulfur Illinois coal, said company spokesman Ron Greenfield.
Large users of coal have continued to switch to other forms of
energy such as nuclear energy or use lower-sulfur coal from western
or eastern states, he said.
   ``We have reduced the number of employees at the mine level over
the past several years in response to the highly competitive market
for coal,'' company president Howard W. Williams said Friday in a
statement.
   ``The layoffs bring our support staff more in line with the
current active mining employee levels within these operations,'' he
said.
   Further layoffs will depend on government regulation, Greenfield
said.
   High-sulfur coal contributes pollutants to the air that need to
be reduced in order to comply with federal clean air legislation,
he said.
   ``Further tightening of clean-air legislation will not help,''
Greenfield said.
   In October 1985, Peabody Holding Co. laid off 100 management
employees at what was then its St. Louis headquarters and 70 people
in its Illinois Division, which includes the Fairview Heights
office.
   The company's headquarters was moved in April 1986 to Henderson,
Ky.
   A total of 151 miners were laid off at two Belleville-area mines
in 1987.
   The company's Illinois Division office is responsible for seven
mines _ six in Illinois, with four in the Belleville area, and one
in Oklahoma.
   At the end of 1987, those mines employed 2,844 and produced 10.8
million tons of coal, Greenfield said. That was down from 4,890
employees and coal production of 16 million tons of coal from 15
mines three years ago.
</TEXT>
