<HEAD>Crop Future Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, but analysts said the market
remained shaky following Friday's volatile session.
   Soybeans for delivery in May opened up the 30-cents-a-bushel
daily limit, then retreated slightly.
   ``I wouldn't read anything into what's happened so far,'' Ted
Mao, a New York-based grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., said shortly after the opening. ``The market really needs
some time to sort itself out.''
   Crop futures finished lower on Friday despite an overwhelmingly
bullish crop report from the Agriculture Department.
   Weather forecasts called for mostly hot and dry weather in the
Corn Belt this week, but Mao said traders also were looking for
evidence of new export business and further drought damage to the
crops before bidding prices up decisively.
   In early trading, wheat was 4 cents to 5 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.84{ a bushel; corn was 2}
cents to 6\ cents higher with September at $2.90 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with September at $2.81{ a bushel;
soybeans were 4} cents to 26 cents higher with August at $8.68 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange ahead of this afternoon's USDA monthly
7-state cattle-on-feed report.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August
at 69.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .15
cent higher with August at 81.10 cents a pound; hogs were .32 cent
lower to .50 cent higher with August at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .35 cent higher with August at
34.05 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Friday while pork futures
finished mostly lower.
