<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewspaperFeud     08-15 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspaper Feud,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Publishers To Pay Legal Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INEZ, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-publishers of the Martin County Mercury
have been ordered to pay the court costs incurred by their rival
legal newspaper in a dispute over circulation.
   Attorneys John W. Kirk, of Lexington, and Leonard Stayton, of
Inez, have been ordered to pay legal expenses exceeding $11,000 for
Homer Marcum, publisher of the Martin Countian.
   Circuit Judge Nick Frazier of Paintsville also ruled that they
must pay Marcum's costs if they appeal the order.
   Frazier said they must pay the legal bills because they
continued to press the circulation case after it was settled in
March, 1987. Kirk and Stayton are the Mercury's co-publishers.
   ``The continued litigation as set forth can only lead this court
to believe that counsel for the Mercury caused the Martin Countian
to incur additional legal expenses for no valid reason other than
to harass the plaintiff,'' Frazier said Friday in his 39-page
decision. The decision was the result of a hearing held last
December.
   The case began in February, 1987, when Martin Fiscal Court voted
to designate the Mercury as the county's legal newspaper based on
figures presented by that newspaper. The move took the county's
legal business away from Marcum's feisty Martin Countian.
   Marcum called Kirk's circulation figures ``bogus'' and sued the
next day. In his ruling, Frazier said that the Mercury's press run
of 2,800 included hundreds of papers given away free in Kirk's law
offices in Prestonsburg and Hindman.
   The Martin Countian's circulation is about 4,350, Marcum said.
   On March 13, 1987, fiscal court voted 5-0 to reinstate the
Martin Countian as the legal newspaper.
   Frazier ruled that even though the circulation dispute was
settled when the magistrates reversed their decision, Kirk and
Stayton continued to press the case, forcing Marcum to incur
additional legal costs for depositions and responding to motions.
   Frazier invoked a civil judicial procedure rule requiring
attorneys who file so-called frivolous lawsuits or motions to pay
for defendants' legal expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
