<DOCNO> AP880815-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Britain-Economy Adv20-21   08-15 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Economy, Adv 20-21,0789</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Cured Economy is Suffering Something of a Relapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Britain-Unemployment</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a few months ago, Britain's economic
``disease'' of rampant inflation, sky-high interest rates and
persistent unemployment was pronounced cured y just about everyone
except the Conservative government's staunchest critics.
   Today, the economy is suffering something of a relapse,
exhibiting that old familiar symptom, higher inflation, and the
government admits it is troubling.
   In addition, a hike in interest rates and a sharp widening of
the trade deficit are worrying economists.
   Ironically, the symptoms' cause is the economy's vigorous
growth, which is stretching resources and driving up prices. Like
its trading ally, the United States, Britain faces the threat that
its economy could overheat into recession.
   The peak came in March when the Treasury's top official,
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, announced the first
surplus budget in nearly 20 years and slashed the top income tax
rate to 40 percent from 60 percent.
   Since then, the attention has turned instead to Britain's annual
inflation rate, which, fed by strong consumer spending, has jumped
from 3.5 percent to 4.6 percent in June. In his budget speech,
Lawson had forecast an inflation rate of 4 percent by the end of
the year.
   To combat higher inflation _ Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
No. 1 economic priority _ the government has pushed interest rates
up more than 3 percentage points since early June.
   ``Whatever action is necessary to keep inflation under control,
this government will take,'' Lawson told members of Parliament in
late July, characterizing the pickup as ``modest but unacceptable.''
   Strength in the dollar gave the government room to raise
interest rates without pushing the British pound dangerously high.
But the pound, which has been trading at about 3.20 West German
marks, remains well above a rate of 3 marks which the government
long had protected.
   The pound broke through that ceiling in March, raising concerns
that Britain's export competitiveness might be hurt. Indeed, the
trade deficit is much worse than Lawson had forecast.
   For the first six months of 1988, Britain had a current account
deficit of 5.6 billion pounds ($9.6 billion), compared with a 1.6
billion pound ($2.6 billion) deficit in all of 1987. The current
account includes ``invisible'' trade such as services and overseas
investment earnings.
   In his budget speech, Lawson had forecast a trade deficit of 4
billion pounds ($7 billion) for all of 1988.
   ``Things have deteriorated,'' said Ian Harwood, an economist at
the London investment firm Warburg Securities. ``The major part of
the reason for the deterioration has been the way the economy has
been growing so much faster than expected.''
   David Owen, an economist with the London investment firm
Kleinwort Grieveson Ltd., said ``domestic demand is just growing
too quickly for its own good.''
   The latest survey conducted by the polling organization Market
and Opinion Research International, showed that in July, for the
first time since February 1987, more people thought the state of
the economy would get worse rather than better over the next year.
   Economists expect Britain's gross domestic product _ its total
output of goods and services _ to grow between 3.5 percent and 4
percent this year, faster than the 3 percent forecast by Lawson in
March, and following growth of 4.4 percent in 1987.
   On top of the troubling symptoms, there have been recurrent
reports of a rift between Mrs. Thatcher and Lawson over currency
exchange policy.
   These have been fueled by the pound's rise and the government's
negotiations with Mrs. Thatcher's former economic adviser, Sir Alan
Walters, for him to return to her Downing Street office next year.
   Mrs. Thatcher advocates free-market policies while Lawson favors
managing exchange rates through direct intervention in the markets
and the adjustment of interest rates.
   However, Lawson survived a Cabinet reshuffle by Mrs. Thatcher in
late July and now appears likely to remain until at least after
next spring's budget.
   But the economic outlook remains worrying, Harwood said.
   Inflation will peak at 6 percent early next year, interest rates
might move higher into the double digits, and the trade deficit
probably will balloon to 10 billion pounds ($17.2 billion) in 1988,
Harwood predicted.
   The government remains upbeat.
   ``The difficulties that beset us are difficulties we have
successfully dealt with in the past, and will do so again, without
drama, and without interrupting the steady progress we have already
achieved,'' Lawson said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Britain-Unemployment Adv20-21   08-15 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Unemployment, Adv 20-21,0656</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rate Has Fallen For Two Years, But Critics Claim It Is Massaged</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to a strong economy, Britain's persistently
high unemployment rate has fallen sharply, but critics claim the
government is massaging the figures to make them ook even better
than they are.
   Opponents of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government agree
that unemployment is down, but say exaggeration in the degree of
improvement is encouraging apathy toward the unemployed.
   The jobless rate has been falling for two years, reaching 8.4
percent in June, its lowest point in nearly seven years, the
Department of Employment says.
   Unemployment has fallen to 2.38 million people from a peak of
11.5 percent, or about 3.31 million in June 1986.
   The decline is the fastest among major Western industrialized
nations, the government says.
   But the Unemployment Unit, a private research and lobby
organization, says the rate would be 10.6 percent, representing
3.03 million people, if the calculation method were the same as
when the Conservatives first came into power in 1979.
   The British figures compare with a West German rate of 8.9
percent in June, which is unchanged from two years earlier, and a
French rate of 10.9 percent in May, which is up from 10.7 percent
two years before.
   An Employment Department spokesman, who requested anonymity,
said: ``We're still reasonably confident that it (ours) is an
accurate measure of unemployment.''
   Lawmaker Michael Meacher, the opposition Labor Party's spokesman
on unemployment, said: ``Unemployment has indeed been going down
over the last two years, but only about half as fast as the
government has been claiming.''
   Peter Kellner, a columnist for the Independent newspaper, wrote:
``If ... the calculations were done differently, it is doubtful
whether the government could claim, or would receive, anything like
the credit that the media and the public now bestow upon it.''
   Paul Convery, a director of the Unemployment Unit, said Britons
have become ``a little bit anesthetized,'' partly because they
generally are feeling better off economically, and partly because
the government has scored ``several sizable propaganda victories.''
   National unemployment registers have been the source for
unemployment statistics in all Common Market countries except
Spain, Portugal and Greece, the Unemployment Unit said.
   In 1982, Britain alone began basing its unemployment rate on the
number claiming unemployment benefits, rather than the number
registered as unemployed, it said.
   Since 1979, the government has made 22 changes in the way it
measures joblessness, all except one of which have reduced the
official unemployment rate, the Unemployment Unit said.
   The government denies that it has made that many changes or that
its alterations are designed to make the numbers look better.
   In a recent monthly unemployment report, the government said it
began counting as employed those people who are in government
training programs. That reduced the unemployment rate by 0.1
percent.
   The unit said the government has removed from the unemployment
benefit lists jobless men over age 60 who receive other kinds of
benefits.
   Part-time workers, whose numbers are increasing, have always
been counted as employed, and many jobless married women aren't
eligible for unemployment benefits, it said.
   Another way of measuring unemployment is to conduct surveys
which ask adults questions about their employment status. This
method is used monthly in the United States.
   In Britain, the government uses the method once a year, and
reveals the results a year later. By the survey method, Britain had
an unemployment rate of 10.7 percent in the spring of 1987. By the
government's regular method, the rate was 10.8 percent.
   ``They are so close that it shows that our own measure is
accurate,'' the department spokesman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
