<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0441</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices dropped this morning in slow
trading, weakened by growing pressure for higher interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, still wobbly from a big
loss last week, fell 17.43 points to 2,020.09 as of noon EDT on
Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 1.05 to 147.48. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index dropped 1.26 to
295.22.
   Losing NYSE issues outnumbered gains by nearly 3-to-1, with 919
down, 338 up and 496 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled
56.3 million shares in the morning session, about half the 106.24
million traded Friday morning.
   Besides moves last week by the Federal Reserve and banks to
raise interest rates, Wall Street brokers said a number of
inflationary developments were pointing to still tighter credit
conditions worldwide and depressing stocks.
   Among them were a stronger-than expected-figure on U.S.
industrial production reported by the Commerce Department today.
The 0.8 percent July gain was double the June figure. In Britain,
meanwhile, stronger-than-expected retail sales contributed to a
selloff in the stock market there.
   ``The liquidation process is going on because of pressure on
short-term interest rates,'' said William King, head trader for
Nikko Securities Co. International in New York. ``You can't fight
that.''
   In addition, nervousness about the impact of the June trade
deficit figures to be released Tuesday played a role in the market
today, traders said. The consensus is for a shortfall little
changed from the $10.9 billion figure in May, but a
larger-than-expected number could provide a further excuse to sell.
   Newton D. Zinder, technical analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. said in a daily commentary that ``the market is clearly on the
defensive. A reflex rally could occur soon but a new sustainable
advance is still some time away.''
   Dividend-capture strategies dominated the NYSE's most-active
list and inflated the actual volume of business. GTE fell \ to 40{,
with more than 7.6 million shares traded. Washington Water Power
rose [ to 26~ on volume exceeding 1.6 million shares.
   Takeover-related activity boosted the value of some stocks. U.S.
Shoe jumped 5\ to 23~ on reports the company was evaluating ways to
maximize shareholder value, including a possible sale or a
restructuring.
   Interco rose 2] to 72] after an investor group announced a
$70-a-share tender offer for the company. Polaroid rose { to 42|
after the Wall Street Journal reported the possibility of a hostile
tender offer by suitor Shamrock Holdings.
