<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0015 08-15 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Sharply Lower On Inflationary Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished sharply lower Monday amid
growing fears that the British economy was overheating.
   The release of two British economic reports, which showed the
British economy growing at a greater-than-expected pace, caused
many investors to dump stock and flee to the sidelines.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed off
26.6 points, or 1.4 percent, at 1,816.8, slightly above its worst
level for the day of 1,816.6.
   Volume was a relatively light 346 million shares, compared with
Friday's 495 million shares.
   Also depressing British stock, dealers said, were sliding prices
on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average was off
around 19 points at the 2,019 level as London trading drew to a
close.
   The British government reported Monday that retail sales rose 2
percent in July and that industrial production fell 0.9 percent in
June.
   The figures sparked concern that a continuing boom in consumer
demand coupled with capacity constraints in industry could further
fuel inflationary pressures in the British economy, dealers said.
   That raised fears that British commercial banks' base lending
rate, which has been increased seven times, to 11 percent from 7.5
percent in early June, would be pushed up even higher.
</TEXT>
