<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OverseasInflation     08-15 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Overseas Inflation,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Report Says Inflation Up Last Spring in US, Industrial
Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation, as measured by consumer prices,
rose last spring in the United States and its main trading
partners, according to a Central Intelligence Agency report made
available Monday.
   The CIA's Directorate of Intelligence found that while U.S.
inflation fell from 3.7 percent in 1987 to an annualized rate of
3.4 percent in the first quarter, it rose in the March-June period
to 4.8 percent.
   Canada's inflation rate fell from a 4.4 percent rate last year
to 3.2 percent in the first quarter, but also picked up in the
second quarter, to 5 percent, the report said.
   Britain had a 4.1 percent inflation rate in 1987. The level
dropped to 2.4 percent in the first quarter and rose to 6.1 percent
in the second quarter, the report said.
   Among other major industrialized nations tracked in the CIA
report, Japan's first-quarter inflation rate fell by 2.1 percent
from a 0.1 percent rate in 1987 but rose to 2.8 percent in the
second quarter.
   West Germany's 1987 inflation of 0.3 percent doubled to 0.6
percent in the first quarter and rose to 1.9 percent in the spring.
   The rise was less marked in France and Italy, countries more
usually inclined to inflation. The French rate of 2.8 percent in
the second quarter of 1988 was an increase over the winter rate of
2.3 percent, but still below the 3.3 percent of 1987.
   In Italy, the rate was 4.6 percent in 1987, after falling
steadily since the 14.9 percent level of 1983. It was down to 3.1
percent in the first quarter of this year but then rose again to
4.5 percent in the second three months.
   The CIA's twice-monthly ``Economic and Energy Indicators'' for
July 29 did not provide figures for smaller countries.
   The International Monetary Fund, which does, says inflation on
the consumer level among 21 industrial countries rose to an
annualized rate of 3 percent in May from 2.9 percent of 1987.
   The IMF said the average inflation level for 116 other
countries, mostly in the Third World, was 39.8 percent in 1987. It
increased to a rate of 55.7 percent in January, however few figures
for later months were available.
   Financial authorities have been especially worried about Brazil,
with the biggest economy in Latin America and the biggest debt in
the Third World. The IMF reported Brazilian inflation at more than
229 percent last year and rising at an annual rate of just under
500 percent in April.
   Argentina's rate was 131 percent in 1987, having risen steadily
throughout the year, according to the IMF. It has been reported
rising since, but the fund had no 1988 figures for Argentina in its
statistics for August.
   South Korea, on the other hand, has been keeping its rate below
3 percent in recent years, although it reached that level in 1987
and reported an annual rate of 7.4 percent this June, the IMF said.
   Bolivia, where the inflation rate hit a high of 11,750 percent
in 1985, was down to 15 percent last year and has been reporting
between 8 percent and 9 percent in 1988, the IMF said.
   The current inflation front-runner among the IMF's members is
Nicaragua, with an annual rate of more than 3,766 percent in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
