<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-15 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0189</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fear of rising interest rates bedeviled the
stock market again today and depressed the Dow Jones industrial
average to the lowest closing level in nearly three months.
   Trading was extremely light, which brokers called a reflection
of slack summer business, the extrordinarily hot weather and
skepticism about the market's prospects in the aftermath of the
sharp losses last week.
   ``The sellers are just getting plain tired. They're just getting
worn out,'' said Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter
trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``There's no
bids.''
   Stronger-than-expected industrial production figures released by
the Commerce Department set the mood for the market's weakness by
raising anxiety that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates
further to slow economic growth.
   Last week the Fed's hike in the discount rate from 6 percent to
6.5 percent rattled the stock and bond markets and contributed to a
81.61-point weekly drop in the Dow average, the biggest weekly
decline since early spring.
</TEXT>
