<DOCNO> AP880815-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OPEC     08-15 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Head Sees 1 Million Barrel Per Day Cut After Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC General Secretary Subroto said
Monday the Persian Gulf cease-fire should lower OPEC production by
around 1 million barrels a day, enabling the organization to solve
its overproduction problem without drastic output cuts.
   Oil traders reacted skeptically to the statement and oil prices
were little changed. The September contract for West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 9 cents
to $15.61 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Subroto, who is touring Latin American oil producers, said he
will go to Iran and Iraq following the scheduled Aug. 20 cease-fire
to try to convince the former enemies to accept equal production
quotas as they end their eight-year war.
   He said said the organization could opt for a new lower
benchmark price ``of, say, $17'' in its November regular meeting as
an alternative to cutting production.
   He added that the organization's price committee would meet
sometime after the last week in August but before the Nov. 21 OPEC
ministerial conference.
   ``The outcome of the cease-fire is anyone's guess, but my
opinion is that (Iran and Iraq) will be rational and what they will
rationally want is higher prices to build their economies,''
Subroto told a press conference.
   ``By bringing Iraq's production to equal that of Iran, this will
reduce OPEC production without reducing the temporary quota of
anyone (else). ... With that policy, we will be able to strengthen
prices without a lower production level,'' he said.
   ``I will try my best to convince Iran to accept parity,'' said
Subroto, who is the Indonesian oil minister. Iran's quota is
2,369,000 barrels per day.
   He said a parity agreement would ``at least'' reduce Iraq's
production by 600,000 to 700,000 barrels per day, while an end to
oil loans to Iraq by its allies Saudi Arabia and Kuwait could
result in a total cutback of 1 million barrels.
   He said he would visit both nations in the last week of August
and would report the results of his talks to the OPEC price
committee, which would then meet prior to the organization's
November regular conference.
   He said OPEC might decide in November for ``a higher production
level but at a lower price of, say, $17'' per barrel.
   ``What strategy we take depends on the (regular) conference,''
he said. OPEC's current target price is $18 per barrel, although
actual market prices are $14 to $15 a barrel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
