<DOCNO> AP880815-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Boesky-Drexel     08-15 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boesky-Drexel,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Employees Owned Stake in Boesky Arbitrage Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 27 employees of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., including top dealmaker Michael Milken, owned a stake
in the arbitrage firm of Ivan F. Boesky beginning in 1984,
according to a published report Monday.
   The previously unknown financial tie raises questions of
potential conflicts of interest for Milken and Drexel, according to
lawyers and Wall Street executives interviewed by the Wall Street
Journal.
   From 1984 to 1986, when the Drexel employee group held a stake
in Boesky's operation, Boesky was Wall Street's most powerful
takeover speculator and traded in many stocks about which Drexel
had valuable inside information.
   A spokesman for Drexel said the Drexel employees were only
passive investors with no role in the operations Boesky's firm.
   The Journal said the tie was revealed in public documents filed
in Washington, D.C., and California; private offering documents;
and people familiar with the relationship.
   Boesky was sentenced to three years in prison last December on a
criminal charge stemming from the government's investigation into
wrongdoing on Wall Street. He previously agreed to pay a $100
million penalty to settle a civil complaint of insider trading and
was banished from the securities business.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission approved civil charges of
securities-law violations against Drexel, Milken and three other
Drexel employees, but so far the charges have not been filed.
   The charges are based largely on allegations of illegal dealings
between Boesky and Drexel, the Journal said, citing people familiar
with the investigation.
   The Journal said people close to Drexel say the Drexel
employees, through a general partnership known as Camro Associates,
invested $1 million in the Boesky firm, Seemala Corp., in 1984, and
received $3 million for their stake in 1986.
   Camro was made up largely of employees of Drexel's junk bond
operations in Beverly Hills, Calif., the Journal said.
   A Drexel spokesman, Steven Anreder, told the Journal, ``The
investment was made over four years ago with the full knowledge and
consent of'' Drexel. ``It was fully disclosed and the amount
involved was only 1 percent of the equity (of Seemala) based on
book value.''
   Anreder described the investment as ``strictly passive,''
meaning the Drexel investors were not involved in the business of
Seemala. He said Monday that Fried Frank Harris Shriver & Jacobson,
a law firm working for Seemala, proposed the investment for tax
reasons.
   Leon Silverman, a lawyer for Boesky, declined comment Monday.
   After the Drexel employee group sold its stake in Boesky's
arbitrage firm in 1986, Drexel took its own stake in Boesky's
successor firm. Drexel sold $660 million in notes as part of
Boesky's effort to raise $1 billion in debt and equity for his new
firm, received $24 million in investment banking fees, and invested
$5 million in the new firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 1915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     08-15 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 3.6 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 1.822 million tons in
the week ended Aug. 13, a decrease of 3.6 percent from the previous
week's 1.890 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 85.4 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 88.6 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
62.259 million net tons, a decrease of 19.6 percent from the 52.044
million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 90.0 percent of capacity,
compared with 75.3 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended Aug. 13: Northeast
Coast, 270,000; Pittsburgh, 171,000; Youngstown, 87,000; Lake Erie,
155,000; Detroit, 152,000; Chicago, 503,000; Midwest, 179,000;
Southern, 211,000; and Western, 94,000.
</TEXT>
