<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Unilever 1stLd-Writethru   08-15 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Unilever, 1st Ld-Writethru,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Households Products Group Posts 11 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS thruout to reflect use of constant exchange rates;
CORRECTS earnings percentage increases and totals.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch household products
group, said Monday its second-quarter net profit jumped 12 percent,
with most lines of business contributing to the improvement.
   Unilever, whose brands include Lever, Lipton, and
Chesebrough-Pond's, said net profit in the three months ended June
30 rose to $410 million from $367 million in the same period a year
earlier.
   Sales gained 5 percent to $8.25 billion from $7.84 billion in
the year-earlier period.
   Those results are based on translating results into dollars for
both periods at the rates of exchange that applied at the end of
1987: one British pound equal to 3.33 Dutch guilders equal to $1.87.
   ``The second quarter showed a stronger improvement over 1987
than that achieved in the first quarter,'' said Michael Angus,
chairman of the company's British arm, Unilever PLC. ``Most parts
of the business contributed to this result.''
   ``The outlook for the year as a whole is encouraging,'' the
chairman added.
   For the first six months of the year, net profit rose 9 percent
to $760 million from $696 million in the first half of last year.
   Sales increased 4 percent to $15.9 billion from $15.4 billion a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
