<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-15 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Soar On Hot, Dry Weather Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures posted their strongest gains in a week
Monday in response to predictions that crops in the drought-weary
Corn Belt would bake in triple-digit heat for most of this week.
   On other markets, most livestock and meat futures rose; precious
metals advanced; energy futures were higher; and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Monday's midday weather forecasts, coming on the heels of a hot,
mostly dry weekend in the Midwest, stoked fears of further damage
to the crops and helped push most corn, oat and soybean contracts
up their permitted daily limits on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Meteorologists said the same weather pattern that had made the
spring and early summer unseasonally warm and dry was
reestablishing itself and intensifying, promising at least several
more days of searing heat in the Midwest.
   ``We're going to have extreme heat right into Thursday, 100 to
110 degrees in the Corn Belt,'' said Charles Notis, a private
forecaster based in Des Moines, Iowa.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a
six-to-10-day outlook predicting above-normal temperatures but
normal to above-normal rainfall for the Farm Belt during the first
five days of next week.
   Analysts said the soybean crop was nearing the end of its
vulnerable flowering and pod-setting stage, a four-to-six-week
period during which weather plays a crucial role in determining
yields.
   The hot weekend weather probably caused some deterioration of
the soybean crop, analysts said. And the forecasts for similar
weather this week likely means yields will fall further, making
contracts for future deliveries of soybeans more precious, Karlin
said.
   Corn and oat futures soared their 10-cents-a-bushel daily limit.
Soybeans were limited to moves of 30 cents a bushel, expect for the
limitless August contract, which finished with a gain of more than
38 cents.
   Wheat settled 9 cents to 14{ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.92 a bushel; corn was 7} cents to 10
cents higher with September at $2.97\ a bushel; oats were 7{ cents
to 10 cents higher with September at $2.87{ a bushel; soybeans were
27{ cents to 38{ cents higher with August at $8.87 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange ahead of the Agriculture Department's monthly
seven-state cattle-on-feed report.
   The government reported cattle marketings during July were 4
percent higher than the same month a year ago, which surprised most
analysts and prompted predictions of a sharply higher opening
Tuesday.
   The number of cattle on feed Aug. 1 in the seven largest
cattle-producing states was 2 percent larger than a year ago, while
2 percent fewer cattle were placed on feedlots in those states
during July.
   The high marketing number startled analysts, most of whom had
expected a decline. The number meant there had been fewer
drought-related sales of cattle to packing houses than analysts had
believed, said Chuck Levitt, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in Chicago.
   Live cattle closed .07 cent to .45 cent higher with August at
69.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to 1.15 cents
higher with August at 81.75 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to
.57 cent higher with August at 47.37 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .52 cent lower to .70 cent higher with August at 33.65
cents a pound.
   Precious metals futures posted modest gains on the Commodity
Exchange in New York in response to the inflationary implications
of higher prices for most other commodities, said Bernard Savaiko,
an analyst in New York with PaineWebber Inc.
   Gold settled $1.70 to $2 higher with August at $433 a troy
ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 4.6 cents higher with September at
$6.785 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange
in thin dealings in the absence of major fresh news to drive the
market.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 14 cents
higher with September at $15.61 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent
to .41 cent higher with September at 44.27 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .39 cent to .75 cent higher with September at 46.37
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures slumped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
amid fears of rising interest rates, analysts said.
   The contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 3.45 points lower at 259.10.
</TEXT>
