<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-15 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed Ahead of Trade Figures; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed Monday in mostly light
trading, as some dealers sold the currency in anticipation of
Tuesday's report on the U.S. trade deficit for June.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid price for gold of $432.35 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up
from $431 late Friday.
   The dollar started the trading day by falling in the Far East,
then recovering from its early lows to finish little changed in
Europe. The dollar retreated anew against several key currencies in
later New York trading.
   Analysts attributed that decline mainly to dollar sales by
traders balancing their dollar-heavy positions ahead of the latest
of the monthly trade reports, which tend to strongly influence the
U.S. currency's movements. A negative trade performance usually
sends the dollar lower, and vice versa.
   ``We had some slight lightening of long dollar positions,'' said
Robert Hatcher, a vice president of corporate trading at the New
York office of Barclays Bank PLC of Britain.
   Traders are reluctant to hold big dollar positions because of
the possibility of a surprise in the June figures. Many traders and
economists are expecting a shortfall of between $10 billion and $12
billion. The trade deficit was $10.9 billion in May.
   Dealers said the dollar was supported, on the other hand, by the
continuing impact of last week's unexpected hike to 6.5 percent in
the Federal Reserve's discount rate, the interest it charges on
loans to member U.S. financial institutions. Rising U.S. interest
rates make dollars more valuable.
   The dollar was scarcely affected by the news Monday that U.S.
industrial production shot up 0.8 percent in July, the biggest
increase in nine months, market watchers said.
   ``All the traders are waiting for the next direction in the
dollar'' from the trade figures, said David Godwin, a dealer for
Union Bank of Switzerland.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar traded at 132.95 Japanese yen, down 0.10 yen from
Friday's close. Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.15 yen. By
the end of New York trading, the dollar was at 133.32 yen, up
slightly from 133.28 yen late Friday.
   In London, it cost $1.7145 to buy one British pound, cheaper
than $1.7155 late Friday. Later, in New York, the pound remained
steady at $1.7145, more expensive than $1.7130 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8805 West German marks, down from 1.8833; 1.5790
Swiss francs, up from 1.5777; 6.3760 French francs, down from
6.3965; 1,394.75 Italian lire, down from 1,397.50; and 1.2270
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2111.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday: 1.8810
West German marks, up from 1.8805; 1.5780 Swiss francs, up from
1.5750; 6.3780 French francs, down from 6.3810; 2.1257 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1146; 1,398.00 Italian lire, up from 1,395.50;
and 1.2196 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2195.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $430.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's bid of $431.50. In Zurich, Switzerland,
gold fell to a bid $431.00 an ounce, compared with Friday's $432.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $433.80 an ounce, up from
Saturday's finish of $430.68.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
rose to $433 a troy ounce from $431.30 late Friday.
   Silver bullion prices dipped in London to a late bid price of
$6.72 a troy ounce from $6.73 late Friday.
   On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery rose to $6.757
a troy ounce from $6.712 late Friday.
</TEXT>
