<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EasternFares     08-15 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Fares,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Slashes Some Fares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines announced Monday that it was
slashing fares between Florida and 16 Northeastern cities to $69
for the post-Labor Day season.
   Houston-based Continental Airlines, Eastern's sister company
under the Texas Air Corp. umbrella, also has announced a special
$69 one-way fare between Florida and 10 cities in the Northeast.
   The Eastern tickets, which carry a number of restrictions, went
on sale Monday and will be sold through Aug. 26. The tickets apply
to travel beginning Sept. 11 through Dec. 15 at savings of as much
as 40 percent.
   Louis Markesano, an airline analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc., called the move a typical seasonal promotion. ``Other
airlines will have some kind of matching with similar
restrictions,'' he said.
   Paula Musto, a spokeswoman for Eastern, said she did not expect
the special fare to touch off a pricing war.
   ``That's not our intention,'' Musto said. ``We just want to put
a good fall promotion out there.''
   Eastern suffered a drop in passengers during its
highly-publicized inspection by the Federal Aviation
Administration, which found no important safety violations.
   The $69 fare is based on round-trip travel and applies Tuesdays
through Fridays on northbound flights and Sundays through
Wednesdays on southbound flights.
   The fare applies to travel to and from Florida cities such as
Miami, Fort Lauderdale, Orlando and Tampa as well as Baltimore,
Boston, Buffalo, Cleveland, Hartford, Newark, New York,
Philadelphia, Providence and Washington, among others.
</TEXT>
