<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-COMECON     08-15 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-COMECON,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Establishes Diplomatic Relations With Some COMECON Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community has
established formal diplomatic relations with some member nations of
its Soviet bloc counterpart, COMECON, a West German official said
Monday.
   The official, who asked not to be identified, said at least four
of the COMECON countries _ the Soviet Union, East Germany,
Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria _ had established formal ties with the
EEC and that announcements on others were expected.
   The other COMECON members are Hungary, Poland, Romania, Albania,
Mongolia, Cuba and Vietnam.
   East Germany's state-run ADN news agency quoted the country's
foreign ministry spokesman, Wolfgang Meyer, as saying the move
contributes to the creation of a ``common European house.''
   Soviet bloc officials have used that phrase in recent weeks in
calling for closer unity between Eastern and Western Europe.
   Two months ago COMECON, which stands for the Council for Mutual
Economic Assistance, and the EEC paved the way for establishing
formal ties by signing documents of mutual recognition.
   Talks between COMECON and the EEC on establishing official links
began in September 1986.
</TEXT>
