<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BeverlyEnterprises     08-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Beverly Enterprises,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Firm in Real Estate Deals Worth $155 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled Beverly Enterprises, the
nation's biggest nursing-home company, announced Monday it had
arranged real estate transactions to raise $155 million to cover an
anticipated debt.
   The company said it would mortgage 75 nursing homes to raise
$120 million in cash and raise an additional $35 million by selling
and then leasing back 27 additional facilities.
   Neither transaction will affect patients or staff at any of the
nursing homes or congregate living centers involved, the company
said.
   Beverly Enterprises, suffering under heavy debt and slow
reimbursements, said it would use the cash to repay $148 million
worth of liquid yield option notes due Sept. 30. The notes, similar
to zero-coupon bonds, are publicly traded.
   The company has arranged with a lender to take out mortgages on
75 nursing homes in 17 states that either are owned outright or
carry small mortgages, said Beverly Enterprises spokesman William
Wright. He refused to reveal the identity of the lender for the
pool of mortgages.
   The sale-leaseback deal calls for purchase of 26 nursing homes
and one congregate living center in seven states to Health Care
Property Investors Inc., a Los Angeles real estate investment trust.
   Health Care Property announced it had agreed to pay $62 million
for the facilities. The transaction includes assumption of $10
million in mortgages by Health Care Property and for Beverly
Enterprises to temporarily finance $10 million of the price.
   Beverly Enterprises, which said it expects to get approximately
$35 million cash out of the deal, immediately will sign long-term
leases on the facilities and continue operating them without
interruption, Wright said.
</TEXT>
