<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Cabot-GAF     08-15 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cabot-GAF,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Defense Keys on GAF's Legal Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a unique move aimed at fending off a
possible hostile takeover by GAF Corp., which has been indicted on
charges of stock manipulation, Cabot Corp. has adopted a defense
designed to repel attacks by companies facing government
investigation.
   Wayne-based GAF asked the Federal Trade Commission on Aug. 1 for
antitrust clearance to raise its 4.9 percent stake in Cabot, a
Waltham, Mass.-based energy and chemicals company, to as much as 25
percent.
   Cabot responded by amending its anti-takeover defense so it
would be triggered if at least 15 percent of a company's common
stock was held by a person targeted for government investigation or
action.
   Once the ``poison pill'' was triggered, Cabot stockholders could
buy more shares at half the market price, making a hostile takeover
prohibitively expensive.
   A federal grand jury in Manhattan indicted GAF and its
vice-chairman James T. Sherwin in July on charges they manipulated
the price of Union Carbide common stock after an unsuccessful
attempt to take over the larger company in 1986.
   GAF and Sherwin both pleaded innocent to the charges in the
indictment, which marked the first criminal charges against a U.S.
industrial enterprise stemming indirectly from revelations of Ivan
Boesky, the Wall Street felon at the center of the widespread
insider trading scandal.
   The indictment charged that GAF and Sherwin attempted to create
an artificial demand for Carbide stock after GAF's takeover attempt
failed, allegedly to allow GAF to sell its 10 percent stake at a
better profit or a minimal loss.
   Cabot's takeover defense, which was designed by the New York law
firm Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom, is considered possibly
the first attempt to capitalize on Wall Street's insider trading
scandal.
   The idea could signal a trend, as several other major takeover
players are under investigation in the scandal.
   It was not clear whether GAF actually intended to mount a
takeover bid for Cabot, however. Telephone calls to the company
seeking comment on Monday night were not answered.
   Cabot has been considered by some analysts as a candidate for
takeover or restructuring aimed at boosting its stock price. Cabot
shares rose $3 to $37 a share Monday on the New York Stock
Exchange. With some 27 million common shares outstanding, Cabot had
a market value of about $999 million based on Monday's closing
price.
   A GAF spokesman told the Wall Street Journal over the weekend
that ``we have no comment whatsoever with regard to Cabot's
mean-spirited response to our company's filing.''
   GAF first disclosed its stake in Cabot in 1986, according to a
company spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
