<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0262 08-15 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0262,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Lower, Dollar Higher In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE morning closing figures, adds
quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices dipped in morning trading Tuesday on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar inched up against
the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the exchange's
main index, declined 114.09 points to 27,787.20 by the close of
morning trading.
   The dollar, which opened at 133.20 yen, up from 132.95 yen at
Monday's close, was changing hands at 133.13 yen in late morning
trading.
   Securities dealers said the decline in the Tokyo stock market
primarily was due to a 33-point decline overnight in the Dow Jones
industrial average in New York.
   ``In very thin trading, share prices are lower across the
board,'' said a dealer at a major Tokyo securities firm. ``This is
because of unfavorable factors in New York and the U.S. trade
report scheduled to come out soon.''
   Dealers also said they expect no major market shifts until the
release of the U.S. trade report for June, scheduled for later
Tuesday in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
